{[%evp 0,17,19,38,18,26,21,2,3,-20,-29,-31,-56,-31,-42,-55,-35,-28,-33,-18]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 {Welcome, dear chess friends, to this new course: The Scotch Gambit for White. This was one of my childhood favorites, and the last time I played it—back in 2013—I won a crucial game that helped me become a FIDE Master. After that, I moved on to more serious preparation and switched to 1.d4. For over a decade, I’ve only looked at the Scotch Gambit from Black’s perspective. But that changed when GM Lucas Van Foreest proposed the idea of working together on a course dedicated to this opening. He’s been analyzing it in depth for years, especially while preparing elite players rated 2700 and above. He shared several of his ideas with me, and I was impressed. That’s when I knew it was time to return to the Scotch Gambit—not just as a memory, but as a weapon. Now, with fresh analysis, we’re excited to share this course with you—an aggressive and practical repertoire designed to surprise your opponents and avoid heavy theory.} Nf6 {[%csl Cf6] Black's mainline.} (4... Be7 {and other sidelines will also be covered.}) (4... Bb4+ {This is a move the engine likes, but it's rarely chosen by strong players—because even a small mistake can lead Black into a lost position. Moreover, the resulting positions, while often evaluated as "0.00" by the engine, are much easier and more enjoyable to play with White.}) (4... Bc5 {Black's second most important move. Here, we will offer you three different alternatives:} 5. O-O $5 {Very principled line.} (5. c3 Nf6 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 $5 {This is another interesting direction, and it will be extensively covered by Lucas in this course.}) (5. Ng5 $5 {It’s a great line when you’re looking for a practical game—risk-free for White, with plenty of chances to outplay your opponent right from the first moves.}) 5... d6 {This is considered Black's best, but here Lucas will show you an interesting new idea for White.} (5... Nf6 6. e5 {This leads to the very interesting Max Lange Variation. After analyzing it in depth, I can say it’s a lot of fun for White—and personally, I would never play it as Black, because even with engine support, it’s unclear where equality really lies.})) 5. e5 d5 {By far Black's mainline.} (5... Ng4 $5 {is another important line that we will need to discuss.}) (5... Ne4 {This move is very popular nowadays among strong players, and I really liked the ideas Lucas came up with to challenge it.}) 6. Bb5 Ne4 (6... Nd7 $5 {I have also played this move ones from the Black's side. This is a positional line where Black isn’t trying to equalize directly, but simply looking to get a playable game—and of course, we’re perfectly fine with that.}) 7. Nxd4 Bd7 {The old way.} (7... Bc5 {Modern way. Objectively, it’s a solid line—but Black is playing for a draw at best, with no real guarantee of achieving it.}) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O {[%cal Gf8e7,Cf8c5] and here Black has two important moves: 9...Bc5 and 9...Be7. Against both of them, Lucas will show you how to achieve interesting positions where you can fight for the initiative. The Scotch Gambit is a killer surprise weapon—fast, aggressive, and extremely practical. But it’s not just a one-time trick: players like GM Gawain Jones and GM Thomas Beerdsen use it consistently, even in many of their classical games. Unlike the Spanish or the Italian, which demand heavy theoretical knowledge just to reach a playable position, the Scotch Gambit is easy to learn and can deliver far better practical results—even against well-prepared opponents.} *

