{[%evp 0,15,24,8,8,28,14,25,24,-33,46,46,60,25,25,19,37,44]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gg8f6]} Nf6 (4... Be7 {The most sound option.} 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Main line.} O-O 7. O-O d6 {The position reminds a bit the Old Philidor, and we are able to use the same principles:} 8. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Od6,Oe4,Bf4] In this structure, f4 is the best square to develop the bishop.}) (4... Bb4+ {Black's best option according to the engine, but it's only the 4th move by popularity for a number of reasons: Black must be very precise and must have concrete knowledge of only moves, and also the arising positions are very tricky (one wrong move can cost Black the game).} 5. c3 dxc3 6. bxc3 {I used this move in my childhood.} Ba5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] The strongest move.} (6... Be7 $4 {Many opponents fell for this trap.} 7. Qd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Bd5,Rf7][%cal Gd5f7,Rg8h6,Gc1h6] And there is no defence against Qxf7.}) (6... Bc5 $2 {Also bad.} 7. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Rc5,Gf7][%cal Re8f7,Gd1d5] A typical tactical motif.} Kxf7 8. Qd5+ $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rf7e8,Gd5h5] White regains material, with a clear advantage.}) 7. O-O Bb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] The best way to play, although it has been played in only 33 games out of 263.} (7... d6 $6 {The most common move, it's not completely bad, but a bit risky.} 8. Qb3 Be6 {The best try.} (8... Qe7 9. e5 $1 $16 {[%csl Be5,Re7,Re8] White has a better position.}) 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gg5e6] We want to capture on e6 with the knight.} Bb6 {Only move.} 11. Nxe6 Qe7 12. Bg5 {White has a lot of ideas for the initiative.} (12. Nd2 $5 {Also deserves attention.}) 12... Qf7 13. Na3 $14 {[%csl Re8] It's unpleasant for Black to play with the king in the center.}) (7... Nge7 $2 {It would seem logical to finish development, but after:} 8. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] The position is terrible for Black, since f7 is too vulnerable.} Ne5 (8... O-O $2 9. Qh5 $18 {[%csl Rf7,Rh7] Game over.}) 9. Nxf7 $1 {White can use this typical tactic:} Nxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qh5+ $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rf7][%cal Gh5f7,Gh5a5] The point, White has a big advantage.}) 8. e5 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd7d6] An interesting try, to stop Black's development.} Nge7 9. Ba3 O-O 10. Re1 h6 {For the engine, this is fine for Black, but the engine evaluation doesn't mean much in these type of positions, White has full compensation for the pawn anyway and it's easier to play, for example:} 11. Bb3 $1 $44 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4] A good move, to support the Nbd2-Nc4 idea.}) (4... Bc5 5. Ng5 $5 {[%csl Gg5] This is a risk free alternative for White. The theory is quite concrete, so it can become unpleasant for Black, because he needs to remember a lot, just to equalize.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] Only move.} (5... Ne5 $2 {This is a mistake.} 6. Nxf7 $1 {[%csl Bf7] Typical tactic and White will reach a much better version compared to the main line:} Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ {[%csl Rc5,Rf7][%cal Gh5c5,Gh5f7] The point.} g6 9. Qxc5 $16 {[%csl Gc6,Rg8] Black has a knight on g8 compared to having a knight on c6.}) 6. Nxf7 {White uses the standard tactical resource:} Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ {[%csl Rc5,Rf7,Gh5][%cal Gh5c5,Gh5f7] This is the point.} g6 {Main move.} 9. Qxc5 {Up to this point, the variation is forced. Now Black can choose.} d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Black's most concrete and critical move, every strong player is using it.} (9... d6 {Most common move, not a bad one, but here the game continues and White keeps a certain pressure.} 10. Qc4+ Be6 {Critical.} 11. Qe2 Qf6 {The best, to fight against White's development.} 12. O-O Rhe8 $1 {[%cal Gf7g8] The best, with idea of Kg8.} (12... Kg7 13. b3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1b2] Once again, the bishop gets to the long diagonal.}) 13. Nd2 $146 {This is a new position, and it's the critical one of the 9...d6 line.}) (9... Qe7 $6 {This is similar to the 8...Kf8 endgame.} 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 (10... Kxe7 11. O-O $14 {[%csl Rg6] I don't believe that g6 is such an useful move for Black, since it weakens the dark squares after all.}) 11. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3] Typical move.} dxc3 12. Nxc3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge1g1] White is better in the endgame.}) 10. O-O {Necessary to finish development.} (10. Qxd5+ $2 {Common mistake!} Qxd5 11. exd5 Nb4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5] Black is just better.}) 10... dxe4 {[%csl Bd4,Be4][%cal Gh8e8] Black needs just one extra move, and he would have a fantastic position, that's why White should act fast.} 11. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] White must urgently dismantle Black's strong pawn center.} Qd6 $1 {This is universally known as Black's safest option.} (11... Be6 {was played in the game Grischuk-Karjakin, 2018.} 12. cxd4 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3] We can open the c3 square the knight.} Qxd4 13. Qg5 $1 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gg5h6] The queen can be annoying.} Qe5 14. Qh6 $36 {[%cal Gb1c3] +0.30 evaluation.}) (11... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Rc5g5] This is a logical move, to develop the bishop and stop White's future Qg5.} 12. cxd4 Qxd4 13. Qb5 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb5b7] We can get a tempo on the pawn.}) 12. Qxd6 cxd6 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nc3 {White is down a pawn but aims to recapture the pawn on e4, giving White a better pawn structure.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] The strongest move, and I also recommended it from the Black side. Black is threatening Ne2+, followed by an exchange of knights.} (14... Bf5 {Second most common move.} 15. Bh6 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1] Strong development.} Rad8 16. Rad1 $36) 15. Nxe4 Nc2 $1 16. Nxd6+ {The main try.} Ke6 17. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] We want to enter an endgame with opposite colored bishops.} Nxa1 {The most logical.} 18. Rxa1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ra8c8,Rc8c7,Rh8e8,Rh8g8,Rg8g7] Unlike the 16.f3 variation, here White has an extra pawn for the exchange and a more stable position. For now it's equal, but statistically, White wins 1 time out 4 this endgame.}) 5. e5 d5 (5... Ng4 $5 {This line is ocasionally used by strong players in blitz/rapid. Black aims to target the e5 pawn.} 6. O-O $1 {The correct answer.} (6. Qe2 $6 {is a common mistake.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Be7] Black's only move.} 7. Bf4 f6 $1 $15 {Black is slightly better. Lie-Carlsen, Arctic Chess Challenge 2007.}) 6... d6 {The main line.} (6... Be7 7. Bf4 $5 {I think this is the most challenging approach, and it is a lot of fun to play.} g5 $1 {The second most common move, Black wants to expand on the kingside.} (7... d6 $6 {Black's most common move, but in fact, this is what we are hoping for.} 8. exd6 cxd6 {was played by GM Bacrot.} (8... Bxd6 9. Re1+ $1 {Black has to lose a tempo to go back to e7.} Be7 10. c3 $36 {[%csl Gc3] White has a huge initiative.}) 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 $14 {White is better and later won in Socko-Bacrot, 1-0, Bundesliga 2016.}) (7... O-O $2 {Just bad.} 8. h3 $1 $16 {[%cal Rg4h6] Black has to go to h6, where White can either take or ignore the knight.}) 8. Bg3 $1 {[%csl Gg3] Necessary.} (8. Nxg5 $2 {would be a nice tactic, but it fails to:} d5 $3 $17 {[%csl Gg4,Rg5][%cal Gc8g4] Important intermezzo, and Black wins material.}) 8... h5 9. Bd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rd7d5] Key move, to stop d5.} Nb4 $1 {was played in the only game that reached this position: Pap-Pressman, San Sebastian op 2011.} (9... h4 $2 {falls into the trap.} 10. Nxh4 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Rg4][%cal Gd1g4,Rd7d5] We use the vulnerability of the g4 knight, especially since there is no ...d5 with tempo on the c4 bishop.} gxh4 11. Qxg4 $36 {[%cal Gg4g7] Qg7 is a big idea, White has a great initiative.} hxg3 $4 {Blunder.} 12. Bxf7+ $3 $18 {[%csl Re8,Gf1,Gf7][%cal Re8f7,Gf2g3] Mate is soon to follow.}) 10. c4 $3 $146 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] This is why I recommend to play 7.Bf4 instead of 7.Re1, the positions are very unbalanced and fun.} c6 11. a3 $1 $13 {Intermezzo.}) 7. exd6 Qxd6 {The best for the engine.} (7... Bxd6 {Most common, but not a challenging line.} 8. Re1+ $1 {[%csl Re8] To annoy the king on e8.} Kf8 {This is Black's idea. However White is slightly better with a number of moves, that's why I'll recommend something relatively new.} (8... Be7 $6 {Too slow.} 9. c3 $5 $14 {[%cal Rd4c3,Gd1c2] We are happy both to play for compensation if Black accepts to take on c3, where 10.Qc2! is a nice response or we just regain material with a slight edge.}) 9. h3 $5 {The line is semi-forced.} Nge5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Bd5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1d4] The idea is to take on d4 with the queen, without running into the Bh2+ tricks, so we are provoking c6, which is a weakness.} (11. Qxd4 $4 {[%csl Rd4] Common blunder.} Nf3+ $1 12. gxf3 Bh2+ $1 $19 {[%csl Rd4] The queen is lost.}) 11... c6 {Black doesn't have a choice.} 12. Bb3 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gc8h3] The only critical move, to introduce the Bxh3 threat.} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gd2e4] To control f3 and also threaten Ne4.}) 8. h3 $5 {In this line, I also want to recommend something fresh and fun.} Nf6 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7,Gg5] We play for activity, not for capturing back material.} Nd8 10. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3b5,Ga3c4] The knight is ready to jump to b5 or c4, Black must be careful, only 2 games have been played here.}) (5... Ne4 $5 {Despite being less played than 5...d5, it had a recent boost in popularity, since strong players prefer to avoid the main theory, and try out this safe variation, with less lines to study.} 6. Qe2 $5 {[%csl Be2] White's most testing line.} Nc5 $1 {Necessary move.} (6... Bb4+ $2 {It seems pretty smart to include this check, since White didn't castle, but in reality, it's a losing mistake:} 7. Kd1 $1 {[%csl Re4] The knight is in trouble.} Nc5 8. a3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,Rb4a5] Followed by b4 and White wins a piece.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Gg1] I like castling, it is the most useful move, and we don't reveal our cards to the opponent yet.} Ne6 $1 {[%csl Be6] The correct move order for Black.} (7... Be7 $6 {In the majority of games, Black confused the move order and started with this natural developing move, but it's a mistake!} 8. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Rd4] White can organize fast play against the d4 pawn, that for the moment is attacked.} Ne6 {Black's most common try, to defend the pawn.} (8... d5 {or 8...d6 will lead to the same.} 9. exd6 {Black doesn't have a satisfactory recapture.} Qxd6 {looks fine, but it's very risky:} 10. b4 $1 {[%csl Bb4,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gb4b5] Key move, White dismantles the coordination of Black's knight, it was played by GM Jones, if you want to improve in the Scotch Gambit, checking his games is valuable.}) (8... O-O {Not challenging, of course.} 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Rxd4 {[%csl Gd4] White succesfully regains the pawn.}) 9. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] We play for activity, we don't care about the pawn so much.} d5 {Probably the best, and it was used by GM Vidit.} (9... dxc3 $6 {Black accepts the challenge, but it's a dangerous decision.} 10. Nxc3 O-O 11. b3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc3d5,Gc3e4,Ga1c1] This is extremely easy to play for White, the compensation is huge. Also visually, it's simple to understand that the Black extra pawn is absolutely irrelevant, Black has no space and the pieces are shut down.}) 10. exd6 cxd6 {The best.} 11. cxd4 {We can follow the game Mamedov-Vidit, 0-1, Gashimov Memorial Rapid 2023.} d5 12. Bb3 O-O 13. Nc3 $14) 8. Bxe6 $5 {I think this is the only viable approach to fight for an advantage. I played this move myself in 2 games against strong GMs.} dxe6 {You should expect this recapture more often, since Black tries to play a known structure that can be reached from many openings.} (8... fxe6 {Less often played, and understandably so. Black keeps the d-file closed, so the queen is safe, but the structure is quite unusual.} 9. Rd1 {White goes for the pawn.}) 9. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Rd4] The pawn on d4 will sooner or later fall, and we will have an interesting position, where White has more space and some dark squares control, while Black has a potentially very strong light-squares bishop.} Be7 {Most logical move.} (9... Bc5 {is met with:} 10. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Rc5][%cal Gc3d4] To win the pawn back with tempo.}) 10. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Gc3b5] Key move to remember, since the pawn can be recaptured in many ways, but this is the most precise.} O-O 11. Nb5 {We can follow my game against GM Sanal Vahap:} Bd7 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 $6 {Black went for the logical trade, but in fact, it was very dangerous.} 13. Rxd4 $1 {[%csl Rd7,Rg8][%cal Gd4d7,Gd4g4] Important recapture, first I threaten to pin the bishop down, and later I swing the rook to g4.}) 6. Bb5 Ne4 (6... Nd7 {This is a far less played line than 6...Ne4, but it's a serious one nevertheless, and it has been played in 1200 games.} 7. O-O {[%cal Yf8e7,Yf8c5] Black has 2 logical squares to develop the bishop.} Be7 {Main move.} 8. Bxc6 {The main move.} bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 $1 {[%csl Cb8] The most sound variation, I have also used it once with Black.} (9... Nxe5 {Possible move, but very concrete, so Black must have serious knowledge to enter into this line.} 10. Bf4 Ng6 $6 {The most common move, but inaccurate:} 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Nxe7 Nxe7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3] Simple, and slightly better, thanks to the better structure and dark squares.}) 10. Nc3 O-O {The best move for Black.} (10... c5 $6 {Is a bit premature.} 11. Ndb5 $1 {[%csl Rd5] Attacking the d5-pawn.} c6 12. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] This is an annoying check.} Bxd6 13. exd6 O-O {Necessary move.} (13... Qxd6 $4 {14 games continued like this, including one with GM Shirov, but it's a losing mistake.} 14. Re1+ $1 {The beginning of a forced sequence:} Be6 15. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd6][%cal Rd5e4] With tempo on the queen.} Qe7 16. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re7] Another tempo.} f6 17. Nxc5 {White wins with brute force.} Qxc5 18. Rxe6+ Kf7 19. Rxf6+ $3 $18 {[%csl Gf6] A beautiful tactic, as we can see in the game Jones-Shirov, 2020.}) 14. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6] White holds onto the passed pawn.}) 11. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga1d1,Gf1e1] Preventing c5} a5 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Ga5a4,Ga8a6] Strong positional move with two ideas: a4, grabbing queenside space, and Ra6, activating the rook (c5 next).} 12. Re1 {Simply some useful moves, and then Bd2-Rad1-h3. If Black waits, White's position will for sure be slightly better.} (12. Nf5 $6 {Premature.} Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 $1 14. Qd3 Na6 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e6] Black will improve the knight and even be slightly better.}) 12... a4 $1 {[%csl Ba4] This is Black's priority.} (12... Ra6 {Black's most common continuation.} 13. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Oa6,Ge1] Now it's a different story, Nf5 is a strong move, since the rook is too early on a6.} Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Qd7 15. Qd3 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Rb8a6] Here the point of 13.Nf5 is well highlighted.}) 13. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2] That's why, the bishop is placed on d2 for the moment, and it's not a bad square.} (13. Bf4 $6 {[%cal Rd4f5] Not wise, as there is no Nf5 move in the future.} Ra6 14. Rad1 c5 $132 {[%cal Rd4f5] Nf5 is impossible.}) 13... Ra6 {A human move.} 14. Nf5 {Straight-forward.}) 7. Nxd4 Bd7 (7... Bc5 {The best way for Black.} 8. Be3 {[%csl Ce3] This is our recommendation.} O-O $1 {[%csl Bg8] The best line.} (8... Bd7 {The old main line.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nd2 $1 $14 {[%csl Bd2] Key move, to eliminate Black's strongest piece.} Nxd2 {Black must capture the knight.} 11. Qxd2 Qe7 {A common move, but the queen is not great on this square.} 12. O-O O-O 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rf7f6] Tough to come up with a plan for Black.}) 9. Nxc6 {White should enter into this semi-concrete line:} bxc6 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. Qxd5 {For the moment, White won two pawns, but the theory only begins here.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Be7] The best move.} (12... Qxd5 {[%csl Rd5] Entering the endgame is quite risky for Black:} 13. Bxd5 Rxb2 14. Na3 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] I don't want to say that it's lost, but White can for sure try to convert the extra material.}) 13. O-O Rxb2 {The main line.} 14. Nc3 {Black has two tries with an equal amount of 64 games: 14...Rd8 or 14...Rxc2.} Rxc2 {This is the most challenging, Black aims to kill the game in a concrete manner.} 15. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4e5,Gc3d5,Gd4c3] White defends the c3 knight, and at the same time prepares the knight jump.} Ne6 $1 (15... Ba6 $2 {Was played in the game Lu Miaoyi-Spasic, 2022 ,but Black soon ended up in a lost position.} 16. Nd5 $1) 16. Qd3 Rb2 17. Nd5 {This is my recommendation.} Qc5 18. Rac1 {Critical try.} Qd4 19. Qf5 $5 {[%csl Bf5] This is interesting, to protect the e5 pawn, there are only 6 games here, and Black, even after all of these good moves, must show precision.}) 8. Bxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6] White must ruin Black's structure.} bxc6 9. O-O {The starting position of the main line. Black has two plausible replies: 9...Be7 or 9...Bc5.} Bc5 {[%csl Bc5] The main line. You should be expecting to face this quite often, since this move has a good reputation and is consistently used at all levels.} (9... Be7 $5 {This is an old line, but objectively it has the same strength as the more active Bc5. That's why ocasionally this is used by strong players as well.} 10. f3 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3f4] White's idea is to first kick the knight from e4 before going f4, this way we win a tempo.} Nc5 11. f4 O-O $1 {Black's most common and best try.} (11... Ne4 $6 {It was played in 1/3 of the games that reached this position, but it's not a great idea.} 12. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Re4][%cal Gc3e4] White trades Black's most active piece.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 {[%cal Gf4f5]} c5 $5 {[%csl Gc5] Black's best bet is to improve the pawn structure.} (13... O-O $2 {Common mistake.} 14. f5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Rg8][%cal Gf5f6] White gains all the space.}) 14. Nb3 c4 15. Nd4 c5 16. Ne2 Bc6 {However Black's position is still super risky:} 17. Ng3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg3f5,Rg7g6] We plan to go Nf5 or provoke g6, which is a clear concession.}) 12. f5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] White achieves f5, and the position becomes concrete, since Black must have a reaction, otherwise he gets run over.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rf5f6,Gc6c5] Black gets the knight to e4, stopping f6 and also preparing c5.} 13. Nb3 $5 {[%csl Bb3] I think this is White's best try, it's an useful prophylactic move.}) 10. f3 $1 {White should include this move.} Ng5 11. f4 {White's most testing line.} Ne4 {Most common.} (11... Ne6 {Positional line, but a bit passive.} 12. c3 f5 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5] This is Black's point, to blockade the passed e5 pawn.} 13. Na3 $5 {This is my recommendation, and it's a new move. The idea is to support the d4 knight.} O-O (13... Bxa3 {Not scary.} 14. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Rd7] The important asset is the undisputed c1 bishop.}) 14. Nac2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a3,Gc1e3,Gg1h1] White can slowly create a bind on the dark squares, and enjoys a positional advantage.}) 12. Be3 {Black has some options.} Bb6 {The old main line.} (12... O-O {Second most common move, but White gets very easy and standard play:} 13. Nd2 {We want to get rid of the knight.} Nxd2 {Most played, but White achieves the goal of this line:} 14. Qxd2 f6 15. Rae1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3] Same spirit of the position, White has a positional advantage.}) 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Re4][%cal Gd2e4] Usual good move.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Re8] Black's best reaction, to get rid of the holes on the dark squares.} 14. N4f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 d4 $1 {The most logical.} (15... Bc6 $6 16. c3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rd5d4] White can stop d4, and c5 will be a target, that's why Black should hurry.}) 16. Bf2 Bc6 {The most played move, but also here, White has a large choice to be slightly better:} 17. a4 $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5] I prefer the usual plan, to provoke a5.} a5 18. b3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gf2h4,Gf3d2] White needs a few moves to positionally dominate.} *

