{[%evp 0,25,25,8,24,8,8,-19,-16,-16,20,56,33,35,44,44,39,44,26,26,48,63,58,62,79,49,46,59]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gh7h6] This chapter is dedicated to Black's sidelines on move 4, and in particular the moves: 4...h6, 4...d6 and 4...Be7 (which will most likely lead to the same line).} Be7 {The most sound option.} (4... h6 $6 {[%cal Rf3g5] Black doesn't want to allow Ng5 at all costs, but it has little theoretical value.} 5. Nxd4 Nf6 (5... Qf6 $2 {This line is already refuted.} 6. Nb5 {[%csl Rc7] Black has problems with the c7-pawn.} Bc5 7. O-O {[%csl Gf2] Defending f2.} Bb6 8. Be3 $1 {[%csl Gf1,Rf6,Rf7][%cal Rb6e3,Gf2e3] Black's queen is misplaced.} a6 9. Nd6+ $1 {[%csl Bd6] This is the concrete refutation:} (9. N5c3 {Good enough for a solid advantage.}) 9... cxd6 10. Bxb6 Qxb2 11. Qd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Rf7][%cal Gd5f7] Key point.} Qxb6 12. Qxf7+ Kd8 13. Qf8+ Kc7 14. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5] The knight lands on d5, and Black is lost.} Qd4 15. Nd5+ Kb8 16. Rad1 Qxc4 17. Nb6 $18) (5... Bc5 $4 {A typical blunder.} 6. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Gf7]} Kxf7 7. Qh5+ $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rf7][%cal Gh5f7,Gh5c5] White wins a pawn, and soon enough the game.}) (5... Ne5 6. Be2 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf2f4] f4 next and the knight is simply misplaced.} Nf6 7. f4 Nc6 (7... Nxe4 $2 {Fails tactically.} 8. fxe5 Qh4+ 9. g3 Nxg3 10. Nf3 $1 {[%csl Bf3] Key move, but not a difficult one.} Qh5 11. Rg1 Nf5 12. Nc3 $18) 8. Nxc6 $5 {Practical way.} (8. Nc3 {White can finish development, and enjoy a better position:} Bb4 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 Ne4 11. Qd3 d5 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Cc1,Ce2] White has the better structrure and the pair or bishops.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] This way there are no weaknesses in White's camp.} d6 10. O-O Be7 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 $16 {A much better position.}) (5... Nxd4 6. Qxd4 d6 {The best.} (6... Nf6 $2 7. e5 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge5] Black is just lost.}) 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. e5 {Transposes to the line below.}) 6. Nc3 {[%csl Gc4,Rh6] White is playing a Four knights opening, but with an extra half tempo, thanks to the inclusion of Bc4 and h6.} Nxd4 (6... Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O O-O 9. e5 $16 {[%csl Ge5] The extra tempo means a lot here.}) (6... Bc5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 $16) 7. Qxd4 {[%cal Ge4e5] White is ready for e5, and it's difficult to stop it:} d6 8. e5 $1 {Using the tactical trick.} Qe7 (8... dxe5 9. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Re8f7,Gd4d8] The point.} Ke7 10. Qc4 $18 {[%csl Re7] White wins.}) 9. Bf4 dxe5 10. Bxe5 $18 {[%csl Re7,Re8][%cal Ge1c1] White will finish development, and Black is not surviving here.}) (4... d6 {Doesn't have any independent value.} 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {[%cal Rf8e7] Black doesn't have a better move than the natural bishop development.} Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bf4 {Transposes to the main line.}) 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {Main line.} (6. Nxc6 $5 {In this move order, this is an extra option that White might consider:} dxc6 (6... bxc6 7. e5 $14) 7. Qxd8+ Bxd8 8. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Ce4] With a slightly better endgame for White.}) 6... O-O 7. O-O d6 {The position reminds a bit the Old Philidor, and we are able to use the same principles:} 8. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Od6,Oe4,Bf4] In this structure, f4 is the best square to develop the bishop.} (8. Re1 {White has tried other lines, but I don't think that anything can be more useful than Bf4, for example:} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 c6 10. Bf4 Qb6 $1 $132 {[%csl Gb6] Black is more or less fine.}) 8... Ne5 {The main line, and it was played in the recent Olympiad, in the game Fawzy-Abdusattorov. So we should take this move seriously.} (8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 (9... Nh5 {A strange way to develop.} 10. Be3 Bf6 11. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rh5] The knight is misplaced.}) (9... c6 $6 {Too slow, compared to 8.Re1.} 10. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Gf4] White can immediately target the d6 pawn.}) 10. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gf1e1] White is only slightly better, with no need to know the theory.}) (8... Re8 {A logical move.} 9. Re1 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge5g6] This is Black's typical knight maneuver.} (9... Bf8 {This is part of Black's plan, but White can play the concrete reaction:} 10. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 11. e5 $1 $14 {[%cal Rd6e5,Gd1d8] Trying to enter a better endgame.}) 10. Bf1 Ng6 11. Bg3 c6 12. h3 {[%csl Gh3] A useful move.} Bf8 13. a4 $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5] As a rule, this can't be a bad inclusion if Black can't make use of the b4 square, since White wants to take space and stop b5 or provoke Black's ...a5, which weakens the structure overall.} (13. f4 $6 {Premature.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Rg1][%cal Gb6b2,Gb6g1] Strong reply.} 14. Bf2 Qxb2 15. Qd2 Qa3 $15 {[%csl Ga3] Black has the a3 escape.}) 13... a5 14. f4 $14 {[%csl Gf4] Now it's a good time to grab space with f4, since:} Qb6 $2 {is bad with this inclusion.} 15. Bf2 Qxb2 16. Qd2 $18 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rb2a3,Ge1b1] White is winning compared to 13.f4.}) (8... Nd7 $6 {[%csl Rd5] A dubious move, as it weakens the d5 square.} 9. Nd5 Nb6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Cd3,Cf4] White is slightly better thanks to the pair of bishops:} Nc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Black might try to surprise you with this funny move, but no worries, there is no need to take it.} 13. Qc1 {Not the only way, but good enough.} (13. Bxc4 Qxe4 $11 {[%csl Rc4,Rf4] Black's point.}) 13... Ne5 14. Re1 Nxd3 15. cxd3 c5 16. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Gd2][%cal Gd2a5,Gd2c3,Ge1e3,Ge3g3] Long term initiative thanks to the active pieces and poor Black structure.}) 9. Bb3 c6 {This was Nodirbek's choice.} (9... c5 {Concrete try.} 10. Bxe5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Key move, we ruin Black's structure.} (10. Nf3 $6 {Allows Black to equalize:} c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Black's idea.} 11. Bxe5 cxb3 12. Bxf6 bxc2 $1 {[%cal Rc2d1] Important intermezzo.} 13. Qxc2 Bxf6 $11) 10... dxe5 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5,Re7,Gf3] That's why c5 is not positionally correct. This is a typical early 20th century position, where we will most likely achieve a good knight vs bad bishop on e7 scenario.}) (9... Ng6 {Standard idea.} 10. Bg3 Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8] The most logical, just to improve the pieces.} (10... Ng4 $6 {Time consuming maneuver.} 11. h3 N4e5 12. f4 Nc6 {Black has spent 5 moves just to transfer the f6 knight to g6.} 13. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Bd5,Rf6,Rg6] We will gladly grab the d5 square.}) 11. f4 Bf8 12. Nf3 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3g5,Gf4f5] A very good move, to highlight the f7 weakness.} c6 (12... Nxe4 $4 {Fails tactically:} 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Bxf7+ $1 $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3g5]}) 13. f5 $1 {[%csl Rg6] And Black's knight from c6 has made a long journey just to end up on h8, the worst square possible.} Nh8 (13... Ne5 $4 {Loses the game.} 14. Bxe5 $1 dxe5 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Nxe5 $18 {[%csl Rf7] f7 is tough to defend.}) 14. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gd1f3] White is better.}) 10. h3 {[%csl Ch3] I like this move, useful and improving.} (10. a4 $5 $14 {[%cal Rb7b5,Ga4a5] This is a simple alternative, to stop b5, and also to create space for the b3 bishop.}) (10. Re1 Re8 {[%csl Bd4] The knight stays well on d4, and White is slightly better with any logical move.} 11. h3 $14 (11. Nf5 $2 {GM Fawzy took the wrong direction.} Bf8 12. Ne3 b5 $1 $15 {[%csl Cd4,Re3] The knight stays worse on e3 than on d4, and in fact Black managed to win this game.}) (11. Bg3 $14)) 10... Re8 (10... Qc7 11. Bg3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] White is ready for expansion.}) 11. Bg3 {[%cal Gf2f4] The plan is to play for f4 and slowly build up a kingside attack:} Bf8 12. f4 Ned7 13. Qf3 $14 {[%csl Ce4,Cf3,Cf4] White should be very happy with the opening outcome, with a slightly better position, and we didn't need to do anyhting extraordinary to achieve it.} *

