{[%evp 0,35,33,12,12,12,13,-3,-3,-15,13,13,13,8,8,-18,-4,-14,-17,-32,0,-3,0,17,17,-24,-24,-24,5,22,22,65,62,74,108,-65,25,-49]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bb4+ {Black's best option according to the engine, but it's only the 4th move by popularity for a number of reasons: Black must be very precise and must have concrete knowledge of only moves, and also the arising positions are very tricky (one wrong move can cost Black the game).} 5. c3 dxc3 6. O-O {Personally, I would go for the main line, as out of 1200 games, the best move according to the engine is the 4th one by popularity, with only 200 games. So, there are decent chances that not everybody will know and remember it during the game.} (6. bxc3 {I used this move in my childhood.} Ba5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] The strongest move.} (6... Be7 $4 {Many opponents fell for this trap.} 7. Qd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Bd5,Rf7][%cal Gd5f7,Rg8h6,Gc1h6] And there is no defence against Qxf7.}) (6... Bc5 $2 {Also bad.} 7. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Rc5,Gf7][%cal Re8f7,Gd1d5] A typical tactical motif.} Kxf7 8. Qd5+ $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rf7e8,Gd5h5] White regains material, with a clear advantage.}) 7. O-O Bb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] The best way to play, although it has been played in only 33 games out of 263.} (7... d6 $6 {The most common move, it's not completely bad, but a bit risky.} 8. Qb3 Be6 {The best try.} (8... Qe7 9. e5 $1 $16 {[%csl Be5,Re7,Re8] White has a better position.}) 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gg5e6] We want to capture on e6 with the knight.} Bb6 {Only move.} 11. Nxe6 Qe7 12. Bg5 {White has a lot of ideas for the initiative.} (12. Nd2 $5 {Also deserves attention.}) 12... Qf7 13. Na3 $14 {[%csl Re8] It's unpleasant for Black to play with the king in the center.}) (7... Nge7 $2 {It would seem logical to finish development, but after:} 8. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] The position is terrible for Black, since f7 is too vulnerable.} Ne5 (8... O-O $2 9. Qh5 $18 {[%csl Rf7,Rh7] Game over.}) 9. Nxf7 $1 {White can use this typical tactic:} Nxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qh5+ $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rf7][%cal Gh5f7,Gh5a5] The point, White has a big advantage.}) 8. e5 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rd7d6] An interesting try, to stop Black's development.} (8. a4 $5 {This is a rare move that deserves attention.} d6 9. Nbd2 $44 {White has full compensation for the pawn, and the position is almost unexplored (only 1 e-mail game where White won).}) 8... Nge7 9. Ba3 O-O 10. Re1 h6 {For the engine, this is fine for Black, but the engine evaluation doesn't mean much in these type of positions, White has full compensation for the pawn anyway and it's easier to play, for example:} 11. Bb3 $1 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4] A good move, to support the Nbd2-Nc4 idea.} Re8 12. Nbd2 Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Ga5c4,Ga5b3] The engine stops it.} 13. Bc2 $5 {You can keep the bishops on the board, for a richer position.} (13. Nc4 {We can play this anyway.} Nxb3 14. axb3 Nc6 15. h3 d6 $1 {Black will need to give up the pawn at some moment.} 16. exd6 Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 cxd6 18. Bxd6 $11 {An equal, and playable position.}) 13... d5 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Ne4 Nc4 16. Bb3 $5 {This is some sort of forced engine line:} Nxa3 17. Nxd6 Rf8 18. Nxf7 $1 {[%csl Gf7] A simple tactical resource.} Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Nc6 $1 {The best move for the engine.} (19... Rxf7 $4 {Loses.} 20. Rxe7 $18 {[%csl Rf7] The rook is lost.}) 20. Rd6 $11 {Interesting visually, but the engine shows 0.00.}) 6... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] This is the most challenging move, Black is not scared to allow the move e5.} (6... d6 {The most common move, and the most human one.} 7. Qb3 $5 {This is an interesting direction.} (7. a3 {The statistical main line is also a fine option.} Ba5 8. b4 Bb6 9. Qb3 Be6 $1 {The strongest reaction.} (9... Qf6 $6 {Is extremely dangerous for Black:} 10. Nxc3 Nge7 11. Bb2 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Kh1 $36 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gc3d5,Gf2f4] The position plays itself out.}) (9... Qe7 $6 {The most common, but as usual, not that impressive.} 10. Nxc3 Nf6 11. Bg5 $16 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gc3d5] White is better.}) 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ Qe7 12. Qc4 {And we can transfer into a slightly more pleasant endgame after:} Qf7 13. Qxf7+ Kxf7 14. Nxc3 $36 {[%csl Gd5,Rf7][%cal Gc1e3,Gf2e3,Gc3d5] Some questions can still be asked by Black.}) 7... Qf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] The best move.} (7... Qe7 $2 {Most common, but a mistake.} 8. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rb4,Gb5,Rc6] Strong idea.} Bc5 (8... c2 9. Nc3 $1 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rg7] Attacking both the knight and the g7-pawn.}) 9. Nxc3 Nf6 10. Bg5 $18 {[%cal Gc3d5] Nd5 is coming, with a winning position.}) (7... Be6 $6 8. Bd5 $1 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gd5c6] A cool intermezzo, Bxc6 is a threat.} c2 $1 {The best for White, but not easy to spot.} 9. Nc3 $14 {[%eval 40,0] Advantage for White.}) (7... Qd7 $6 {[%cal Rc8e6] Doesn't allow Black to develop.} 8. Nxc3 Bxc3 9. Qxc3 Nf6 10. b4 $14 {White is better.}) 8. Bb5 c2 $1 {[%csl Gc2] This is Black's idea, to use the pawn as a distraction.} 9. Qxb4 {The most logical.} (9. Nc3 {[%csl Gf6] A possible try, but this is an improved version thanks to the queen on f6.} Bxc3 10. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] White must include this intermezzo.} (10. Qxc3 $6 Qxc3 $1 $17 {[%csl Gc3] A big difference.}) 10... Qg6 11. Qxc3 {[%csl Gg7] But compared to having a queen on e7, at least the g7-pawn is not hanging.} Bd7 12. e5 $13 {[%csl Ge5] No advantage, but a very unclear position.}) (9. Bg5 {A playable line.} Qg6 10. Qxb4 cxb1=Q 11. Raxb1 $44 {With full compensation.}) 9... cxb1=Q 10. Rxb1 Bd7 {The strongest move.} (10... Nge7 11. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rf6e6,Gf3d4] This is better for White, since the king is still stuck on e8.}) (10... h6 {Black stops Bg5.} 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White can develop an initiative:} Nge7 12. Bb2 Qg6 13. Qc3 O-O 14. Bc4 $40 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gc4,Gf3] White's pieces are very active, for the engine this is a big advantage.}) 11. Qb3 Nge7 12. Bg5 Qg6 13. Rfe1 {White has full compensation for the missing material, for example:} a6 14. Bd3 Ne5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Qxb7 Qb6 18. Qd5 $36 {White regained material, and it's equal for the engine, only +0.10, but I'm guessing that not many players would pick Black in this position.}) (6... c2 $2 {Some players tried to give back the pawn this way, but it's very bad.} 7. Qxc2 d6 8. Qb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf7] White has a big advantage.}) (6... Nge7 $2 {Bad, due to the standard reaction:} 7. bxc3 Bc5 8. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] To put pressure on f7.} Ne5 (8... O-O $4 9. Qh5 $18 {White wins.}) 9. Nxf7 $1 {[%csl Gf7] Typical tactic and White is much better after:} Nxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qh5+ Ng6 12. Qxc5 $16) (6... cxb2 $2 {The second most common move, but it's a mistake.} 7. Bxb2 Nf6 (7... f6 8. Nh4 $1 $40 {[%cal Gd1h5] Qh5 is coming with a big attack.}) 8. e5 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4] White has a serious initiative.}) 7. a3 $5 {[%csl Ca3] This is our idea for this line, Lucas showed it to me, and I was very surprised to see that it poses serious problems to this line. Once again, Black has only one good move for equality:} (7. e5 {The most common move, we can follow the game Mastrovasilis-Vidit, FIDE World Cup 2023. It has high theoretical value:} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] The best way to equalize.} 8. exf6 dxc4 9. fxg7 Rg8 10. Qxd8+ Nxd8 {The endgame is equal, for example, the game continued with:} (10... Kxd8 11. Bg5+ Be7 12. Nxc3 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Rxg7 14. f4 Bd7 15. Nd5) 11. Nxc3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge8f7] Key move, to improve the king.} 13. Re1+ $5 {I tried to make an improvement over the game, but it's not easy to pose problems:} Kf7 14. Nd4 Rxg7 15. Bf4 Ne6 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Bxc7 Rag8 18. Bg3 $11 {Playable, but objectively equal.}) 7... Be7 $1 {[%csl Ge7] The best move.} (7... Bc5 $6 {Allows White to gain another tempo:} 8. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] This is part of White's plan anyway.} Be7 9. Nxc3 O-O 10. Ra2 $1 {[%cal Ga2d2] Another strong idea, very typical in these lines.} d6 11. Rd2 $36 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd2,Gf3][%cal Gc1b2,Ge4e5] All of White's pieces are active, this is not compensation, but an initiative.}) (7... cxb2 $6 {As usual, this is quite dangerous.} 8. Bxb2 Be7 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7] White can try the concrete line:} O-O 10. e5 $1 d5 $1 {Black steers the game into an endgame:} 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Nxf7 $3 {[%csl Bf7] Brilliant intermezzo.} Rxf7 13. Bxd5 Bxb2 14. Bxf7+ $1 {[%cal Rg8f7,Gd1b3] The point.} Kf8 15. Qxd8+ Nxd8 16. Ra2 Bf6 17. Bc4 $14 {Perhaps an engine could hold this endgame, it's only +0.50, but objectively, it is a difficult task for a human.}) 8. e5 {This is the critical position of this chapter, Black now has a choice:} Ng4 {This is the main try.} (8... d5 $5 $146 {A possible novelty, but also very engine heavy.} 9. exf6 dxc4 10. Qe2 (10. fxg7 Rg8 11. Nxc3) 10... Qd3 $3 {[%csl Bd3] This is Black's only move, which is why nobody has yet entered into this line.} (10... gxf6 $2 11. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd8,Re8][%cal Gb1c3] And White will develop a crushing attack.}) 11. Qxd3 cxd3 12. fxe7 {An amazing position, Black has a choice:} d2 {The human way.} (12... c2 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3] Black plays for the passed pawns, but it's a bit risky, as the pawns are well blockaded.} 13. Nbd2 Nxe7 14. Re1 Be6 15. Re3 O-O-O 16. Ne1 $13 {For the engine the position is equal, but I suppose it's an unclear and playable endgame.}) 13. Nxc3 dxc1=Q 14. Raxc1 Nxe7 {The endgame is balanced, but still playable:} (14... Be6 {This is a more standard reaction, but here White actually has some pressure:} 15. Ne4 Kxe7 16. Nc5 Rab8 17. Rfe1 h6 18. b4 $36 {[%csl Gc1,Gc5,Ge1,Re6,Re7] +0.15 For the engine, so White can definitely try to create something.}) 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Rxc7 Nd5 17. Rc4 Bd7 18. Nd6 Rfd8 19. Nxb7 {White won a pawn, and the engine is fast to jump into pawn down rook endgame:} Rdb8 20. Rd4 Rxb7 21. Rxd5 Bc6 22. Rd2 Bxf3 23. gxf3 $11 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e2] The engine will hold this, but it's a pawn up rook endgame, so is still play left in the position.}) (8... cxb2 {Possible, but not in the spirit of the position.} 9. Bxb2 Nh5 10. Ng5 $5 $146 {[%csl Bg5] White has this tactical try.} (10. Nc3 d6 11. Nd5 Be6) 10... Bxg5 11. Qxh5 g6 $1 {Black should first include g6.} (11... O-O $6 {Is met with:} 12. f4 $1 {[%csl Gf4,Rg5] And the bishop is locked out.} Bh6 13. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Rg7g6] White is better.}) 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gf2f4,Ge5e6] A strong maneuver, with both f4 and e6 ideas.} Bf4 $3 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Bf4e5] Super strong move.} 14. e6 Be5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Black's point.} 15. exf7+ Kg7 {But okay, it's difficult to believe that a human will be ready to enter into this position:} 16. Qd2 Bxb2 17. Qxb2+ Qf6 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. Nc3 $11 {The endgame is unclear visually, but equal for the engine.}) 9. Qe2 $5 $146 {[%csl Ce2] This is the invention of Lucas.} (9. Re1 d6 $1 {[%csl Bd6] This is the best try, also from a human standpoint.} (9... cxb2 {The engine gladly takes the pawn, but of course, it's never easy for a human to go for this decision.} 10. Bxb2 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Qc2 O-O 13. h3 Nf6 14. Nbd2 {White has full compensation, but the engine is as usual is very good at neutralizing:} Qf4 $1 {[%csl Bf4] Key move.} 15. Bd3 Be6 $1 16. Ne4 {Still, play is left, for example:} Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Qh6 18. Rae1 $36 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gb2c1] All of White's pieces are active, and it might happen that a human may blunder something.}) (9... O-O $2 {Is a mistake.} 10. h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4] The knight is in trouble.} cxb2 11. Bxb2 Nh6 12. Nc3 $36 {[%cal Gc3d5] Dream scenario.}) 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Qxd6 cxd6 {The endgame is just equal, and I don't think White can ask too many questions, for example:} 12. Nxc3 Nge5 13. Bd5 O-O 14. Nxe5 $5 {[%cal Rc6e5,Gf2f4] To meet Nxe5 with f4.} dxe5 $1 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rxe5 Be6 17. Bg5 $11 {Some small ideas here and there, but of course, at this point, Black should be out of the danger zone.}) 9... d6 $1 {The strongest.} (9... O-O $2 {Bad move.} 10. h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4] Key motif.} cxb2 11. Bxb2 Nh6 12. Nc3 d6 13. Rad1 Re8 14. Rfe1 $36 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gc4,Gd1,Ge1,Ge2,Gf3,Rh6] Every piece joined the game, and also the engine agrees that White is objectively better.}) (9... c2 10. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] First we can develop.} d6 11. exd6 cxd6 12. Qxc2 $44 {[%csl Gd5] Long term compensation, thanks to the d5 square.}) (9... d5 {Is met with:} 10. Rd1 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb1c3] And Black should reconsider his choice of having a pawn on d5.}) 10. exd6 cxd6 {[%cal Gg4e5] This is the more human move, to have the e5 square for the knight.} (10... Qxd6 {Positionally it's understandable, but it's a very risky decision to allow the Rd1 tempo.} 11. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Gd1] We bring the piece into the game.} cxb2 $1 {[%csl Gb2] The engine bravely captures the pawn.} (11... Qg6 $2 {Natural, but actually very bad.} 12. Nxc3 O-O 13. Rd5 $3 $40 {[%csl Bd5,Rg6][%cal Re7c5,Rc8e6,Gc4d3,Gc1g5] A super move, to stop Bc5 and actually Black is actually short of squares for the pieces.}) 12. Bxb2 Qg6 13. Bd5 {Visually, White is doing great, but as usual, Black can force things:} Be6 $1 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. h3 Nf6 {And don't worry that you are 2 pawns down, White has a big safety net thanks to the activtiy:} 16. Ne5 Qe4 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxc6 Bd6 19. Nc3 Nxc3 20. Bxc3 Kd7 {Black can try to hold on to the extra pawn, but it doesn't lead anywhere:} (20... O-O 21. Bb4 $11 {Full compensation.}) 21. Nd4 f6 22. Nb5 Rab8 23. Nxd6 cxd6 24. Bb4 d5 25. Rac1 Rhc8 26. f3 $11 {[%cal Gg1f2,Gf2e3,Ge3d4] The best position that Black can achieve, I guess a draw offer is imminent.}) 11. Nxc3 O-O 12. h3 Nge5 {White doesn't have an attack, but can still try to play positionally, for example:} (12... Nf6 13. Bf4 $44 {Full compensation.}) 13. Nxe5 dxe5 {Critical, to improve the structure.} (13... Nxe5 $6 {This is a positional inaccuracy.} 14. Bd5 Re8 15. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Gd5] This is not only compensation, but slightly better for White, since the pieces are very active.}) 14. Rd1 Bd6 15. Qh5 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] This is Black's point.} 16. Ne4 Be7 {Black defends from all of the threats, but White can still try to trick the opponent:} 17. Bh6 $5 {[%csl Gh6] To scare the opponent.} (17. Ng5 {This is a safe alternative.} Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Qd6 19. Be3 $11 {Equal, everything will come off the board quite soon.}) (17. Qxe5 $4 {Don't fall for the trap.} Nf3+ $1 $19 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gd8d1] Black picks up the rook with check.}) 17... Qc7 (17... gxh6 $4 18. Qxe5 $1 $18 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Ga1d1] This is the point, d1 is defended.}) 18. Rdc1 $36 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rg7h6,Gc4f7] And the adventure continues.} *

