{[%evp 0,26,30,19,19,19,11,29,29,-28,27,-11,5,5,5,-1,12,6,6,6,6,21,21,21,13,23,17,17,18]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. c3 Nf6 {The main line, and the best move by far.} (5... d3 {Not a challenging sideline, but you can expect this from somebody who wants to avoid main theory.} 6. b4 $5 {I like to start with this move, since taking space on the queenside is part of White's plan anyway.} Bb6 {Necessary.} (6... Be7 $2 {Is not available.} 7. Qb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf7] Black can't defend f7 in a natural way.}) 7. a4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5] a5 is a threat, a nice inclusion.} a6 8. O-O {White will finish development and regain the pawn on d3:} d6 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10. Bxd3 O-O 11. Nc4 {[%csl Rb6,Gc4][%cal Rc4b6] We can see the use of 7.a4, abd Nc4 comes with the threat of ruining Black's structure.} Ba7 12. Bg5 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Gd1c2,Yb4b5] The position is very pleasant for White, with a lot of ideas, and simple play in the center.}) (5... dxc3 $2 {A typical mistake.} 6. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd1d5,Re8f7] White can make use of the vulnerable bishop on c5.} Kxf7 7. Qd5+ Ke8 8. Qh5+ $1 {[%csl Gh5] A precise move to include, since Black must make a concession:} Kf8 {The best, but White can capture the piece with check.} (8... g6 $6 9. Qxc5 $18 {[%csl Rh8] The rook may become a target on the diagonal.}) 9. Qxc5+ Qe7 10. Qe3 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge4] Defending e4, and White has a close to winning advantage.}) 6. cxd4 Bb4+ {The starting position of this tabyia.} 7. Nbd2 $5 {This is the modern trend and my recommendation, it is a far less common move (only 800 games compared to roughly 10k games for each main line), which means that Black will most likely not be so prepared, and could end up in a potentially dangerous position.} (7. Bd2 {This is the statistical main line.} Nxe4 $1 {The cleanest equalizer, and it's already a well known one.} (7... Bxd2+ {The most common response.} 8. Nbxd2 d5 {It is a very rich position, and I think that White might be able to get some kind of game after:} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 $5 $132 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gf1e1,Ge4c5] Objectively, Black is doing okay, but White can play and develop an initiative.}) 8. Bxb4 Nxb4 9. Bxf7+ {White must win back material:} Kxf7 10. Qb3+ Kf8 $1 {[%csl Bf8] The precise idea.} 11. Qxb4+ Qe7 {And we are forced to enter into an endgame:} 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O Kd8 {Straight-forward.} 14. Re1 Nf6 15. Ng5 Rf8 $11 {[%csl Rd4] The endgame is equal, but as the game Kosteniuk-Kramnik, 2014 showed, I think White doesn't have any chance to outplay Black, and it could even potentially get tricky.}) (7. Nc3 {This is the old main line, but it's too forcing, in my opinion.} Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. d5 Bf6 10. Re1 Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6 {For the moment, White is a pawn down, but has a development lead. It was an interesting position perhaps half a century ago, but for today's standards, engines have found good continuations for Black:} 12. Bg5 {The old try.} (12. Rf4 $5 {[%cal Re8g8,Gf4f6] This is probably White's best, with idea to sacrifice on f6, and in case of 12...0-0, the problem is that Black can repeat moves.} Ng6 13. Re4+ Ne7 $11 {White repeated in Mamedov-Karjakin, Gashimov Memorial 2021.}) 12... Bxg5 13. Nxg5 h6 $1 {Black attacks the knight before castling, and White's idea is to not allow it with:} 14. Qe2 $5 hxg5 15. Re1 {But Black has:} Be6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] Key defense.} 16. dxe6 f6 $13 {The position is unclear, but engines slightly prefer Black, due to the solid extra pawn.}) 7... d5 {Black's second most common move. He is not trying to equalize in a forcing manner, only striving to obtain a playable position.} (7... Bxd2+ {Doesn't have independent value.} 8. Bxd2 Nxe4 9. d5 {Transposes to the 7...Nxe4 line.}) (7... O-O $6 {Not particularly challenging.} 8. d5 $1 {Important to insert this move in so that d4 will not be hanging.} (8. O-O $6 {But make sure to not play this automatic move!} Bxd2 $1 {[%csl Gg8] And compared to the main line, Black's king is already on g8.} 9. Bxd2 (9. Nxd2 $6 {Drops d4.} Nxd4 $36 {[%csl Gd4]}) 9... Nxe4 10. d5 $11 {[%csl Gg8] Objectively, White is not worse, but the position is concrete, so this is just an improved version for Black.}) 8... Ne7 9. O-O {[%cal Rb4d2,Gf3d2] Now Bxd2 leads to nothing, since White can recapture with the knight.} d6 10. a3 $1 {[%csl Rb4] Black has to make an unpleasant decision.} Bc5 {Keeps the bishop, but White can develop with tempo.} (10... Bxd2 11. Nxd2 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2] White has the bishop pair and nothing to worry about.}) 11. b4 Bb6 12. Bb2 $40 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb2g7] This is a dream scenario for White, with a lot of play on the long diagonal, more space and amazing development.}) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O O-O {[%csl Rb4] Compared to the similar position after 7.Bd2, the dark squared bishop is still on the board, which is an improvement for White, since the b4 bishop is still a bit awkward at the moment.} 10. a3 {We immediately ask a question, Black has three possible responses:} Be7 {The most common move.} (10... Bxd2 {This is a logical decision, to trade the bishop for a potentially strong knight.} 11. Bxd2 {[%csl Gc4,Gd2] Although objectively, Black is doing okay, it doesn't mean that it's a dead equal position, White has the bishop pair, which is a long term asset.} Nb6 {This is probably Black's best.} (11... Be6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc4e6] A solid approach, but now the d5 knight is a bit stuck since it allows White to ruin the structure.} 12. Rc1 {[%csl Gc4] Best to start this way, to defend the c4 bishop.} (12. Re1 $6 {Was played in Jones-Adams, 2022, but both GMs overlooked that:} Nc3 $1 $11 {[%csl Gc3,Rc4][%cal Ge6c4] Equalizes immediately.}) 12... h6 {Black stops Ng5.} 13. Re1 Re8 14. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7,Re6][%cal Rd5b6] This type of position is not easy to play for Black, since the pieces are a bit stuck.} Rb8 15. Re4 $5 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh2h3,Gc1e1] Overprotecting d4, and later on we can continue improving.}) (11... Bg4 {[%csl Rd4] The most common option.} 12. h3 Bh5 {The best.} (12... Bxf3 $6 {Taking the pawn is too optimistic.} 13. Qxf3 {[%csl Rd5] d5 is hanging for the moment.} Nb6 14. Bd3 $1 $36 {[%csl Gd2,Gd3] The two bishops are very strong, and it's not even so easy for Black to win the d4-pawn without a serious concession. In fact, out of 7 games that reached this position, White won 5 of them.}) 13. g4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] A necessary move, Black was ready for Nxd4.} Bg6 14. Re1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gc4,Gd2,Rd5][%cal Gd1b3,Rc6e7,Gf3e5,Gd2a5] Although Black can still play this position, it is for sure unpleasant, since Black can't easily coordinate the pieces after Qb3, since Nce7 can be met with Ne5, further gaining momentum and space.}) 12. Ba2 Be6 $1 {[%csl Be6] This is Black's best, and it was played in the game Savitha-Alekseenko, Sunway Sitges 2024.} (12... Bg4 $6 {This was tried in Vokhidov-Wei, 2024.} 13. Bc3 $1 {An improvement over the game, and actually d5 is a big threat already.} Re8 14. d5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rg4,Rg7][%cal Gd1d4] When the knight moves, Qd4 is an idea.}) 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Bc3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Re6][%cal Gd1e2,Gf1e1,Ga1d1] The position is equal, but it's pretty simple to play for White, and after all, White is not risking anything.}) (10... Ba5 $6 {[%csl Ra5] The worst square, the bishop will get locked out of the game.} 11. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4][%cal Ge4c5,Gb2b4] The knight is headed to c5, where it puts pressure on b7 and can be easily consolidated with b2-b4.} Bg4 $2 {A mistake.} 12. Nc5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ra5,Rb7][%cal Rb7b6] And in fact, Black's situation is quite bad, since, b6 will simply trap the a5 bishop.} Rb8 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 $1 {White can crash through with brute force.} Bg6 15. b4 $1 Bb6 16. Qb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4] A very dominant position, the evaluation is big for White.}) 11. Re1 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2e4] Compared to a French Exchange, Black lost a tempo by going Bb4+ and Be7, while the knight on d2 is not as perfect as the knight on c3, but still, it can jump to e4, from where it can be useful.} Be6 {The most logical, Black just wants to be solid.} (11... Bg4 {The most common move, to put pressure on the d4 pawn, but it's a bit optimistic.} 12. h3 $1 {[%csl Gh3] Always a good inclusion.} Bh5 {[%cal Gd5b6,Gc6d4] Black is threatening Nb6 followed by Nxd4, which is why:} 13. Ba2 $1 {[%csl Ba2][%cal Gd1b3] Is the key prophylactic move, and it also prepares the Qb3 tempo against d5.} (13. Qb3 $2 {Keep in mind, that this works only with a bishop on d2.} Na5 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ga5b3,Ga5c4] Black gains the c4 bishop.}) 13... Bf6 {The main try, but White has two good options:} (13... Nxd4 $4 {Fails tactically.} 14. g4 $1 Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Rh5] White wins a piece.}) 14. Qb3 {[%csl Gb3] Straight-forward choice.} (14. g4 $5 {Deserves attention.} Bg6 15. Nc4 $36 {[%cal Gc4e5] The knight gets to e5 with a big initiative.}) 14... Nb6 15. d5 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rc6a5,Gb3b4,Rc6e7,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Black has problems with coordination.} Nd4 $1 {Necessary.} 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5] The bishop enters g5, and Black has to be very careful.}) 12. b4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Cd2][%cal Gb4b5,Gf3e5,Gc1b2,Cd2b3,Cb3c5] There is only one game here, Maurizzi-Deac, EU-ch 2024. I really like this multi-purpose move, as it is part of our long term plan of getting the knight to c5, but at the same time, it is a waiting move, since the knight on d2 still protects the c4 bishop.} (12. Ne4 {At first, engine approves this move, but I am not sure of it:} Ne3 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd1,Ge3] Standard reaction.} 13. Bxe3 Bxc4 $11 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gd8d7,Gf8e8] Looks completely fine for Black.}) 12... Nf4 {GM Deac went for the straight-forward approach.} (12... a6 {The most human move, since it prevents b5, and somewhere prepares b5 for Black.} 13. Bb2 {We just finish development:} Qd7 14. Qc2 (14. Qb3 $6 {Not on b3, as it runs into:} b5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ge6b3] With concrete counterplay against the queen.}) 14... Rad8 15. Rad1 Rfe8 16. h3 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gd2e4] There is no need to hurry with our long term plan of getting the knight to c5, but whenever it happens, White will for sure have a very pleasant advantage.}) (12... Qd7 {A logical move, but it's quite slow.} 13. Nb3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c5,Gb4b5,Rd5c3,Gc4e6] We are ready for both b5 or Nc5, and Nc3 leads to nothing, due to the Bxe6 intermezzo. White has a pleasant advantage.}) 13. Re4 $5 $146 {[%csl Ge4] I prefer 13.Re4, to keep the game more alive.} (13. g3 {Was played in the game, it's a good move, and probably it was Maurizzi's prep.} Nh3+ 14. Kg2 Nxd4 $1 $146 {[%csl Bd4] The best engine move, but of course, not an easy one to find.} (14... Ng5 $6 {Black went for this logical retreat, but it's actually a mistake:} 15. Rxe6 $3 {[%csl Be6] A brilliant find by Maurizzi, White sacrifices the exchange for positional trumps.} fxe6 (15... Nxe6 $2 {Is not possible.} 16. d5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Re6] Fork.}) 16. Bb2 Kh8 {In the game, White tried the concrete 17.b5, but I think that White should continue slowly:} 17. Qe2 $5 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gd4d5] e6 will fall anyway, and for now Black is very cramped and his position is just sad. White has the advantage.}) 15. Bxe6 fxe6 $1 {[%csl Rf3,Gf8] This is Black's point.} 16. Bb2 {This is the best, but the endgame is quite drawish after:} (16. Kxh3 $6 Nxf3 {Black wins back the piece after:} 17. Nxf3 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Rxf3 $36 {[%csl Gf3] But, during a game, it's not that obvious.}) 16... Nxf3 17. Nxf3 Ng5 $11 {However, we must give credit to GM Maurizzi, it was an interesting try, and you can use it in your own games if you believe that your opponent will not be aware of this.}) 13... Bxc4 {The best.} 14. Nxc4 Nd5 {Black's position looks quite solid, but not fantastic, as the difference in piece activity is noticeable, and it's not like the d4-pawn will be a target anytime soon, for example:} 15. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2] White can simply finish development.} a6 16. Nfe5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 $36 {[%cal Gd1f3,Ga1d1,Gc4a5] Objectively, for the engine it's fine, but visually only White is applying pressure, and it's not easy to suggest a straight-forward path to equality, that's why White can play this position for a long game.} *

