{[%evp 0,49,23,23,23,23,13,-11,-11,-31,-1,3,24,8,-4,7,20,4,4,-1,7,6,6,13,20,18,18,25,26,26,12,17,17,14,14,8,8,13,13,13,43,-10,43,43,56,8,4,3,4,0,33,25]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. c3 Nf6 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 Nxe4 {The main line and the most critical.} 8. d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Black simply won a pawn, so White must be fast.} Ne7 {The most common move by far.} (8... Nxd2 {This is a solid choice, Black aims to exchange pieces off the board.} 9. Bxd2 Bxd2+ (9... Qe7+ $4 {Was played by GM Duda in a Titled Tuesday game, but it's a blunder.} 10. Kf1 $1 {[%csl Rb4,Rc6,Re7] Black's pieces are just awfully placed.} Na5 (10... Bxd2 11. Qxd2 {[%cal Ga1e1] White wins material.} Qc5 12. Qc3 $18 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc3g7] Perhaps even simpler.} (12. Qf4 $5 {[%cal Rc6e7,Gd5d6] Is one way.})) 11. d6 $1 {[%csl Gd6] A nice way to win a piece.} Qxd6 12. Qe1+ $1 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Re8][%cal Gd2b4] This is the point.}) 10. Qxd2 Ne7 11. O-O-O {For a pawn, White is very much ahead in development.} d6 12. h4 $1 {[%csl Bh4][%cal Gh4h5,Gh1h4] This is the key move for obtaining a nice position, White will simply gain maximum space on the kingside.} O-O {Black should castle short.} (12... Bg4 {[%csl Ra7,Rg4,Rg7][%cal Gd8d7] Might seem natural, for Black to not yet reveal which side he intends to castle, but the problem is that too many pieces are vulnerable.} 13. h5 $1 {A strong move.} Qd7 $1 $146 {The best.} (13... h6 $2 14. Rh4 $1 {[%csl Rg4,Gh4][%cal Gh4g4] We force Black to take on f3.} Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qd7 16. Re4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd1,Gd2,Ge4,Re8] Here we can see the display of maximum power of the White pieces.} O-O-O $4 17. Qe3 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra7,Re7][%cal Ge3a7,Ge4e7] With a double attack, and White wins.}) 14. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh5h6,Rd4a7,Re8c8] A strong move, played in Mamedyarov-Karjakin, Gashimov Memorial 2021. Castling long is out of the question for Black, and h6 is also a big threat.} (14. Rh4 {Black is in time to castle.} Bxf3 15. gxf3 O-O-O $13 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh4e4,Gd2e3] White misses the Qe3 double attack.}) 14... h6 {[%csl Gh6] Karjakin stopped the threat.} 15. Qxg7 $5 $146 {I think that White can afford to regain the material.} (15. Rde1 {This was Mamedyarov's move.} Kf8 16. Bb3 $5 $44 {Was an improvement, and White has full compensation.} (16. Nh4 $2 {Turned out to be unfortunate.} Bxh5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gh5] Black is two pawns up, and there are not a lot of threats.})) 15... O-O-O {Black is in time to castle.} 16. Rde1 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Rf7] A strong move, and it is very hard for Black to keep the position intact.} Bxf3 (16... Rdf8 $2 {Fails tactically.} 17. Rxe7 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rd7e7,Gg7g4] g4 drops.}) 17. gxf3 a6 $5 {Black should give up f7.} (17... Rdf8 {Very passive.} 18. Qf6 $16 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gc4f1,Gf1h3] Black's knight is in a lot of trouble.}) 18. Qxf7 $14 {But of course, White enjoys a safe advantage thanks to the extra pawn.}) (12... h6 {Will transpose into 12...0-0.} 13. h5 O-O {And we have the same position.}) 13. h5 h6 14. Rdg1 $1 {[%csl Bg1][%cal Gg2g4] This is the way White can continue the attack.} Bg4 $1 {The best move for Black.} (14... f5 $2 {[%csl Rc8,Rf5][%cal Rg2g4] Black stops g4 at all costs, but it's a very bad positional choice.} 15. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gg1e1,Gc1b1,Gc4b3] White has a very pleasant advantage.}) (14... c6 $2 {Was played in the game Van Foreest Jorden-Navara David, Charity Cup 2022, but this is simply losing.} 15. g4 $1 {The attack is too strong.} cxd5 16. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gg4g5] White is ready to go g5.} f6 {Necessary.} 17. Kb1 {[%cal Gb1a1,Ga2a3,Gd3b1,Gd2d3,Cf3h4,Cf3d4,Cf2f4,Cg4g5] White is just positionally winning, that's why Black must try to do something fast:} Nc6 {[%cal Gd8a5] Qa5 is a threat, so White can try the forcing:} 18. Bc2 $1 $18 {[%cal Gd2d3,Rd8a5] Qa5 is met with Qd3, Black is busted.}) 15. Rh4 Qd7 {Necessary.} (15... Bxf3 $2 {This is too dangerous.} 16. gxf3 $40 {[%csl Gg1,Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gh4g4] The attack is very scary.}) 16. Qf4 {The best move.} (16. Qd4 {Looks strong, but Black can hold on with:} f5 $1 {To keep the bishop on g4.} 17. Nh2 b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5,Rc4] A strong intermezzo.} 18. Bb3 Be2 $1 $13 {But this is of course very difficult to find.}) 16... Bxf3 {Was played in both of the games that reached this position.} (16... Bf5 {This is playable, but quite risky.} 17. g4 $1 Bh7 18. g5 {Black is lost if not for:} Qf5 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2] The tactical point.} 19. Qxf5 Nxf5 20. Re4 {[%cal Gg5g6] However in the endgame, Black still needs to be careful.} hxg5 21. Nxg5 $36 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gg5h7,Gc4d3,Be4c4,Be4a4,Be4b4] The bishop on h7 will fall, after which Bd3 and the rook can swing over to attack the pawns on the 7th rank.}) 17. gxf3 $1 {[%csl Gg1] Of course, White opens up the g-file for the rook.} Kh8 18. Rxg7 {This is the critical try.} (18. Rhg4 $5 $146 {This is a decent approach, we aim for a slow attack.} Qf5 $1 {[%csl Bf5] Black's key defence.} 19. Qe3 Qe5 $1 {But Black is probably fine, and White's attack is not really working.} 20. Re4 Qh2 $1 {[%csl Rg1] The point.} 21. Reg4 Qe5 $11 {Repetition.}) 18... Kxg7 19. Rg4+ Ng6 $1 {Only defense.} 20. Qd4+ {The forcing line follows with:} Kg8 $1 21. Bd3 Qe7 $3 {[%csl Ge7] An important move to find.} 22. Bxg6 Qe1+ 23. Kc2 Qe2+ 24. Kc1 Qe1+ $11 {Draw by repetition.}) (8... Bxd2+ {A rare move, but not challenging.} 9. Nxd2 $5 {To try to retain the pair of bishops.} Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Ne5 {We are following the game Kosteniuk-Oparin, 2022.} (10... Ne7 $2 {This is too passive.} 11. Bc3 $1 $40 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4] The pair of bishops are slicing the board.}) 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O $5 {Is probably the simplest, and an improvement over the game.} (12. f4 {This was the concrete try played by Kosteniuk.} Ng6 13. O-O d6 $2 {Is of course, just bad.} 14. f5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf5f6] Followed by f6, and Black has a sad defensive task ahead.}) 12... d6 13. Re1 $44 {[%cal Gd2c3,Ga1c1,Gd1b3,Ge2f1,Gh2h3] This is a typical scenario in this line, White has a very clear compensation for the missing pawn, and the play is so easy, that Black is the one who has to be careful, despite being a pawn up.}) 9. O-O {This is the main try.} (9. a3 $5 {This is an amusing try, we are basically inviting Black to play the 8...Bxd2 line, a tempo up.} Bxd2+ (9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 Ba5 $2 {A poor choice, played in Van Foreest J-Kosteniuk, 2022.} (10... Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 {Transposes to 9...Nxd2.}) 11. b4 Bb6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qg4 $18 {[%csl Rg8] White basically has a winning attack.}) 10. Nxd2 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] This is probably Black's best, but of course, difficult to play without knowledge.} (10... Nxd2 {Leads to a playable position for White:} 11. Bxd2 d6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 $44 {We will see something similar in the main line, but White for sure has full compensation.}) 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O d6 13. h3 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2] We reach the standard type of position, however the bishop is still on c1, so it means that White can develop with b4-Bb2:} Ng6 14. b4 $44 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gf1e1] Full compensation for White, Black can also play this, but it's for sure easier to come up with moves for White.}) 9... Nxd2 {The most logical move.} (9... Bxd2 10. Nxd2 $1 {[%csl Gc1] We recapture with the knight, to keep the c1 bishop on the board.} Nxd2 11. Bxd2 d6 {The game will develop naturally:} 12. Re1 O-O 13. Rc1 $36 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7,Rc7][%cal Gh2h3,Gd1b3,Ge1e3,Ge3g3] The compensation is through the roof, without needing to do something concrete, and in fact White won 5 out of 6 games that reached this position.}) (9... Nf6 $6 {Too passive.} 10. a3 Bd6 {White is better with a lot of moves, but I like:} (10... Bxd2 11. Bxd2 O-O 12. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Gc4,Gg5] White has a big initiative thanks to the pair of bishops.}) 11. Re1 $5 {[%cal Gd2e4] With the idea of Ne4.} O-O 12. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rd2,Gf6] We exchange Black's healthiest piece for our Nd2 which was not fantastic.} Nxe4 13. Rxe4 $36 {[%csl Rd6,Rg8][%cal Re7g6,Gh2h4] The bishop is misplaced, White can seriously start looking towards the kingside.}) 10. Nxd2 $1 {[%csl Gc1] We still want to keep as many pieces on the board.} O-O 11. a3 Ba5 $1 {This is probably Black's best move, but it's a very risky one, since it allows both d6 and b4.} (11... Bc5 $6 {Has been played in a few games, but it seems very counter intuitive to allow Ne4 with tempo.} 12. Ne4 d6 13. Nxc5 $5 {The most concrete reaction.} dxc5 14. b4 $36 {[%cal Gc1b2] As seen in Dubov-Karjakin, 2022, White has a very clear initiative.}) (11... Bxd2 {This is again the most played move, and it's what I like most about this line, we reach a standard scenario throughout all lines, and the tempi don't matter so much.} 12. Bxd2 d6 13. Re1 Ng6 14. Rc1 Bd7 15. h3 $5 $36 {Or any other solid move, it's just a playable, slightly more pleasant position for White.}) 12. d6 {This is the most principled.} (12. b4 Bb6 13. Bb2 d6 {[%csl Gb6] The point is that Black's bishop on b6 is well placed.} 14. Qh5 Bf5 $13 {[%cal Gf5g6] And it's unclear how White can try to apply any pressure.}) (12. Bd3 $5 $146 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2c4] This is a tricky option, to threaten Nc4.} d6 13. Nc4 Bb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 $11 {[%csl Gb6,Gb7,Gc7] And we reach a similar position as we have discussed in the previous lines, but Black's structure is more compact in this case.}) 12... cxd6 13. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8] For the moment we want to take advantage of Black's poor development.} d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Forced reaction.} 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 {The most logical, and it looks like Black is solving all of his problems.} (14... d6 $1 {This is probably Black's cleanest move.} 15. Bg5 h6 $1 16. Bh4 {Black must know:} Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7] A very strong prophylactic move.} 17. Nxd6 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Bd8 $1 {[%csl Bd8] The most accurate move.} (18... Bc7 $6 {Runs into:} 19. Nxc8 $1 {[%cal Rd7d5,Gc8e7] Using the tactic.} Qxc8 20. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gd5] White maintains the pressure thanks to the active pieces.}) 19. Bxd8 (19. Bg3 Bf6 $1 {And Black objectively equalized, but White can continue to play:} 20. Rab1 $132 {[%csl Rc8] The bishop still has to get out.}) 19... Rxd8 20. Rad1 $36 {This is also a safe way for a risk free initiative.}) 15. Qxd5 d6 16. Bg5 $5 {But I don't think that it is all 100% clear after:} Be6 17. Bxd8 Bxd5 18. Nf6+ $1 {Intermezzo.} gxf6 19. Bxa5 {[%csl Gc3,Rf6,Rh7][%cal Ga5c3,Gd1d3,Gd3h3,Gd3g3] The endgame seems quite drawish at first, but in fact, White can still apply pressure, for example:} Rfe8 (19... Bb3 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gb3c2,Gc2g6] This is the engine's recommendation.} 20. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga1a3] We can try the rook lift.} Rfe8 21. Ra3 {Anyway, the game continues:} Bc2 22. Rg3+ Bg6 23. Bc3 Re6 24. f3 $36 {[%cal Gg3g4] There is no immediate draw as long as you keep rooks on board, and if you are the better player, you can for sure outplay your opponents.}) 20. Bc3 Kg7 21. Rfd1 Bc6 22. Rd3 Re6 23. Rg3+ Kf8 24. f3 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rc6g2,Gg3g4,Gg3h3] A very nice move to block the diagonal. Black has no counterplay.} Rae8 25. Rh3 $36 {[%cal Ga1d1] With simple play, and White can keep on improving.} *

