{[%evp 0,45,24,23,29,29,13,20,9,-28,-5,-25,-36,-21,-57,-50,-47,-55,-56,-66,-25,-36,-30,-56,-23,-39,-29,-5,-7,0,-25,-38,-20,-28,-27,-27,-50,-42,-29,-27,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-52]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. Ng5 $5 {[%csl Gg5] This is a risk free alternative for White. The theory is quite concrete, so it can become unpleasant for Black, because he needs to remember a lot, just to equalize.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] Only move.} (5... Ne5 $2 {This is a mistake.} 6. Nxf7 $1 {[%csl Bf7] Typical tactic and White will reach a much better version compared to the main line:} Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ {[%csl Rc5,Rf7][%cal Gh5c5,Gh5f7] The point.} g6 9. Qxc5 $16 {[%csl Gc6,Rg8] Black has a knight on g8 compared to having a knight on c6.}) (5... d5 $2 {No sense.} 6. Bxd5 $16 {White is much better.}) 6. Nxf7 {White uses the standard tactical resource:} Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ {[%csl Rc5,Rf7,Gh5][%cal Gh5c5,Gh5f7] This is the point.} g6 {Main move.} (8... Kg8 {doesn't have independent value.} 9. Qd5+ $1 {[%csl Bd5] Intermezzo.} (9. Qxc5 $6 {[%csl Rc5] Don't take on c5 now.} h6 $1 $11 {[%csl Bh7][%cal Gg8h7] The king has a nice square on h7.}) 9... Kf8 10. Qxc5+ {See under 8...Kf8.}) (8... Kf8 9. Qxc5+ d6 {Most logical.} (9... Qe7 $6 {Black wants to enter a safe endgame, but it's quite passive.} 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. O-O $1 {[%csl Gg1] This is an improvement.} (11. Bg5+ $6 {This check was used in the majority of games, but it's a bit premature.} Kf7 12. O-O h6 $1 {Black gets counterplay with tempo.} 13. Bh4 Re8 14. f3 d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] To open the position.} 15. exd5 Nb4 $11 {Equal endgame.}) 11... d6 $1 {Best move.} (11... h6 $6 {[%cal Rc1g5] Black prevent Bg5, but it's quite slow.} 12. Rd1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gb1a3,Ga3b5] White can target the pawn on d4.} d6 13. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rd4] White has a big advantage, around +1.} (13. b3 $16 {[%csl Rd4] also fine.})) 12. Bg5+ $5 {[%csl Od6] It's a good time to do it, since Black commited the pawn on d6 (no d5 in one tempo).} Kf7 13. c3 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3] White wants to develop the knight on the dream square.} h6 (13... dxc3 $6 14. Nxc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Rc7][%cal Gc3d5,Ga1c1] White has big pressure against the c7 pawn.}) 14. Bf4 Be6 15. Rd1 dxc3 16. Nxc3 $14 {[%csl Cc3,Rc7,Cd1,Cf4][%cal Ga1c1] Equal material, but for the engine this is real pressure, +0.50, that's why this line is not popular.}) 10. Qb5 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb5h5] The strongest square for the queen, controlling the 5th rank.} (10. Qc4 $6 {was tried in most of the games, but Black has a strong reaction:} Qh4 $1 {[%csl Re4] To target e4.} 11. Nd2 Qg5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rg2] g2 is weak.} 12. O-O $2 {is not possible, because of:} Bh3 $19 {[%csl Rg2] Black wins material.}) 10... Qe8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] The best way to activate the queen.} (10... Qh4 11. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Rh4g5] The point behind 10.Qb5.}) (10... Qe7 11. Nd2 Qe5 12. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Ge1g1] White has the better structure and the better pieces.}) (10... a6 11. Qe2 {[%csl Ce2] The queen is well placed on e2.} h6 12. O-O Kg8 13. c3 $1 $14 {[%csl Cc3][%cal Gc3d4,Gb1c3] Typical move to develop the knight to c3, White has an advantage.}) 11. f3 $1 {[%csl Gf3] Good defense.} (11. Nd2 $2 {is bad due to:} Qg6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rg2] And again White has problems with the g2 pawn.}) 11... Qe5 {[%csl Ge5] Black improves the queen.} (11... Qg6 $6 {doesn't lead anywhere.} 12. O-O Bh3 $6 13. Rf2 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Bf2] Big difference for White to have a pawn on f3.}) 12. Na3 $5 {I like including this move, since anyway Black cannot capture on b5.} (12. Qd3 $5 $14 {Decent alternative.}) 12... a6 13. Qd3 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Ga3c4] For the engine, with or without the inclusion, the evaluation is the same.} Be6 {Black's best.} (13... d5 14. O-O Kf7 15. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd3b3,Ga1e1] The king is still in a strange spot.}) 14. O-O Ke8 $1 {[%csl Cd7][%cal Ge8d7] This is the point, the king belongs to d7 in the long term.} 15. b3 d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] This is the way engine is playing, but of course, for a human it's incredible to understand that BEFORE opening the e-file, Black must voluntarily place the king on the e-file!} (15... Kd7 $2 {Immediately is bad.} 16. Bb2 $40 {[%csl Rd4] Troubles with the pawn.}) 16. exd5 (16. Re1 Kf7 $1 $13 {[%csl Gf7] The king runs to f7 now, because the rook is not on the f-file. Fantastic stuff!}) 16... Qxd5 17. Bf4 Kd7 {Still, after all these strong moves, White keeps some small initiative:} 18. Nc4 Rae8 19. Rfe1 Bf5 20. Qd2 Kc8 {[%csl Gc8] After 20 moves, finally Black's king is safe on c8.} 21. c3 (21. Bg3 $5 {[%cal Gd2f4] Possible as well, to keep queens on the board.}) 21... Qc5 22. cxd4 Qxd4+ 23. Qxd4 Nxd4 24. Kf2 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4] /=. For the engine, this is +0.20, so it's not too much, but White can easily advance the pawns on the kingside, while Black can't do the same, since the king on c8 can become vulnerable.}) 9. Qxc5 {Up to this point, the variation is forced. Now Black can choose.} (9. Qd5+ $2 {No need to include this check.} Kg7 $15 {[%csl Bg7] Black's king is much better on g7 than f7.}) 9... d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Black's most concrete and critical move, every strong player is using it.} (9... d6 {Most common move, not a bad one, but here the game continues and White keeps a certain pressure.} 10. Qc4+ (10. Qb5 $6 {Main move, but not a great one.} Re8 $1 {[%csl Re4] Black is immediately fine.} 11. O-O (11. Nd2 d5 $15) 11... Rxe4 $1 12. Qd5+ Re6 13. Nd2 Kg7 14. Nf3 Qf6 $44 {White has some compensation, but no more, maximum for equality.}) 10... Be6 {Critical.} (10... Kg7 $6 {Slow move.} 11. O-O Re8 12. f3 Be6 13. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb1d2,Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Positionally better.}) 11. Qe2 Qf6 {The best, to fight against White's development.} (11... Kg7 $6 {Common, but not great.} 12. O-O Rf8 13. b3 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc1b2,Gb1d2] The king often times will be misplaced.}) (11... Re8 12. O-O d5 {Logical try, but White can support the center with:} (12... Qf6 {transposes to 11...Qf6.}) (12... Kg8 13. Bf4 $14) 13. f3 $1 {[%csl Gf1,Gf3,Rf7][%cal Gf3e4] To open up the f-file for the rook.} Kg8 (13... dxe4 14. fxe4+ Kg8 15. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Yg6,Rg7,Rh6] The g6 move is a long term weakening, the dark squares are extremely vulnerable, White can also think about setting up a mating net.}) 14. Bf4 {[%cal Gb1d2]} dxe4 15. fxe4 $14 {[%csl Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gb1d2] Slightly better for White.}) 12. O-O Rhe8 $1 {[%cal Gf7g8] The best, with idea of Kg8.} (12... Rhf8 $6 13. Bh6 $1 $16 {[%csl Gh6] Useful tempo.}) (12... Kg7 13. b3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1b2] Once again, the bishop gets to the long diagonal.} d3 $2 14. cxd3 $16 {[%cal Rf6a1,Gc1b2] White won a pawn.}) 13. Nd2 $146 {This is a new position, and it's the critical one of the 9...d6 line.} Kg8 $1 {[%csl Gg8] The correct square.} (13... Kg7 $6 {[%csl Rg7] This is the wrong square, and it can be seen in the critical line:} 14. f4 a5 15. a3 a4 16. Rf2 Ra5 17. Nf1 Rc5 18. Ng3 {[%cal Rf6g7] Black doesn't have Qg7.} Qe7 19. Bd2 $1 Rxc2 {fails to:} 20. f5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd2h6] Followed by Bh6 tactic, that's why, the king stays better on g8.}) 14. a3 $5 {[%cal Rc6b4] Since White can't make progress concretely, we switch to positional play.} (14. f4 {is not so great now:} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] Good move to gain space.} 15. a3 a4 16. Rf2 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] White's idea is to improve the knight to g3.} Ra5 17. Nf1 Rc5 18. Ng3 {Visually, the position is equal, but it's only equal, because Black can move away the queen.} Qe7 $11 (18... Qg7 $11) 19. Bd2 $2 Rxc2 $1 $40 {[%csl Rg7,Cg8] And it's a big improvement to have the king on g8.}) 14... d5 15. f3 Bf7 16. Qd3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gf1f2] White has some pressure, for the engine it's +0.25, but the most important is that Black didn't kill the game.}) (9... Qe7 $6 {This is similar to the 8...Kf8 endgame.} 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 (10... Kxe7 11. O-O $14 {[%csl Rg6] I don't believe that g6 is such an useful move for Black, since it weakens the dark squares after all.}) 11. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3] Typical move.} dxc3 12. Nxc3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge1g1] White is better in the endgame.}) 10. O-O {Necessary to finish development.} (10. Qxd5+ $2 {Common mistake!} Qxd5 11. exd5 Nb4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5] Black is just better.}) 10... dxe4 {[%csl Bd4,Be4][%cal Gh8e8] Black needs just one extra move, and he would have a fantastic position, that's why White should act fast.} 11. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] White must urgently dismantle Black's strong pawn center.} (11. Bf4 $6 {too slow.} Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7f5,Gf5g4] Qf5 or Qg4 next, and Black has a promising initiative.} 12. Qg5 Qg4 13. Qh6 Qh5 $1 14. Qxh5 gxh5 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gc8f5] Very good for Black.}) 11... Qd6 $1 {This is universally known as Black's safest option.} (11... Be6 {was played in the game Grischuk-Karjakin, 2018.} 12. cxd4 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3] We can open the c3 square the knight.} Qxd4 13. Qg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5h6] The queen can be annoying.} Qe5 14. Qh6 $36 {[%cal Gb1c3] +0.30 evaluation.}) (11... Re8 12. cxd4 Nxd4 (12... Qxd4 {is once again met with:} 13. Qg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Strong move, to keep queens on the board.} Kg8 14. Nc3 Bf5 15. Bf4 Qg7 16. Nd5 Rf8 17. Qh4 Rf7 18. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6] White has a big advantage, thanks to the dark squares.}) 13. Be3 $1 {[%csl Ce3] Critical try, played by GM Azarov against GM Ragger, a few years ago.} (13. Nc3 $6 {was played in the game Kovalev-Kramnik, Dortmund 2018, but Black had a strong idea in mind.} b6 14. Qc4+ Be6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5] And Kramnik had a pleasant position.}) 13... Nf5 14. Nc3 c6 15. Rfe1 {White slowly improved the position, and Black soon ended in up in a much worse position:} Qe7 16. Qc4+ Be6 17. Qxe4 Kg8 {Equal material, but White can ask unpleasant questions:} 18. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Bd2] Strong prophylactic.} Qf7 (18... Bf7 19. Qxe7 Rxe7 20. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2c3] The bishop is transfered to c3, White has a big advantage.}) 19. Qf4 Rad8 20. f3 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Rf5d4,Gf4h4] This is another super deep move by the engine, to have the rook protected in the critical line:} Nd4 21. Qh4 Nc2 22. Bg5 Nxe1 23. Rxe1 $40 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4e1,Gc3e4,Ge4f6] The point of Qh4.} Bf5 $4 {was strong with a pawn on f2, now it loses material.} 24. Bxd8 $18 {[%cal Gh4e1] White is a piece up.}) (11... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Rc5g5] This is a logical move, to develop the bishop and stop White's future Qg5.} 12. cxd4 Qxd4 13. Qb5 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb5b7] We can get a tempo on the pawn.} Qd6 $1 {Best move shown by the engine.} (13... Qb4 $6 {was tried in some games, but White can use a neat trick:} 14. Qd5+ $1 {[%csl Gd5] Cool intermezzo.} Be6 15. Qg5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gg5h6] The queen gets to the beloved g5 square, with play on the dark squares.}) 14. Nc3 (14. Be3 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 14... Nd4 15. Qc4+ {The position is still very tense, for example:} Be6 16. Qa4 Bd7 17. Qa5 {[%csl Ga5] Some deep queen maneuvers.} Bc6 18. Be3 $132 {[%cal Ga5g5] Playable position.}) 12. Qxd6 cxd6 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Nc3 {White is down a pawn but aims to recapture the pawn on e4, giving White a better pawn structure.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] The strongest move, and I also recommended it from the Black side. Black is threatening Ne2+, followed by an exchange of knights.} (14... Re8 $2 {Wrong move.} 15. Be3 Nf5 {Kovalev-Mamedyarov, 2022.} 16. Nd5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Ra8,Gd5,Re8][%cal Gd5c7,Ge3a7] Strong improvement, and Black has concrete problems.} (16. Nb5 $6 {was played in the game, but it was quite unfortunate.} Re7 $1 $13 {[%csl Ge7]})) (14... Nc2 15. Rb1 Be6 {was played in the game Beerdsen-Pasztor, EU-ch 2023.} 16. Bh6 Bc4 17. Rfd1 Bd3 $2 {Black went for seemingly a logical setup, but it's close to over.} 18. f3 $1 {[%csl Bf3] Strong move.} Nd4 19. fxe4 Bxb1 20. Rxd4 $18 {[%csl Rb1] The bishop is trapped.} Bxa2 (20... Bc2 21. Rd2 $18) 21. Nxa2 Rhd8 22. Nc3 $18 {White converted without problems.}) (14... Bf5 {Second most common move.} 15. Bh6 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1] Strong development.} Rad8 16. Rad1 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5] The best place for the knight.} (16... Ne6 $2 {The knight is very bad here.} 17. f3 $1 exf3 18. Rxf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg2g4] There are some concrete issues for Black.} Ke8 19. Nd5 $18 {Karacsonyi-Nemitz, Basel 2024. White is crushing.}) 17. f3 $1 {This leads to a safer position.} (17. h3 {was played in the game Gilevich-Brunello, ITA-ch 2020.} Rhe8 $1 $146 {Improvement.} (17... d5 $6 18. Nxd5 $14 {White was better.}) 18. Bg5 Rd7 19. g4 d5 $3 {[%csl Bd5] Super strong piece sacrifice, that's why 17.h3 is also a good attempt.} (19... Be6 $2 {is bad.} 20. Nxe4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Rf6][%cal Ge4d6,Ge4f6] Just game over.}) 20. gxf5 gxf5 {Black has full compensation, but it's not easy to understand in a real game.} 21. Kh1 d4 22. Ne2 Rg8 23. Bc1 d3 24. Nf4 {Black however should still mantain accuracy.} Rgd8 $1 25. b3 Nd4 26. Be3 Nf3 27. Ra1 $1 {[%csl Ga2,Ra7][%cal Rd8a8] To target the a7 pawn.} a6 28. Rfc1 $13 {[%cal Gc1c4] +0.30 evaluation, but it's tough to say that one side is better.}) 17... exf3 18. Rxf3 Ne5 19. Rff1 Ke6 20. h3 a6 21. Nd5 $14 {The evaluation is +0.50, so White can for sure continue to put pressure, this is not an equal endgame.}) 15. Nxe4 Nc2 $1 16. Nxd6+ {The main try.} (16. f3 $6 {This is slightly risky for White.} Nxa1 17. fxg4+ Ke6 $36 {White certainly has compensation, but not more than that, and the extra exchange could eventually become decisive. Our knight on a1 will escape via c2.}) (16. Rb1 $6 {runs into:} Be2 $1 $15 {[%csl Gc2,Ge2,Rf1] This is Black's point.}) 16... Ke6 17. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] We want to enter an endgame with opposite colored bishops.} Nxa1 {The most logical.} (17... Rhf8 18. Bg3 Nxa1 19. Rxa1 {transposes to the main line.}) (17... g5 18. Bg3 (18. Rae1+ $5 $146 {deserves attention.} Nxe1 19. Rxe1+ Kd7 20. Be5 Rhf8 21. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4f6] looks dangerous for Black, but he is just in time:} Rae8 $1 {[%cal Ge4f6,Rf8f6] To stop Nf6.} 22. Bg7 $1 {Intermezzo.} Rf7 23. Nf6+ Rxf6 24. Rxe8 Re6 25. Rxe6 Bxe6 $11 {Black makes a draw in this pawn down endgame.}) 18... Nxa1 19. Rxa1 {This was played in the game Mamedov-So, 2023.} Rhd8 20. f3 Bf5 21. Re1+ Kf6 22. h4 h6 $11 {Basically it's no improvement for White and no improvement for Black.}) 18. Rxa1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ra8c8,Rc8c7,Rh8e8,Rh8g8,Rg8g7] Unlike the 16.f3 variation, here White has an extra pawn for the exchange and a more stable position. For now it's equal, but statistically, White wins 1 time out 4 this endgame.} Rhf8 {The main move.} (18... g5 19. Re1+ Kd5 {We can follow the game Guseinov-Amin, 2024.} (19... Kd7 20. Be5 Rhf8 {Guseinov-Wagner, 2024.} 21. Ne4 Rae8 22. Bg7 Rf7 23. Bh6 $5 $14 {Maybe White can try to create chances like this.}) 20. Bg3 Kc6 $6 {Black played this innocent move, but White is better here:} 21. f3 Bh5 22. Rc1+ Kd5 23. Ne4 Bg6 24. Rc5+ Ke6 25. Nxg5+ {[%csl Gg5] Of course, with two pawns, White is a real favorite.} Ke7 26. Rc7+ Kf6 27. Bh4 Rhc8 28. Rxb7 Rc2 29. Nxh7+ Ke6 30. Ng5+ Kd5 {And here came the decisive point:} 31. g4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] Strong improvement and White has a winning advantage:} (31. h3 {was played, but after:} Re8 $1 $11 {[%cal Ge8e2] Black had sufficient counterplay.}) 31... Re8 32. Bf2 Ree2 33. Nh3 $1 $18 {[%csl Cf2,Ch3] Cute defensive setup.} Red2 34. Rxa7 Rxb2 35. Kg2 Ke5 36. a4 $18 {Just lost, Black has no counterplay.}) (18... b6 {Playable, but White can try the concrete:} 19. Re1+ Kd7 20. Nf7 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rg4,Rh8][%cal Gf7e5,Gf7h8] With a double threat.} Rhe8 21. Ne5+ Ke6 22. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c3] Strong maneuver.} Bf5 23. Nxg6+ Kd6 24. Bb4+ Kd5 25. Ne7+ Kc4 26. Bc3 Bb1 27. a3 $14 {[%eval 60,0] advantage.}) (18... Rhg8 $6 {too slow.} 19. Re1+ Kd7 20. Nxb7 $14 {[%csl Gb7]}) 19. Bg3 b6 {Black's best strategy is to just wait.} 20. f3 $5 {White should also take it slow and steady.} (20. h3 {This is another plan, to try to achieve g4.} Bf5 21. Re1+ Kd7 22. Rd1 Ke6 23. Bh2 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] This is the point of h3.} h5 24. Bg3 $5 $36 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg3f2,Gg2g4] No need to hurry, maybe your opponent will start feeling pressure, since White has a long term idea.} (24. f3 {allows:} h4 $1 $132 {[%csl Gh4] which can be annoying.})) 20... Bf5 21. Re1+ $5 Kd7 22. Rd1 {Repeat once.} Ke6 23. h4 $132 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge1d1] Then you can repeat once again and play Kf2, White is not risking and can play on forever, waiting for Black to make a mistake.} *

