{[%evp 0,51,20,17,17,17,23,4,2,-19,-11,-19,10,10,22,22,22,-18,44,41,26,23,23,45,11,37,50,37,50,65,43,36,50,15,22,9,26,49,50,57,57,56,51,51,65,24,26,23,16,21,13,23,7,7]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. O-O Nf6 {This is the historical main line, with more than 5000 games played. This is also one of my favorite childhood lines, as I have been playing it with White from 2009 to 2013, and in the last game of a tournament during that period, I managed to win with it, and with this become an FM. With that being said, I was very surprised to see how theory has changed and evolved since then, so I have several new and interesting things to share with you here.} 6. e5 d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Black's best move, by far.} (6... Ne4 $4 {This has been played in around 300 games, but it's a huge mistake.} 7. Qe2 $18 {[%csl Re4] or Re1, and the knight is lost.}) (6... Ng4 $6 {900 games, but also not advisable.} 7. Bf4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3] White defends e5 and h3 is a big threat.} d6 {The main try.} (7... O-O {Already quite sad.} 8. h3 Nh6 9. Bxh6 gxh6 10. c3 $36 {White at the very least has a nice initiative, and a +0.70 evaluation.}) 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Re1+ $1 {[%csl Re8] An annoying check.} Be7 {The best option.} (9... Kf8 $6 {[%csl Rf8] The king is simply misplaced on f8.} 10. Bxd6+ Qxd6 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] We can play for development.} Bf5 {Black stops Ne4.} 12. b4 $5 $16 {[%csl Rf8] The engine's top move, the evaluation is more than +1.} (12. h3 {A solid positional move.} Nf6 13. Bb5 $16 {[%cal Gd2b3,Yd2c4] White has the advantage.}) (12. Ne4 $2 Bxe4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Black's idea.} 13. Rxe4 Nf6 $11 {Black is fine.})) (9... Ne7 $2 {This is bad.} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qe2 $1 $146 {[%csl Re8][%cal Re8g8] A typical move, to stop Black from castling.} Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qb5+ $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rh5][%cal Gb5b7,Gb5h5] White has two major threats, and it's just game over.}) 10. h3 Nf6 11. Bb5 {White can play positionally:} O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7] White is better due to the superior pawn structure.}) 7. exf6 dxc4 8. Re1+ {This is the main line.} (8. fxg7 {This has also been played from time to time.} Rg8 9. Bg5 {White wants to develop without Re1+, but it's a neccesary move, and you don't gain too much by starting with this.} (9. Re1+ {transposes to 8.Re1.} Be6 10. Bg5 {But if you want to go for this, then it is better to start with 8.Re1, in my opinion.}) 9... f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] The best move.} (9... Be7 {Black can transpose to the main line if he wishes.} 10. Bxe7 Kxe7 11. Re1+ Kf6 $5 {An extra option.} (11... Be6 {Transposes to 8.Re1.})) 10. Re1+ Kf7 11. Bh6 {White defends the passed pawn and was tried in the legendary game: Short-Fressinet, at the Olympiad in 2010, where White won in less than 30 moves, but Black has a strong reply:} (11. Ne5+ $5 {Is a concrete line, but it leads only to a draw by repetition:} Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Bd6 $1 13. Qh5+ {White will give checks:} Kxg7 14. Qh6+ Kf7 15. Qxh7+ Rg7 16. Qh5+ Rg6 17. Qh7+ $11 {Draw by repetition.}) 11... Re8 $1 {[%csl Be8] An improvement over the game.} 12. Nbd2 Rxe1+ 13. Nxe1 Kg6 $1 {[%csl Bg6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Rg6h6] Black attacks the bishop with his king.} 14. Bf4 Qd5 $1 15. Nxc4 Kxg7 $11 {An interesting, but equal position.} (15... Qxc4 $4 {A huge blunder.} 16. Qd3+ $1 {[%csl Rc4,Gd3,Rg6][%cal Gg7g8] Nice deflection.} Qxd3 17. g8=Q+ $18 {[%cal Gc2d3] White wins the queen.})) 8... Be6 {The most common, by far.} (8... Kf8 $6 {Has been tried in 125 games, but it's a dubious move.} 9. Nbd2 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Rd2c4,Gd2e4] The engine evaluates this as +0.60, but over the board it is even more unpleasant for Black, since he needs to find several good moves:} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Bf5] The best, but with no guarantees.} 10. Ne4 Bxe4 11. fxg7+ Kxg7 12. Rxe4 {[%cal Ge4g4] White is ready to swing the rook over.} h5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bh5] The only move for Black, to control g4 and h6.} (12... Qd7 $4 {Seemingly natural, but it's a losing mistake.} 13. Bh6+ $3 {[%csl Bh6] Black can already resign.} Kxh6 14. Qd2+ $1 $18 {[%cal Gd2g5,Gg5c5] This is the point.}) 13. Nh4 Qf6 $1 {Necessary.} 14. Rf4 Qe6 $1 15. Bd2 {White can finish development:} Rae8 16. Qf3 Ne5 {The best line continues with:} 17. Qg3+ Ng6 18. Nf5+ Kf8 19. Rf3 h4 20. Qg5 Rh7 21. Nxh4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gg5c5] Black must continue to show accuracy.}) 9. fxg7 {My main recommendation.} (9. Ng5 {The old main line, and how I used to play this line back in the day.} g6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] These days the engines immediately solve all of Black's problems with this strong move.} (9... Qd5 $6 {This was how the theory continued, before engines were strong.} 10. Nc3 Qf5 11. Nce4 O-O-O $6 {The old main line, but for any decent engine nowadays, this is unplayable:} 12. g4 $1 $16 {[%csl Bg4] The key move, and White is much better.} (12. Nxc5 $2 {Is what I was being taught to play when I was a kid, but it's a mistake.} Qxc5 13. Rxe6 {With today's engines, White is worse after:} fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qe5 15. Nxd8 Rxd8 16. fxg7 Qxg7 $15 {But it's amusing to see how things change over time.})) (9... Qxf6 $4 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qh5+ $18) 10. Qf3 O-O 11. Rxe6 $1 {Necessary.} fxe6 12. f7+ $1 {Here begins the line with a series of only moves for both sides.} Kh8 13. Nxe6 Qe7 14. Bg5 Qxf7 15. Nxc5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bc5] White must enter the endgame with doubled pawns.} (15. Qxf7 $2 {Was played in all 9 games that has reached this position, but it's a mistake.} Rxf7 16. Nxc5 Re8 17. Nd2 Kg7 $1 $15 {The only move for an advantage, and Black is better.} 18. c3 Re2 $1 $40 {[%csl Rd2,Rf2] This is the point.}) 15... Qxf3 16. gxf3 Rxf3 {The endgame is unusual and complicated, but objectively balanced for the engine.} (16... Rae8 17. Nd2 {Compared to 15.Qxf7, White has an improved version, since after:} Kg7 18. c3 Re2 19. Kf1 $1 $13 {[%csl Bf1,Gf2,Gf3] Thanks to the pawn on f3, Black is not able to capture on f2.}) (16... Ne5 {This is also fine, if Black just wants to equalize.} 17. Nd2 Nxf3+ 18. Nxf3 Rxf3 $11 {With a pair of knights off the board, it's a bit easier to understand what's going on.}) 17. Nd2 Rf5 18. Nce4 Kg7 19. c3 Re8 20. cxd4 Nxd4 $11 {An interesting endgame, White is not worse, so you might keep it as a blitz/rapid weapon.}) 9... Rg8 10. Bg5 {The starting position. If Black is not prepared, you will have a nice time playing this line, since it is very easy to go wrong. In my childhood, I won a lot of games here.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Be7] The critical move.} (10... Qd5 $4 {This is a terrible move, and a famous trap where many of my previous opponents fell into.} 11. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3,Gd1,Rd5,Re8][%cal Rd4c3] A key tempo, the knight is immune, due to the pin.} Qf5 12. Ne4 Be7 {Black doesn't lose the queen, but it is still a hopeless position.} (12... Rxg7 13. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rf5g4,Rf5d5,Ge4f6] The queen is trapped, since anywhere it goes there is the Nf6+ fork.}) 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 $18 {[%csl Cg7] White is defending the g7 pawn, and mate is soon to come.}) (10... Qd7 $6 {This move doesn't lose on the spot, but it is still a sad way to play.} 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Ge4f6] The knight aims towards the f6-square.} Rxg7 12. Ne4 Be7 {Necessary.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 (13... Kxe7 14. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2f4] Compared to the main line, White has an improved version.}) 14. Nxd4 Rd8 {The best according to the engine, but the endgame is for sure unpleasant:} 15. Nxc6 Rxd1 16. Nxe7 {[%eval 55,0]} Rxa1 17. Rxa1 Kxe7 18. Re1 $14 {[%csl Ge4,Rf7,Rh7][%cal Ge4g3,Gf2f4,Gg1f2,Gg3f1,Gf1e3,Gh2h3,Gg2g4] The engine shows +0.60, but White has a risk free endgame, with a mobile kingside, and a perfect knight.}) 11. Bxe7 {[%cal Cd8e7,Ce8e7] Both recaptures are objectively fine for Black, but the positions are so messy in the end, that it's tough to say which one is the best.} Kxe7 {[%csl Cd4] I think this is more ambitious, since Black keeps the d4 pawn protected.} (11... Qxe7 {The safer move, Black gives up the d4-pawn immediately.} 12. Nxd4 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Bd8][%cal Rd8d1] The best, to avoid Nxc6.} (12... O-O-O $2 {The second most common move, but it's a blunder.} 13. Nxc6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc8,Re7][%cal Gc6e7,Re7c8] Threatening the queen with check.} bxc6 (13... Rxd1 $2 14. Nxe7+ $18 {[%csl Rc8,Ge7] The point.}) 14. Qf3 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Rc8,Gf3] The king is too weak.}) 13. c3 {We defend the knight.} Nxd4 (13... Rxg7 14. Nxe6 $5 {[%csl Be6] The best chance, I believe.} (14. Qf3 {Similar to the main line.} Nxd4 15. cxd4 $11 {Objectively a balanced position, but White can try this.}) 14... Rxd1 {Critical.} (14... fxe6 {Possible, but quite sad.} 15. Qh5+ Rg6 16. Na3 Rd5 {We can follow the engine's preferred line:} 17. Qe2 Qh4 18. Qe4 $1 {[%csl Ge4] A good defensive move.} Qxe4 19. Rxe4 b5 20. Rae1 Kf7 21. R4e2 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rh7] It's clear that White has an edge in the endgame.}) 15. Nxg7+ Kf8 16. Rxd1 Kxg7 {For the engine, this is fine, but I am not sure how many will be ready to play this OTB with Black, as one wrong move, and the evaluation might sky-rocket.} 17. Nd2 {Sample line:} (17. Na3 $14) 17... Qe2 $1 {[%csl Ge2] Key idea.} 18. Rab1 Ne5 19. Nf1 b5 20. Rd2 Qg4 21. Ng3 Nd3 $11 {[%csl Bd3] The engine places a knight on d3 and objectively it's balanced.}) 14. cxd4 Rxg7 15. Nc3 {[%csl Bc3] The knight is able to develop on the dream square.} Kf8 {Best, according to the engine.} (15... c6 {A human move, it has been played by GM Shirov.} 16. Re4 $14 {[%cal Gd1f3,Ga1e1,Yd1d2] In both the engine and human opinion, White is slightly better.} (16. b3 $5 $146 {An interesting novelty.}) (16. g3 $5 $146 {A useful prophylactic move.}) 16... Kf8 17. Qd2 Qg5 18. f4 Qg6 19. Rae1 $132 {Playable, but if it's White to move, then after Qf2 it's winning for some reason, and this means that it's difficult to understand for with Black.}) (15... Qg5 $2 {A bad move.} 16. g3 $1 $16 {[%csl Bg3] And this move is more useful than Black's Qg5.}) 16. Qf3 {This is my main recommendation, as seen in the game Jovanovic-Jovanic, CRO-ch 2010.} (16. g3 {[%csl Bg3] A typical move, but Black has a strong idea:} Rg4 $1 $146 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rg4d4] A strong move to target the d4-pawn, and a playable position, but objectively balanced.}) 16... c6 (16... Rxd4 17. Qxb7 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc4,Rc7] White should be more than happy to play against the ruined structure.}) 17. Re4 Rg6 18. Rae1 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] The best.} (18... Qd6 $2 {Was played in the aforementioned game, but it's a mistake.} 19. h4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4h5] An improvement, White can bother the rook.}) (18... Kg7 $6 {Bad for the same reasons.} 19. h4 $36 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] The rook is uncomfortable.}) 19. Rf4 Qg7 20. Qe4 $1 $146 {[%csl Od4][%cal Ye4d4] White protects the d4-pawn.} Kg8 21. g3 {Typical, and Black really must find an unhuman move:} h6 $3 {[%csl Bh6] This is a very strong prophylactic move, as you can see the reason in the line below:} (21... Z0 22. h4 {If it's White to move again, the attack might develop really fast:} Rg4 23. Qf3 Rxd4 24. Ne4 Rxf4 25. Qxf4 {[%cal Ge4f6] Nf6 is a big threat.} Kh8 {With a pawn on h6, this is fine, but here it loses.} 26. Qb8+ $1 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Rh8h7] The point.} Qg8 27. Qe5+ $1 Qg7 28. Nf6 $1 $18 {[%csl Bf6] And White wins.}) 22. Qe3 $5 $36 {[%cal Gc3e4] White can still play on, but of course, I cannot crush 1.e4 e5, the engine is very strong in defence.} (22. h4 Rg4 23. Qf3 Rxd4 24. Ne4 Rxf4 25. Qxf4 Kh8 $11 {[%cal Gf4b8,Rh8h7] An equal position, only due to the fact that Black has Kh7 after Qb8+.})) 12. Re4 $1 {[%csl Rb1,Rd4] We attack d4, to be able to develop the knight to the nice c3-square.} f5 $1 {The most critical move.} (12... d3 {Statistically, the most common move.} 13. Nc3 $5 {This is more ambitious, to fight for a large advantage.} (13. Nbd2 {Safe and solid option.} dxc2 14. Qxc2 Qd3 $1 {[%csl Bd3] Not a difficult move, but Black needs to find it.} 15. Qa4 {The best try.} a6 $1 $146 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ra4b5] The best move for Black, to stop Qb5 and prepare b5.} (15... Rxg7 {A very natural move, but after:} 16. Qb5 $1 $18 {[%csl Bb5] White has a winning advantage.}) 16. Rae1 Rxg7 17. R4e3 b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] Key defensive idea.} 18. Rxd3 bxa4 19. Nxc4 Rd8 20. Rc3 $14 {[%csl Ra4,Ra6,Rc7,Rf7,Rh7] Objectively, the endgame is holdable for Black, but it's quite disgusting to have this position over the board. Every pawn is isolated and a potential target.}) 13... Rxg7 14. Re3 $1 {[%csl Rd3] Pressuring the d3 pawn.} Nb4 $1 $146 {[%csl Gb4] Necessary move.} (14... dxc2 $2 {Was tried in all 3 games that reached this position, but it's a mistake.} 15. Qxc2 $16 {White has a big advantage.} Kf8 {One game continued in a very natural manner:} 16. Rd1 Qf6 17. Ne4 Qf5 18. Qc1 $1 $18 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Ge4g3,Ge3e4] Strong move, unpinning, and preparing Ng3-Re4. White has a +2 advantage.}) 15. cxd3 Nxd3 16. Ne1 {Straight-forward try.} (16. g3 $5 {Deserves attention as well.} Nxb2 17. Qb1 Nd3 18. Qxb7 Rb8 19. Qxa7 Ra8 {Black repeats the moves, though it's not over yet:} 20. Qb7 Rb8 21. Qa6 $5 {White can play for more.} Kf8 $1 {[%csl Gf8] Good move.} 22. Ne1 Qd4 23. Nxd3 Qxc3 24. Rc1 Qd4 25. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Rf8] Complicated position, but White is slightly better.}) 16... Nxe1 17. Qxe1 Kf8 {The line is very instructive:} 18. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Rd8f6] Critical, to stop Black from playing Qf6.} (18. g3 {allows:} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] And with an active queen, Black is in time to equalize.} 19. Ne4 Qxb2 20. Rb1 Qe5 $13 {Complicated, but fine for the engine.}) 18... b6 $3 {[%csl Bb6] This is Black's ONLY move to equalize, very deep and difficult to find.} (18... Qe7 {Logical, to stop Qb4, but White can develop the queen to c3.} 19. Qc3 Rd8 20. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Ge1,Ge3,Ge4] Fantastic pieces, simply with an advantage for White.}) (18... Qh4 $2 {Loses to:} 19. Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Rb7] The pawn drops.} Kg8 20. Qxb7 $18) (18... Kg8 {Looks very logical, to tuck in the king, but in fact, after the critical line:} 19. Rd1 Qh4 20. Ng3 Rd8 {With a pawn on b6 and king on f8, the position is equal, here, White has:} 21. Nf5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Re6f5,Ge3e8] A winning idea, due to the back rank.}) 19. Rd1 {The most logical.} (19. b3 $5 cxb3 20. axb3 $36 {White has the initiative.}) (19. f4 $5 {[%cal Rd8h4] To stop Qh4, deserves attention.}) 19... Qh4 $1 20. Qb4+ (20. Ng3 Rd8 $11 {[%csl Gf8] White doesn't have the Nf5 resource anymore.}) 20... Kg8 {[%csl Bb6] The pawn is protected, this is the point of 18...b6.} 21. Qd2 {[%cal Ra8d8] To stop Rd8.} Rg6 22. Ng3 Rf8 $1 $13 {Another strong move, to improve the pieces to the maximum, as you see, it's a very rich line.}) (12... Qd7 {This was played by my 2150 opponent, in the decisive game where I passed 2300, to become a FM.} 13. Nxd4 Rad8 14. c3 Qd5 $2 {Was played in the game.} (14... Rxg7 $1 $146 {This is the best according to the engine, and it's a standard element in this line that it transforms from a tactical position to a positional one:} 15. Nd2 Nxd4 16. Rxd4 Bd5 17. f3 c5 18. Qe1+ Kf8 19. Rf4 $14 {[%csl Oe3,Rf5,Rf6,Rf7,Og4,Rh7][%cal Gd2f1,Ge1f2,Ga1e1,Og4f6,Of1e3,Oe3g4] White will slowly activate the pieces, and sooner or later the knight from d2 will become a monster.}) 15. Qg4 $2 {I went for the dynamical choice, giving Black a chance to save the game.} (15. Qe2 $1 $146 {Was an improvement.} Rxg7 16. g3 $1 {[%csl Bg3,Rg7][%cal Gd4e6] To limit Black's rook activity.} Nxd4 17. cxd4 $18 {[%cal Gb1c3] The knight gets to c3, and White is much better.}) 15... Nxd4 $2 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gc3d4,Gb1c3] Was a positional mistake, since it allowed me to develop the knight to c3.} (15... Rxg7 $1 $146 {[%csl Bg7] Key move, but it's difficult for a human to evaluate the following line:} 16. Qxg7 Qxe4 17. Qg5+ Ke8 18. Nd2 Qg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4] Strong move.} 19. Nxe6 Qxg5 20. Nxg5 Rxd2 21. Nxh7 {The endgame looks dangerous for Black, but it's holdable with precise moves:} Rxb2 22. h4 Ne7 $1 {[%csl Be7] Key move.} 23. h5 Rb6 $1 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gb6h6] This is the point.} 24. g4 Rh6 25. Ng5 $14 {For the engine, it is +0.25, which means that it is objectively holdable, although it's tough to blame my opponent for not seeing this during the game.}) 16. Qh4+ f6 17. cxd4 Qg5 18. Qxg5 fxg5 19. d5 {I went for the concrete option:} (19. Nc3 $16 {Was also good enough for an advantage.}) 19... Rxd5 20. Nc3 Rd6 21. Nb5 Rb6 22. Nxc7 Kf6 23. Nxe6 Rxe6 24. Rxc4 Rxg7 25. Rac1 Re2 26. R4c2 Rxc2 27. Rxc2 $16 {In the end, I converted the game in nice style, but practically, it is very tough to hold this endgame with Black.}) (12... Rxg7 13. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3]}) 13. Rh4 {[%cal Ge7f7,Gg8g7] Black has two equally playable moves: Kf7 or Rxg7.} Kf7 $5 {[%csl Cf7,Rh4][%cal Rf3d4,Rd8h4] Prophylactic move against Nxd4 (Since the d8 queen now attacks h4).} (13... Rxg7 {This is more positional, since Black gives up the d4 pawn.} 14. Nxd4 Ke8 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gd8h4] A necessary move, to attack the rook on h4.} (14... Qd5 $2 {Huge mistake.} 15. g3 $1 {[%csl Bg3] Extremely useful move.} Rd8 16. Nc3 $18 {[%csl Gc3] The knight develops to the fantastic square, with a winning advantage.}) 15. g3 $5 {[%csl Bg3] This is my recommendation, a standard useful move.} (15. Qh5+ $5 {In most of the games, White went for this forced line:} Bf7 16. Qe2+ Kf8 17. Nxf5 Rg5 18. Rf4 Qf6 19. Qf3 {Black must have good knowledge to enter this line, as here begins a series of only moves:} Ne5 $1 20. Qh3 Bd5 $1 21. Qa3+ Ke8 $1 22. Qe3 Rxf5 $1 (22... Rxg2+ $4 {Logical, but:} 23. Kf1 $18 {[%csl Re8,Gf1] Black can resign.}) 23. Nc3 Bxg2 $1 {[%csl Bg2] Only move.} 24. Rxf5 Qxf5 25. Kxg2 Kf7 26. Ne4 $11 {According to the engine it's 0.00, but still, the show goes on.}) 15... Rg4 $1 {Only good move.} (15... Qxh4 $2 {Don't worry we are not blundering material.} 16. Nxe6 $1 $18 {[%csl Re8,Rg7,Rh4] It is Black who has blundered.}) 16. Rxg4 fxg4 17. c3 {The game becomes positional, but at least White has easy moves to play (simply finishing development), while Black must still show accuracy.} Qd5 {Best, but logical.} 18. Qe2 Kf7 $1 {[%csl Bf7] Best move.} (18... Nxd4 $2 {Might be obvious for some, but it's a positional mistake as we already know.} 19. cxd4 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3] The knight gets the important c3 square.} Kd7 (19... Kf7 20. Nc3 $18 {[%csl Bc3]}) 20. Nc3 Qf3 21. Qc2 $36 {[%csl Bc2] Big initiative for White, and also the engine agrees, showing a good evaluation.}) 19. Nxc6 {Here Black must demonstrate fantastic understanding:} bxc6 $3 {[%csl Bc6] The cleanest move, voluntarily tripling the pawns to have activity on the b-file.} (19... Qxc6 $6 {Is more human in my opinion, but not the best.} 20. Nd2 Re8 21. Qe5 $1 {[%cal Ge5f4] The queen lands on the typical f4 square.} Kg6 22. Qf4 {[%cal Ga1e1] White is ready for Re1, and engine shows:} Bc8 $3 {[%csl Bc8][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] A fantastic prophylactic move, and also preparing a battery.} 23. Nxc4 b5 24. Ne3 {[%csl Rg4] g4 is also weak, so Black doesn't have the time to play Bb7.} Re4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Only move.} 25. Qf8 Re8 {White can still play for a win:} 26. Nd5 $3 {[%csl Gd5] Beautiful resource.} Rxf8 27. Ne7+ Kf6 28. Nxc6 Re8 $1 {The engine evaluates this as +0.30, so enough compensation to hold, but I don't think that the draw is guaranteed for Black.} 29. Nd4 a6 30. Kf1 $5 {[%csl Ge2] To control the e2 square.} (30. f4 {Is one option, but Black has the concrete:} c5 $1 31. Nb3 Re2 $1 {[%csl Be2] The rook activates.} 32. Nxc5 Rxb2 33. a4 $36 {[%csl Gc5,Rc8] Still, chances remain.}) 30... c5 31. Nc2 $14 {[%cal Gc2e3] The knight has the nice defensive and attacking e3 square, White can definitely push for a win.}) 20. Nd2 Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3] This is also the point.} 21. Re1 Qxe2 22. Rxe2 Rb8 23. Nf1 $11 {[%cal Gf1e3] From a human perspective, White is slightly better, since he is the only one that can play for a win, but for the engine it's not much, only +0.15. Still, you shouldn't expect that someone will play in this way.}) 14. Rxh7 {We capture the pawn.} Rxg7 15. Rxg7+ Kxg7 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Cc4,Rc7,Bd1,Cd4,Bf4,Rg7] This is a very unusual position: Black has the more vulnerable king, but in return a very big center, and is ahead in development. So, visually, I would say that the position is balanced, and before analyzing it deeply, I thought that Black should be at least fine, but I was surprised to see that the engines prefer WHITE, and after analyzing it, I changed my opinion to agree with the engine's assessment. White's priority is to get the queen to f4, but how to actually achieve this in practice?} 16. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Cf4][%cal Gc1f4] Key move, played only in one correspondence game.} (16. Na3 {The most common, but here it's true that Black has easy play.} Qf6 $1 17. Qe2 c3 18. bxc3 dxc3 19. Nb5 Bf7 $1 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8] Strong move, preparing Re8 and Black is fully mobilized.} 20. Nxc7 $2 {Losing mistake.} Rc8 {[%csl Rc7] The knight is poorly placed.} 21. Nb5 a6 22. Na3 Re8 $19 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb7b5] With White's pieces offside, Black is dominating.}) (16. Qd2 $6 {Looks like the most logical move in the position, but it's not the best.} c3 $1 $146 {[%csl Bc3,Cd2] A very good tempo move.} 17. bxc3 dxc3 18. Qxc3+ Qf6 19. Qxf6+ Kxf6 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gc6b4] Black is fully mobilized, and has full compensation for the missing pawn.}) 16... Bd5 $1 $146 {A novelty, and probably the cleanest move for Black.} (16... Qf6 {The most logical move.} 17. Qf4 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Gf4] Tempo against c7.} Re8 $1 {Black must play for activity.} (17... Rc8 $2 {too slow.} 18. Nbd2 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga1e1] White finishes development and it's immediately winning.}) 18. Nbd2 {We are not in a hurry to take on c7.} Bd5 $1 {The best.} (18... Re7 19. Re1 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Ge1] White is now fully mobilized.}) 19. Qxc7+ {With the knight inserted into the game, White can consider taking the pawn.} (19. Re1 {The safer approach.} Rxe1+ 20. Nxe1 Qe7 21. Nef3 {The most critical move.} (21. Ndf3 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Rd4d3] Is a tricky option, since Black must find:} Be4 $1 {Best move.} 22. Nd2 Bd5 {Repeating the position once, and then choosing another move.}) (21. Kf1 $5 {Is possible.} c3 22. bxc3 dxc3 23. Ndf3 Bxa2 24. Nd3 $40 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] The knight and queen can organize some threats against the king.}) 21... c3 22. bxc3 dxc3 23. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Bh4][%cal Gh4f5] This is the engine's point.} Kf7 $1 {[%csl Bf7] Black must find this good move, but okay, who will find it?} 24. Qxf5+ Ke8 25. Nf1 Bxa2 {Engines still prefer White, but of course anything can happen in an OTB game.} 26. Qc8+ Nd8 27. Qg4 a5 $3 $13 {The engine's best move, but okay, we can stop here, you can dig deeper out of curiosity.}) 19... Kh8 20. Qf4 c3 21. bxc3 dxc3 22. Nb3 {I mainly focused on this move.} (22. Nf1 {is an option, but very unclear one:} Re4 23. Qg3 f4 24. Qh3+ Kg7 25. Rb1 Ne5 $1 $13 {The engine shows +0.40, but I don't see a clear solution for a safe advantage, just a very unusual position.}) 22... Re4 23. Qg3 Rg4 24. Qh3+ Kg8 25. Re1 $14 {For the engine, White has a good evaluation, but it's a good moment to stop, since it is tough to analyze it, and also to assess from a human point of view.}) (16... Qd6 $2 {Stops Qf4, but allows:} 17. Qg5+ $1 $18 {[%csl Gg5] Which is an even better square for the queen!}) 17. Qf4 Bxf3 $1 {This is Black's idea, to eliminate a pair of minor pieces.} 18. Qxf3 Qg5 {[%cal Rb1d2] Stopping Nd2.} 19. Na3 Qg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] If not for this move, White would have a serious advantage.} 20. Qxg4+ fxg4 21. Nxc4 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c2,Rb4a2] Targeting both pawns, and for the engine, Black has full compensation, but still White has some small tries:} 22. g3 {The safe and human approach.} (22. Re1 $5 {This is the tricky one, to reach a fantastic endgame:} Nxc2 23. Re4 Kf6 24. Rxg4 {[%csl Bd4,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2] 3 connected passed pawns vs an advanced passed pawn on d4. For the engine it's equal after the precise:} Re8 $1 25. h4 d3 $1 $11 {Still, the better player should win here in my opinion.}) 22... Kf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Bf6e5] A strong move, to control Ne5.} (22... Nxc2 $6 {Is premature.} 23. Rc1 $1 Nb4 24. Ne5 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rg4] White coordinates the pieces and is better.}) 23. c3 dxc3 24. bxc3 Nd5 25. Rc1 Re8 26. Kf1 $36 {Black has full compensation, although it is still not a dead draw, White can play on, without risking too much.} *

