{[%evp 0,18,25,29,28,28,37,19,8,-38,26,-20,-34,-11,25,17,48,19,6,6,-5]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. O-O d6 {The main line and probably Black's best line objectively. The theory developed a lot over the year, so we must be ready for a fight.} (5... Nge7 {Rare sideline, it is kind of playable, but Black must be very accurate.} 6. c3 {This is my recommendation.} (6. Ng5 $5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Rc6e5] is our usual trick, but Black has:} d5 $1 $11 {[%csl Gd5] and he survives.}) 6... dxc3 7. Ng5 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Rd5,Gg5][%cal Rg5f7,Gd1d5,Rd7d5] We go for the f7 pawn and the difference is that our queen from d1 controls the d5 square.} d5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bd5] Black should still go for it.} (7... O-O $4 {Typical blunder.} 8. Qh5 $18 {[%csl Rf7,Rg8,Rh7] White wins.}) (7... Ne5 $2 {runs into:} 8. Nxf7 $1 {Standard tactic.} Nxf7 9. Bxf7+ $14 {[%csl Rc5,Re8][%cal Gd1h5,Gh5c5] White is better here.}) 8. exd5 c2 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Rd1][%cal Gc2d1] Important intermezzo.} 9. Qxc2 Nd4 10. Qd1 $36 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,Gb1c3,Gc3a4] We can target Black's c5 bishop, and despite engine saying that Black has a more or less playable position, I think there is no reason to investigate further.}) (5... h6 $2 {[%csl Rh6] stops Ng5 at all costs, but it's just a mistake.} 6. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] Black is too slow.} dxc3 7. Bxf7+ $1 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Gf7][%cal Gd1d5,Re8f7] The point.}) 6. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1c3] White has to act fast.} Bg4 {The main line, but this position overall is quite rare. Only 370 games, and Black had to be ready for a lot of different options earlier.} (6... dxc3 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd6c5] The second main line, Black accepts the pawn, since the bishop on c5 is safe.} 7. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn, Black has a few options:} (7. Qb3 $2 {is met with:} Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7f7,Gc6a5] Very strong defense.} 8. Re1 {If you want to bluff, you can try this move. But it's very risky and not engine approved.} (8. Nxc3 Na5 $15 {All of White's initiative disappeared and Black is just slightly better.}) 8... Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] The correct refutation, and it was played by GM Adams.} (8... Nf6 $2 {The point is that this is a bad move.} 9. e5 $1 $40 {[%csl Ge5,Re8] White starts an attack against the king.}) 9. Qxc3 Nxc4 10. Qxg7 f6 $3 {[%csl Bf6] The key point.} 11. Qxh8 Qf7 $1 $19 {Black was winning in Cobb-Adams, 2002.}) 7... Nf6 {Most common by far.} (7... Nge7 {Rare line, but looks quite logical.} 8. Na4 $5 {[%csl Ga4] We have to look for compensation elsewhere.} (8. Ng5 $6 {doesn't lead to anything.} Ne5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd6c5,Rg5f7] There are no tricks, so Black is just better.}) 8... O-O {Black should castle, and now the position simplifies a bit.} (8... Bb6 $2 {[%csl Rb6] Natural, but a mistake.} 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] Without the c5 bishop, this move works perfectly.} Ne5 11. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f4,Rc5g1] The point is that since there is bishop, there is no pin on the king, so f4 is available.} h6 12. f4 $1 $18 {[%csl Bf4] Only move to win, but easy to find.}) 9. Nxc5 dxc5 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] The position is close to equality for Black, but it's not 100% since the c7 pawn is in some trouble.} Nd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Rc1 $44 {[%csl Gc4,Gf4][%cal Gf4g3,Gf2f4,Gd1h5] White has full compensation for the pawn, and quite easy play with the pair of bishops.}) (7... Bg4 {can be met with:} 8. Bg5 $5 $146 {[%csl Gg5] It's a novelty, although not the only option available.} Qd7 (8... Nge7 $6 {Risky for Black.} 9. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Re7][%cal Gd5e7] White has a very big initiative.} h6 (9... O-O $4 {Common mistake.} 10. b4 $3 $18 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4b5] Key move, and White wins material.}) 10. Bf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Strong move.} Kf8 $1 {[%csl Bf8] Black must run, but still White can play for the initiative.} (10... Bxf3 $4 11. Qxf3 {[%csl Re8,Gf3] The king is getting mated.} (11. Bxg7 $2 {[%cal Rf3d1,Gd5f6] No need to be fancy.} Nf5 $1 $13 {Black can survive.}) 11... gxf6 12. Nxf6+ Kf8 13. Nd7+ $1 {[%cal Gf3f7] Checkmate next move.} Qxd7 14. Qxf7#) 11. Bxe7+ Nxe7 12. b4 $1 $36 {[%csl Rf8] The king will be unsafe for the rest of the game.}) 9. h3 {[%csl Re8,Gg5][%cal Re8c8] We can go for some trades, since Black is still far away from castling.} Bxf3 (9... Bh5 10. Rc1 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7] To add some pressure on the c-file as well.} h6 11. Bh4 Nge7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 (12... Nxe7 $6 {runs into a fancy trick:} 13. Ne5 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd7,Ge5,Rf7,Rh5] Using the weaknesses in Black's camp.}) 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nd5 $36 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc4b5] We can follow up with active counterplay on the queenside, and White keeps the initiative.}) 10. Qxf3 Ne5 11. Qe2 h6 12. Bh4 {Black doesn't have a good way to develop.} Ne7 {Logical, to try to castle, but White has the standard:} 13. Bxe7 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5] followed by Nd5 and b4.} Qxe7 14. Nd5 Qd8 $1 15. b4 Bb6 {Even if Black finds all the correct moves, White keeps the initiative.} 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. Bb3 O-O 18. Rad1 $36 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf2f4] The pawn is not really felt, White has easy follow-up moves.}) 8. Bg5 h6 $1 {[%csl Gh6] Black should include this move, since it is useful to get rid of the pin.} (8... Be6 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Gc4] The best option, we are fighting for the d5 square.} Bxc4 10. Qxc4 {[%csl Rd8,Rf6,Gg5][%cal Gg5d8] The pin is the main source of White's compensation, and it's quite difficult to get rid of it.} h6 11. Bxf6 $5 {is quite simple.} (11. Bh4 {Keeping the bishop alive is fine as well.} g5 12. Bg3 Bb6 13. Rad1 $36 {Very nice position and easy to play.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Nd5 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb2b4] White is just slightly better.}) (8... O-O $6 {is of course very risky.} 9. Nd5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rf6,Rg8] The pawn structure will be ruined so White will attack for free.}) (8... Bg4 $6 {also very risky for Black.} 9. Nd5 $1 $40) 9. Bxf6 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gb2b4] We go for the forcing approach.} (9. Bh4 $6 {too slow.} Bg4 $15 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Rc3d5,Gg7g5] Black copies us and pins us down, and unfortunately Nd5 can be met with g5.}) 9... Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] Key idea of this line.} Bb6 $1 {Necessary.} (11... Bxb4 $2 {doesn't lose a piece, but still it's very bad.} 12. Nxb4 Nxb4 13. Qb3 $1 $18 {[%csl Gb3,Rb4,Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] Different double attack, White is winning.}) (11... Nxb4 $4 {Taking with the knight loses a piece.} 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. Qa4+ $18 {[%csl Rb4,Re8][%cal Ga4e8,Ga4b4] Double attack.}) 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Rb6][%cal Ga4a5] We continue to harass the bishop.} a5 {Solid move, but it weakens chronically the structure.} (12... Bg4 $6 {Black's most common move, but it's quite risky.} 13. a5 Bd4 14. Rc1 {[%csl Gc1] I like this simple move, just improving the rook.} (14. a6 $5 $146 {[%csl Ga6] Interesting exchange sacrifice to try over the board.} Bxa1 15. Qxa1 O-O 16. axb7 Rb8 17. b5 $13 {[%cal Ga1a7] With a very unbalanced situation.}) (14. Ra3 $5 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Ga3f3] This also deserves attention, kind of practical, to be able to capture on f3 with the rook.} a6 (14... O-O {is met with:} 15. a6 $3 {[%csl Ga6] Fantastic inclusion.} b6 $4 16. Nxd4 $3 {[%csl Ga6,Rb6,Rc6][%cal Gd4c6] This is the point.} Bxd1 17. Nxc6 Qe8 18. Rxd1 $18 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gd5] White is just winning.}) 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Rxf3 $14 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gf3g3,Gf2f4,Gg1h2] The rook comes into play.}) 14... a6 $146 {The most logical move to stop b5.} (14... O-O 15. Be2 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4] Strong reply, and potentially the pieces are hanging for Black.} Bxf3 16. Bxf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4] Black's pieces are just stuck.} a6 17. Bg4 $3 $146 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd5,Gg4][%cal Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Ra8c8] Black can retreat the bishop, but how will he ever improve the knight? White is better long term.}) 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Ne5 17. Qd1 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rd4] In both cases, Black has a real problem with the coordination and the weak structure. All 3 possibilites are good for White, so it's up to you the choice.}) (12... Ne5 {Second most common try, it has been played only in correspondence.} 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qh5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf7,Gh5] Typical move.} O-O 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Qxe5 {Position is equal, but White can keep some small pressure.} Re8 17. Rad1 $1 $36) 13. b5 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Nxb6 cxb6 {Black should capture, but the problems don't end here:} (15... Qxd1 $2 {Taking is a mistake.} 16. Rfxd1 cxb6 17. Rac1 $36 {[%csl Ra8,Gc1,Gc4,Rc8,Gd1,Re8,Rh8][%cal Gd1d6] The difference in piece activity is substantial, White has a huge initiative.}) 16. Qh5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf7] Another developing move with tempo.} Qe7 17. Rfd1 O-O 18. Bd5 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Rc8,Gd5][%cal Rc8e6,Gh5e5,Ga1c1] Black's c8 bishop is stuck and the pawn structure is just very bad.}) (6... Qf6 $5 {Rare sideline, we can play in the spirit of the position:} 7. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Rc5][%cal Ga2a4] To grab maximum space and play against the bishop.} Bb6 8. a4 $146 {[%csl Rb6,Rf6][%cal Ga1a3,Ga4a5,Ga3f3] The position is already new.} a5 $1 {The best for the engine.} (8... a6 $6 {Logical, but not the best.} 9. a5 Ba7 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 $2 {Accepting the pawn is too risky.} (10... Nge7 {Probably the best, but not challenging.} 11. Be3 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gc3] White is slightly better thanks to the extra space on the queenside.}) 11. cxd4 Bxd4 12. Ra3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd4,Rf6,Rf7][%cal Ga3f3] White is having a crushing initiative.}) 9. b5 $1 {[%cal Gc3d4] We go for the concrete option.} Ne5 $1 {This is Black's idea.} (9... Nce7 $2 {makes no sense at all.} 10. cxd4 Bg4 11. Ra3 $1 $16 {[%csl Gf3,Rf6][%cal Ga3f3] Key idea, to defend f3, and Black's pieces are just very clumsy.}) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 {Most logical, to support the d4 pawn.} (10... Qxe5 {is met in the same spirit.} 11. cxd4 $1 Bxd4 12. Ra3 $1 $40 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Ga3g3] Black has to be very careful to not lose immediately.}) 11. cxd4 Bxd4 12. Ra3 $1 $36 {[%cal Ga3f3,Gf3g3,Gc1a3] Typical idea, we are lifting the rook to the kingside, after which Ba3, and White has a pretty big initiative.}) (6... d3 $6 {Not accepting the gambit is always good news.} 7. b4 Bb6 8. a4 a6 {We have seen some similar position to this one already.} 9. Qb3 (9. Bxd3 {Safe option.} Nf6 10. Na3 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5,Ga3c4] White has a pleasant position.}) 9... Qe7 {[%cal Gc4d3] White can grab on d3 and be slightly better, or go for a concrete try:} 10. a5 $5 {To punish Black's lack of development.} Ba7 11. b5 $1 axb5 12. Qxb5 $36 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6][%cal Ga5a6] a6 is coming, Black must be very careful.}) (6... Nf6 $2 {also bad.} 7. cxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White just has the full center.} Bb6 8. h3 $5 $14 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rc8g4] To avoid any Bg4 ideas. White is just better.}) 7. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7,Rf7][%cal Gc4f7,Gb3b7] We remove the queen from the pin, and double attack the weak pawns.} Bxf3 {By far the most played.} (7... Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gc6a5] Decent sideline.} 8. Nxd4 Na5 9. Qb5 $5 {Unfortunately, we have to go for the endgame, but the good news is that it's still quite pleasant for White:} Nxc4 $1 {The best, and it was played in the high-level game: Ponkratov-Goryachkina, RUS-ch 2021.} (9... Qxb5 10. Bxb5+ Bd7 {Necessary.} (10... c6 $2 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5] is too bad.} 11. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4] b4 is a huge threat.}) 11. Bd3 $14 {White keeps a small advantage.}) 10. Qxc4 Ne7 11. h3 $5 {The position is balanced, but White can play normal improving moves and outplay the opponent.} Bh5 $146 12. Re1 {Sample line:} O-O 13. a4 a6 14. Be3 $132 {I still slightly prefer White, but the 7...Qd7 option is quite rare.}) 8. Bxf7+ Kf8 9. gxf3 {[%csl Rf8,Gg1][%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1] Short term White's king is a bit unsafe, but if we get a few moves in (like Kh1-Rg1), Black's king will be more vulnerable, because it cannot castle, and the light squares around him will stay weak for a long time.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] The best move for Black.} (9... Ne5 $6 {[%csl Rf3,Rf7] Logical to double attack, but I think it is a bit dubious.} 10. cxd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4c5,Gb3f3] White can gain a lot of time.} Bxd4 11. Bxg8 $1 Rxg8 12. f4 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Ge4,Gf4] The king is safe now, since the queen is activated, and White is slightly better, for example:} Ng4 13. Nd2 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gd2f3] The best move, if we get a knight to f3 nothing will bother us anymore.} (13. h3 $6 {Be a bit careful, cause this allows a crazy draw:} Qh4 $1 $146 14. hxg4 g5 $3 $11 {[%csl Bg5] And Black will give perpetual.}) (13. Qg3 $6 {is met with:} Nf6 $132 {[%csl Re4,Rg3][%cal Gf6e4,Rg7g5] With some concrete issues.}) 13... Qh4 {Black has to go for this endgame, but of course, it's not pleasant:} 14. Qg3 $1 {[%csl Gg3]} Qxg3+ 15. hxg3 $14 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2,Gf4,Gg3][%cal Gg1g2] The pawn structure is very nice, White can push for a win.}) (9... dxc3 $6 {has been played in a few games, but it kind of gives us what we want:} 10. Bxg8 Rxg8 11. Nxc3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gg1h1,Gf1h1] White needs a few moves to reach a pleasant position.} Nd4 $5 {Black usually tries to force things.} 12. Qd1 Qf6 {[%csl Rf3] f3 is the weakness Black tries to aim at.} 13. f4 $1 {White must be accurate for a few moves.} g5 14. fxg5 Qf3 15. Qxf3+ Nxf3+ 16. Kh1 {[%csl Gh1] With the king safe only White can be better.} Nxg5 17. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gf4g3,Ga1e1,Gh1g2] Slow consolidation next and White enjoys a safe advantage.}) (9... Bb6 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gc6a5] Na5 is a threat now, where the knight is protected by the b6 bishop.} 10. Bd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5c6] This is a good solution, to try and simplify a bit.} Nge7 11. a4 $5 {White has various ideas:} Qe8 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 13. Qd1 $5 $36 {[%csl Gd1,Gf3][%cal Gg1h1,Ga1a3] It feels like White is playing very strange, but remember that for now the task is to consolidate, and after that White can start thinking about activity.}) 10. Kh1 $5 $146 {[%csl Gh1] White is following the plan stated earlier, this is also a novelty, so it helps.} Na5 11. Qa4 Kxf7 12. Qxa5 {The position is playable for both sides, for example:} Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7a4,Gd7h3] Engine suggests this multi-tasking move.} (12... Re8 13. cxd4 Bxd4 14. Qa4 {[%csl Ga4,Rd4][%cal Ga4b3] Winning some tempi to improve the queen.} Bb6 15. Qb3+ Kf8 16. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6,Ge4,Gf3,Yf8,Gh1][%cal Gb1c3] White almost finished development, and this is the scenario I was talking about, the king is safe on h1, and White can make use of the vulnerable king and light squares around it.}) (12... Rf8 {similar to 12...Re8.} 13. cxd4 Bxd4 14. Qa4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Rf7f8,Ga4b3] Better version, since there is no f8 square for the king.}) 13. Rg1 {[%csl Gg1,Gh1] We get our desired setup.} Rhf8 14. Bg5 {The engine goes for a very radical decision:} Kg8 $3 {[%csl Bg8][%cal Gf8f6] To open the rook, and Black is ready to enter the complications after:} 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. cxd4 {[%cal Rc5d4,Ga5d5] The pawn cannot be recaptured.} Bb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] Strong move.} (16... Bxd4 $4 17. Qd5+ $18 {[%csl Rd4,Rg8][%cal Gd5g8,Gd5d4] Winning material.}) 17. Qd5+ $1 {White must also play concretely.} (17. Qc3 $6 {too slow.} Qa4 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3][%cal Ga8f8] White is overwhelmed a bit.}) 17... Qf7 18. Qxb7 Rf8 19. Nd2 $13 {[%cal Gg1g2] The position is quite unbalanced, but it's playable, White is very solid, and can use the long term trumps.} *

[Event "Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8"]
[Black "4...Nf6 5.e5 Ng4!?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Lucas Van Foreest"]
[ECO "C56"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[GameId "2175174925739856"]
[EventDate "2018.03.06"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.02.20"]

{[%evp 0,49,44,22,22,22,22,19,19,-25,-5,-17,-1,-4,-12,-11,-11,-3,5,-11,-11,5,-10,-57,-57,-75,-61,-7,0,0,0,0,161,134,161,17,18,65,65,12,65,40,39,39,39,64,68,64,64,72,65,65]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 Ng4 $5 {This line is ocasionally used by strong players in blitz/rapid. Black aims to target the e5 pawn.} 6. O-O $1 {The correct answer.} (6. Qe2 $6 {is a common mistake.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Be7] Black's only move.} 7. Bf4 f6 $1 $15 {Black is slightly better. Lie-Carlsen, Arctic Chess Challenge 2007.}) 6... d6 {The main line.} (6... Bc5 $6 {This transposes to a dubious version of the Max Lange, that is covered in another chapter.}) (6... Ngxe5 $4 {Losing blunder.} 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. Re1 $1 $18 {[%csl Re5,Re8][%cal Gf2f4] The piece on e5 is lost due to the pin.}) (6... Be7 7. Bf4 $5 {I think this is the most challenging approach, and it is a lot of fun to play.} (7. Re1 {[%cal Gh2h3] Safe move, White aims to go h3.} d6 $1 8. exd6 Qxd6 $132 {We transpose to the main line where White can try to play for the advantage, but Black is fighting as well.} (8... cxd6 $6 {Dubious response, because it ruins the pawn structure.} 9. Bg5 Nge5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Be2 O-O 12. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Rd6][%cal Gb1c3] White has a small advantage.}) 9. h3 Nf6 10. b3 $36 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc1a3,Gc1b2] The d4 pawn will fall, and White can try to make use of the slight development advantage, however, if you want to have something safe and bullet-proof, this is a better option compared to the chaotic 7.Bf4!?.}) 7... g5 $1 {The second most common move, Black wants to expand on the kingside.} (7... d6 $6 {Black's most common move, but in fact, this is what we are hoping for.} 8. exd6 cxd6 {was played by GM Bacrot.} (8... Bxd6 9. Re1+ $1 {Black has to lose a tempo to go back to e7.} Be7 10. c3 $36 {[%csl Gc3] White has a huge initiative.}) 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 $14 {White is better and later won in Socko-Bacrot, 1-0, Bundesliga 2016.}) (7... f6 {Rare option, trying to salvage the g4 knight.} 8. Bg3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gg3] This is a novelty and the beggining of a crazy position.} (8. exf6 $5 {This is a safe alternative.} Nxf6 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 d5 11. Bb3 {The position is balanced, but still playable:} O-O 12. Re1 $36 {[%cal Gd4e5,Rc7c5,Yc2c4] c5 is met with Qe5!, otherwise c4 can be White's next move, to open up the diagonal for the bishop.}) 8... fxe5 $5 {Engine idea.} (8... Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 fxe5 10. Bd5 $1 $36 {[%csl Gd5,Re8][%cal Rd7d5,Gf2f4] To stop d5 from Black, and White is ready to go f4, trying to organize something before the king will be able to castle.}) 9. h3 d5 $1 {Black will sacrifice a piece after:} 10. Bb5 O-O 11. hxg4 Bxg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge5] Black has 3 pawns for the piece, White can choose between simplifying or keeping the bishop on the board.} 12. Be2 $5 $132 {I think this is safer, to keep f3 defended, and it's a crazy position for 3 results.} (12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bxe5 $13 {Most likely Black will be able to force a draw by perpetual check after Bxf3.})) (7... O-O $2 {Just bad.} 8. h3 $1 $16 {[%cal Rg4h6] Black has to go to h6, where White can either take or ignore the knight.}) 8. Bg3 $1 {[%csl Gg3] Necessary.} (8. Nxg5 $2 {would be a nice tactic, but it fails to:} d5 $3 $17 {[%csl Gg4,Rg5][%cal Gc8g4] Important intermezzo, and Black wins material.}) 8... h5 9. Bd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rd7d5] Key move, to stop d5.} Nb4 $1 {was played in the only game that reached this position: Pap-Pressman, San Sebastian op 2011.} (9... h4 $2 {falls into the trap.} 10. Nxh4 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Rg4][%cal Gd1g4,Rd7d5] We use the vulnerability of the g4 knight, especially since there is no ...d5 with tempo on the c4 bishop.} gxh4 11. Qxg4 $36 {[%cal Gg4g7] Qg7 is a big idea, White has a great initiative.} hxg3 $4 {Blunder.} 12. Bxf7+ $3 $18 {[%csl Re8,Gf1,Gf7][%cal Re8f7,Gf2g3] Mate is soon to follow.}) 10. c4 $3 $146 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gc4d5] This is why I recommend to play 7.Bf4 instead of 7.Re1, the positions are very unbalanced and fun.} c6 11. a3 $1 {Intermezzo.} h4 $5 {Logical, to win the g3 bishop.} (11... Na6 {Also possible.} 12. Nxd4 $1 cxd5 13. Nc3 $5 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Gc3d5,Gd4b5] We want to jump in with the knights.} dxc4 14. Ndb5 $13 {[%csl Rc8,Re8][%cal Gc3d5,Gh2h3,Gb5d6] Very wild position.}) 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Nxd4 $13 {[%csl Rb4,Rg4] Amazing position, you can dig deeper if you like, for the engine the evaluation is the usual 0.00, but it is very interesting and rich.}) 7. exd6 Qxd6 {The best for the engine.} (7... Bxd6 {Most common, but not a challenging line.} 8. Re1+ $1 {[%csl Re8] To annoy the king on e8.} Kf8 {This is Black's idea. However White is slightly better with a number of moves, that's why I'll recommend something relatively new.} (8... Be7 $6 {Too slow.} 9. c3 $5 $14 {[%cal Rd4c3,Gd1c2] We are happy both to play for compensation if Black accepts to take on c3, where 10.Qc2! is a nice response or we just regain material with a slight edge.}) 9. h3 $5 {The line is semi-forced.} Nge5 10. Nxe5 (10. Nbd2 $5 $14 {Very decent option as well.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Bd5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1d4] The idea is to take on d4 with the queen, without running into the Bh2+ tricks, so we are provoking c6, which is a weakness.} (11. Qxd4 $4 {[%csl Rd4] Common blunder.} Nf3+ $1 12. gxf3 Bh2+ $1 $19 {[%csl Rd4] The queen is lost.}) 11... c6 {Black doesn't have a choice.} 12. Bb3 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gc8h3] The only critical move, to introduce the Bxh3 threat.} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gd2e4] To control f3 and also threaten Ne4.} Qg6 14. Ne4 Bxh3 15. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] Key point.} Bg4 16. Qxd4 {[%csl Rf8] Black has to know the continuation of the line in order to not lose:} h6 17. Ne6+ $1 {[%csl Rd6,Be6,Rg6][%cal Gd4d6] This is White's idea.} Kg8 $1 {[%csl Bg8] Only move.} 18. Qxd6 Bh3 $1 19. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] To defend from mate.} Nf3+ $5 {The position will simplify most likely:} 20. gxf3 fxe6 21. Bxe6+ Kh7 $3 {[%csl Bh7] Precise move, to get a better version of the endgame.} (21... Bxe6 $2 {Mistake.} 22. Qxe6+ $1 Qxe6 23. Rxe6 hxg5 24. Re7 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rh8] This is a much better version, because the h8 rook is out of the game.}) 22. Qe7 Bxe6 23. Rxe6 Qxg5+ 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. Re7 $14 {However Black is still under some pressure. And objectively, it was very hard to get here.}) 8. h3 $5 {In this line, I also want to recommend something fresh and fun.} (8. Re1+ {This transposes to the safe line that we have seen.} Be7 {See under 6...Be7.}) 8... Nf6 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7,Gg5] We play for activity, not for capturing back material.} Nd8 10. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3b5,Ga3c4] The knight is ready to jump to b5 or c4, Black must be careful, only 2 games have been played here.} a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6] The correct move.} (10... c6 $6 {was played in one email game, but it's slightly dubious.} 11. Bb3 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rc6][%cal Ga3c4,Yd1f3,Yb7b5] Compared to 10...a6, Black cannot stop Nc4 with b5, because Qf3 and the pawn on c6 is just misplaced. White has a huge initiative, and also engine agrees.}) 11. Bb3 b5 $3 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ra3c4] This is Black's absolutely necessary move, to prevent Nc4.} (11... Be7 $2 {was played in the game Karpatchev-Radulski, Marseille op 2004, but Black is close to collapsing after:} 12. Nc4 $1 Qc5 13. Re1 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Re8g8,Ge1e5] And Black cannot castle, because of Re5.} h6 14. Nf3 Ne6 {This is how the game continued, and multiple moves are good.} 15. c3 $1 $146 {[%csl Gc3] This is probably the most convincing.} (15. Nce5 $5 $40 {[%cal Ge5f7] was played in the game, and White won a few moves later.}) 15... dxc3 16. bxc3 $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Re8g8,Gc1a3] Castle is still impossible, Black is short on moves.}) (11... Ne6 $2 {also bad.} 12. Re1 Be7 13. Nc4 Qd8 14. Ne5 {[%csl Rf7] White stacks on the f7 pawn.} Nxg5 15. Bxg5 O-O 16. Qf3 $40 {[%csl Rf7,Rg8][%cal Ga1d1] Once again, White has a winning attack.}) (11... Be6 $2 12. Re1 $16 {[%csl Re6,Re8] And Black cannot finish development.}) 12. Qf3 $5 {[%csl Gf3] This is slightly more annoying, it keeps the game more alive.} (12. c4 $5 $146 {[%csl Gc4] This is a novelty that I enjoy, because White doesn't slow down and continues with the aggresion.} dxc3 $1 {[%csl Yc3] This is kind of necessary if Black wants to have a playable position, but it's crazy difficult to play this over the board.} (12... Be7 $2 {Black is not in time to develop.} 13. cxb5 O-O 14. Re1 $16 {[%csl Rd4,Rd8,Rf7][%cal Ga3c4,Gc4e5] Every Black piece is not in a good spot.}) 13. Qf3 {Black is objectively fine, but still has to know some things:} Bb7 14. Bxf7+ $5 Nxf7 15. Qxb7 Qd5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Looks like Black is in the clear, but White can win a piece:} 16. Re1+ Be7 17. Qxc7 O-O $3 {[%csl Bg8] Cold move, Black gets the king to safety.} 18. Rxe7 cxb2 $1 {[%csl Gb2] Intermezzo.} 19. Bxb2 Qxg5 20. Qc6 $11 {The position is equal, but still, some questions can be asked.}) 12... Ra7 $1 {[%csl Ra3] This is the best for Black, and it's amazing how despite the development advantage Black is surviving.} (12... Bb7 13. Bxf7+ $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gc3,Rd4][%cal Rd4c3,Rd8f7,Gf3b7] Compared to 12.c4, Black's pawn is on d4 not on c3, so taking on f7 will simply not work.} Kd7 $1 {[%csl Bd7] Black must start running with the king.} 14. Qf5+ Kc6 15. c4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc6] If engine says White is slightly better, I believe it.}) 13. Bf4 {White can bring all the forces with tempo:} Qd7 14. Rfe1+ Be7 15. c3 Bb7 16. Qg3 $44 {[%csl Re8] The game goes on, White has full compensation for the missing pawn, and I would take White any day of the week. But as usual, engine will find very good ways to defend. If you are not in the mood for the craziness, there is always the safe Re1 line, where you can regain the d4 pawn and play a symmetrical slightly more pleasant position.} *

