{[%evp 0,29,24,29,8,8,25,13,41,-36,-37,-53,-7,-19,-19,-16,-16,-39,-31,0,17,13,24,-18,12,4,20,18,22,0,15,-35]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 Ne4 $5 {Despite being less played than 5...d5, it had a recent boost in popularity, since strong players prefer to avoid the main theory, and try out this safe variation, with less lines to study.} 6. Qe2 $5 {[%csl Be2] White's most testing line.} (6. O-O {This is the stastical main line, but I prefer to not enter it.} Be7 $1 {The cleanest move.} (6... d5 {Most common try, but things are a bit diffrent in this move order:} 7. exd6 Nxd6 8. Bd5 Be7 {[%csl Gf1] Compared to 6...Be7, White will save up a tempo on Re1, which is a good move, but not a priority.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd1f3] White will be getting some small pressure for free, since Black needs one more tempo to castle.}) 7. Re1 d5 8. exd6 Nxd6 9. Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5c6] White will regain back the d4 pawn, but Black is quite safe, for example:} O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxd4 Qd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Ge7f6] The correct move, played some years ago by GM Wei Yi. Black is pretty comfortable with Bf6 coming next, and Black went on to win.} (11... Bb7 $6 {Common move, but not the most accurate.} 12. Nb3 $1 $146 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7] White can fight for a slight advantage.})) 6... Nc5 $1 {Necessary move.} (6... Bb4+ $2 {It seems pretty smart to include this check, since White didn't castle, but in reality, it's a losing mistake:} 7. Kd1 $1 {[%csl Re4] The knight is in trouble.} Nc5 8. a3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,Rb4a5] Followed by b4 and White wins a piece.}) 7. O-O {[%csl Gg1] I like castling, it is the most useful move, and we don't reveal our cards to the opponent yet.} (7. Ng5 $5 {This deserves attention as well, it is an unexplored line.}) (7. c3 $5 {is used from time to time by strong players, and one year ago it was a succesful weapon for the expert of the Scotch Gambit, GM Jones, to beat legendary GM Adams in the London Classic 2024. It was a very nice game, and definitely worth investigating.}) 7... Ne6 $1 {[%csl Be6] The correct move order for Black.} (7... Be7 $6 {In the majority of games, Black confused the move order and started with this natural developing move, but it's a mistake!} 8. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Rd4] White can organize fast play against the d4 pawn, that for the moment is attacked.} Ne6 {Black's most common try, to defend the pawn.} (8... d5 {or 8...d6 will lead to the same.} 9. exd6 {Black doesn't have a satisfactory recapture.} Qxd6 {looks fine, but it's very risky:} (9... cxd6 {Positionally wrong.} 10. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd6] White is just slightly better thanks to the structure.}) 10. b4 $1 {[%csl Bb4,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gb4b5] Key move, White dismantles the coordination of Black's knight, it was played by GM Jones, if you want to improve in the Scotch Gambit, checking his games is valuable.} Ne6 11. b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc1a3] This is the idea.} Na5 12. Ba3 Qb6 {We can check the game Jones-Ernst, 2014.} 13. Bxe6 Bxe6 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 {So far logical, and here we can improve White's play:} 15. Qe4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Rh7][%cal Ge4h7,Ge4h4,Rh8d8,Rb6b5] Before capturing the pawn, this is a very annoying centralizing move, since it stops Black from finishing development.} (15. Rxd4 $2 {GM Jones took with the rook, but it allowed Black to get back in the game:} Rhd8 $1 $11 {[%csl Ga8,Bd8][%cal Ga8a7,Rd4a4] Better with this rook and Black equalized.})) (8... O-O {Not challenging, of course.} 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Rxd4 {[%csl Gd4] White succesfully regains the pawn.} c6 11. a4 $1 $14 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Rb7b5] The key move, defending from ...b7-b5.} Nxa4 {Concrete try.} 12. Nd2 $5 {[%cal Gd2e4] White can play for big compensation.} (12. Rxa4 $5 $14 {[%cal Rb7b5,Gc4b5] also an option, to play with extra material.}) 12... Nb6 13. Ne4 $36 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White has a lot of control on the position, the missing pawn is irrelevant.}) 9. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] We play for activity, we don't care about the pawn so much.} (9. Bxe6 $6 {Most common move, but it's less challenging since it transposes to the main line. In this move order we have a better option.} fxe6 $1 (9... dxe6 $6 {slightly less precise.} 10. Nc3 $5 $36 {[%cal Gc3b5] This was my game against GM Sanal Vahap, EU-chT 2019. I soon got a winning position, White has a slight initiative.}) 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Rxd4 O-O {transposes to the main line.}) 9... d5 {Probably the best, and it was used by GM Vidit.} (9... dxc3 $6 {Black accepts the challenge, but it's a dangerous decision.} 10. Nxc3 O-O 11. b3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc3d5,Gc3e4,Ga1c1] This is extremely easy to play for White, the compensation is huge. Also visually, it's simple to understand that the Black extra pawn is absolutely irrelevant, Black has no space and the pieces are shut down.}) 10. exd6 cxd6 {The best.} (10... Qxd6 $2 {Not advisable.} 11. Na3 $1 {[%csl Ga3] Very strong preparation, showed by the young chinese girl Lu Miaoyi against GM Nogerbek in the Tata Steel B Tournament 2025.} a6 12. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6,Re6] Black's pieces are too clumsy.} O-O 13. cxd4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Gd4,Re6][%cal Gd4d5] Lu soon enough won material and the game.}) 11. cxd4 {We can follow the game Mamedov-Vidit, 0-1, Gashimov Memorial Rapid 2023.} d5 12. Bb3 O-O 13. Nc3 Nc7 {[%csl Rc7] Sad, but necessary. Any move is good enough for an advantage:} 14. Ne5 $5 $146 {I think White can just play positionally.} (14. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Re7d6,Gf4g5] was Mamedov's choice, it was a valid try.}) 14... Be6 15. Bf4 Rc8 16. h3 $5 $14 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ga1c1,Ge2f3] Anyway, there is no hurry in the position, White can finish development and continue improving.}) 8. Bxe6 $5 {I think this is the only viable approach to fight for an advantage. I played this move myself in 2 games against strong GMs.} (8. c3 {was played in the game Yoo-Aronian, USA-ch Saint Louis 2022.} d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] GM Aronian was well prepared, and showed the best path to equality:} 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bg5 Be7 (10... Qd7 $5 {deserves attention as well.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Rd1 Nf4 $1 {[%csl Bf4] Best move played by Aronian.} (12... O-O $6 {was the choice of some GMs, but in fact, the king belongs in the center.} 13. cxd4 $1 Nf4 14. Qe3 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 13. Qxe7+ {At this point, White should go into the endgame.} (13. Qd2 $6 {was played in the game, but it's overambitious.} Qf6 $1 14. cxd4 Be6 $1 $146 {Improvement over the game.} 15. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 {[%csl Gf6,Rg1] Black is slightly better thanks to the weak king on g1.}) 13... Kxe7 $1 {[%csl Ge7] Best recapture.} (13... Nxe7 $6 {Positional mistake.} 14. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Re7] White is slightly better, the knight is just bad on e7.}) 14. Nxd4 $11 {Full equality, Black can take on d4 and trade more pieces off the board.}) (8. Rd1 $6 {[%csl Rd1,Gd4,Ge6] This move doesn't come with tempo now.} d5 $1 {Logical move, and probably Black is the one fighting for the advantage:} 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. c3 {White has to try and win the pawn this way, but after:} (10. Nxd4 $4 {Common blunder.} Ncxd4 11. Rxd4 Bxh2+ $1 $19 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d4] Black wins the exchange.}) 10... O-O 11. cxd4 Qf6 $1 $36 {[%cal Gc4e6,Gf6e6,Ge2e6,Rd4d5,Rc6d4] Precise move played by GM Tari. d5 is met with Ncd4 intermezzo, and White's best is to trade everything on e6 and play an endgame without the pair of bishops, where only White is risking long term.}) 8... dxe6 {You should expect this recapture more often, since Black tries to play a known structure that can be reached from many openings.} (8... fxe6 {Less often played, and understandably so. Black keeps the d-file closed, so the queen is safe, but the structure is quite unusual.} 9. Rd1 {White goes for the pawn.} Be7 {The only move that has been played.} (9... Bc5 $6 {Waste of time.} 10. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gc5e7] Black has to go back to e7.} Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd1d7] White is slightly better, since Black doesn't have the pair of bishops anymore, and this is the risk the position carries for Black. The d7 pawn is a backwards pawn and it will remain for the rest of the game.}) 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Rxd4 O-O 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rc7,Rd7][%cal Yb7b6,Yc8b7,Yd8e8,Yb7c6,Gd4g4,Gc1h6,Gc3e4,Ga1d1] If we give Black a few moves, he can definitely start using the power and potential of his pair of bishops, but White also has a very straight-forward plan on how to develop an attack and how to target those backward pawns.} b6 {The most played move and the most logical.} (12... d5 {Rare move, Black immediately clarifies the structure.} 13. exd6 cxd6 (13... Bxd6 $6 {was played in Gurevich-Honkman, Bundesliga 2002.} 14. Be3 $14 {[%csl Re6] White is just slightly better thanks to the superior structure.}) 14. Bf4 $1 $146 {[%csl Rd6,Re6,Bf4][%cal Rf4d6] Important move, since Bxd6 followed by Rad1 is a threat.} d5 {Necessary.} (14... b6 $6 15. Bxd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6] The point.} Bxd6 16. Rad1 Bxh2+ 17. Kxh2 $14 {Material is equal, but Black didn't equalize, also White is very ahead in development.}) 15. Be5 $14 {[%csl Rc3,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Re6][%cal Gd4g4,Ga1e1,Gc3d1] White is doing great with a very solid position, the only issue for the moment is the knight, but if we can improve it, White will be slightly better.}) 13. Rg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4,Rg8] We immediately improve the rook.} Kh8 {was played in the game Asadli-Esipenko, EU-ch 2023.} (13... Bb7 $6 {Common move, but not the best one objectively.} 14. Bh6 Rf7 15. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4g5] Black is under some serious pressure, since Ng5 is a serious idea.} Kh8 {Prophylactic move.} (15... Bxe4 $6 {If Black is scared and goes for this solid trade, White is just better:} 16. Qxe4 Rb8 17. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rd7,Rg7] Even if there is no direct breakthrough, the long term weakness of Black's structure guarantees us an advantage.}) 16. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] The point behind our previous move.} Bxg5 (16... Rf8 $4 {loses the queen.} 17. Bxg7+ $1 $18 {[%csl Rd8,Rh8][%cal Gg5e6]}) 17. Bxg5 Qf8 18. Rd1 $14 {White has a safe slightly more pleasant position.}) (13... d5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gd5] This is the best move, it's a novelty, but a very unlogical move, since Black just went b6 to develop the bishop and now changes his mind.} 14. Qd3 $5 $11 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4] Position is equal, and still very complex, White should keep up the pressure.}) 14. Be3 $5 {[%csl Ge3] I like Vugar's move, White for the moment remains flexible and brings the rest of the pieces into the game.} (14. Ne4 {runs into:} d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Re4] This is understandable now, since it hits the knight with tempo.} (14... Bb7 $6 {Not challenging.} 15. Bg5 Bxe4 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Rxe4 $14 {[%csl Ge2,Ge4] White is slightly better.}) 15. exd6 cxd6 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black will go e5 next with a comfortable position.}) 14... Bb7 15. Rd1 Rf5 (15... Qe8 {is met with:} 16. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rc7][%cal Gb5c7,Ra8c8,Gb5a7] Annoying tempo.} Bd8 17. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] To eliminate the defender.} Ba6 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Ra4 $14 {With minor pieces off the board, White is long term slightly better.}) 16. Qd3 $5 $146 {[%csl Gd3,Rd7] We attack the d7 pawn with another idea in mind.} (16. Rgd4 $6 {GM Asadli tried to put pressure on the d7 pawn, but couldn't quite manage.} Bc6 17. b4 a6 18. a4 b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] Strong find by Esipenko and Black overtakes the initiative.} 19. axb5 axb5 20. Nxb5 Rxe5 $15 {Black was slightly better, altough eventually, the game ended in a draw.}) 16... Bc6 17. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2d4] The knight is coming to d4.} Rxe5 $1 {[%csl Be5] The engine suggests to enter the ensuing chaos:} (17... Qf8 $6 {looks logical, to active the queen, but White has a strong idea:} 18. Qc3 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Ge5][%cal Gc3c7,Gb2b3,Ga2a4,Oe2d4] The pawn on c7 is a target now, Nd4 is an idea that Black should alway calculate, but White can also play slowly.}) 18. Rxg7 $1 {[%csl Gg7] Many players can calculate this move before taking on e5, and reject it immediately.} Kxg7 19. Bd4 Bf6 20. Qg3+ {[%csl Re5] looks like Black is on the verge of collapse.} Kf7 21. Bxe5 Qg8 $1 {[%csl Gg8] This is the important point, without it Black is just lost. Is it a difficult line to calculate? Probably yes for some, but still even if you reach this position, the endgame is playable:} 22. Bxf6 Qxg3 23. hxg3 $5 {Safe option.} (23. Nxg3 Kxf6 24. Rd4 $11 {[%eval 0,0] the evaluation, and I agree, Black should have full compensation for the pawn.}) 23... Kxf6 24. f3 $11 {[%cal Gg1f2,Gg2g4,Gd1h1] This is probably slightly safer, to have also some active play on the h-file with better coordination, equal, but playable endgame.}) 9. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Rd4] The pawn on d4 will sooner or later fall, and we will have an interesting position, where White has more space and some dark squares control, while Black has a potentially very strong light-squares bishop.} Be7 {Most logical move.} (9... Bc5 {is met with:} 10. c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Rc5][%cal Gc3d4] To win the pawn back with tempo.} O-O 11. cxd4 Be7 (11... Nxd4 $4 {Impossible.} 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4,Rg7][%cal Rg4d4,Gg4g7] We don't care about the bishop, the goal is to checkmate.} c5 14. Bh6 g6 15. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Gc3e4] White has a winning advantage.}) 12. a3 $1 $14 {[%csl Ba3,Rc6,Gd5,Re7][%cal Rc6b4,Rc6e7] Very instructive move, to stop Nb4-d5 and Black can't improve the stuck pieces.}) (9... b6 $1 {[%csl Gf8] The best move, in my opinion, for now it's not clear where the f8 bishop belons, so Black can focus on improving the c8 one instead.} 10. Be3 $5 {[%csl Ge3] I like this move, and it was tried in a blitz game by Caruana against Carlsen.} (10. Bg5 {Safe, but not challenging.} Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 O-O 14. Nc3 Bb7 $11 {Too many pieces come off the board, Black is fine.}) 10... Bc5 {Carlsen's choice.} (10... Bb7 11. Nxd4 {[%csl Rd8] The queen is immediately under some pressure.} Qh4 12. Nc3 O-O-O $1 {Black can kind of keep it together by castling long, but White is still quite pleasant after:} 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Rxd8+ Qxd8 15. Qc4 $36 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] White can start pushing the queenside pawns, objectively Black is not doing too bad, but still, it's not the most pleasant position I have seen.}) 11. c3 Bb7 12. cxd4 Be7 13. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Rc6][%cal Rc6e7,Rc6b4] Once again, Caruana shows some understanding by restricting Black's knight on c6.} Qd7 $1 $146 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Ge8c8] Engine likes this setup for Black.} (13... a6 $6 {[%cal Gc6a7] Carlsen felt the need to control the d5 square, but it was too slow.} 14. Nc3 Na7 15. Rac1 $146 {There is no reason to hurry.} (15. d5 $5 {[%cal Re6d5,Gf3d4] GM Caruana went all in with this pawn sacrifice, it was a decent choice, but he lost that blitz game.}) 15... O-O 16. Ne1 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge2g4] Key move, to open the diagonal for the queen, and Black has the pair of bishops, but simply cannot use them. Black is too passive.}) (13... O-O {The most logical move.} 14. Nc3 $36 {[%csl Gc3] However, thanks to the piece coordination, White is enjoying a simple initiative.}) 14. Nc3 O-O-O 15. Rac1 Kb8 16. b4 $132 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gh2h3,Yh7h6,Yg7g5,Gd4d5] White can keep improving the pieces a bit and when Black will start advancing his kingside, White will strike in the center with d5 to open up the pieces. Objectively, the position is equal, but very playable.}) 10. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Gc3b5] Key move to remember, since the pawn can be recaptured in many ways, but this is the most precise.} O-O 11. Nb5 {We can follow my game against GM Sanal Vahap:} Bd7 12. Nbxd4 Qc8 $1 {[%csl Bc8] This is the best move for Black, but it's a very difficult prophylaxis move to understand.} (12... Nxd4 $6 {Black went for the logical trade, but in fact, it was very dangerous.} 13. Rxd4 $1 {[%csl Rd7,Rg8][%cal Gd4d7,Gd4g4] Important recapture, first I threaten to pin the bishop down, and later I swing the rook to g4.} c5 $1 {was a better try, played in the very recent game Bai-Xie, China zt 2025.} (13... Qc8 $2 {My opponent went for the natural move, but in fact it is a losing mistake already.} 14. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] To trade the dark squares bishop.} f6 15. exf6 gxf6 {Unfortunately, the game ended in a draw after some adventures, but a straight-forward win was:} 16. Bh6 $1 $146 {[%csl Rf8] To attack the rook.} Rf7 17. Rg4+ Kh8 18. Rf4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Rc8e8,Gf3e5] Ne5 comes next no matter what, and Black will lose the exchange and the game.} Bd6 {is met with:} 19. Ng5 $1 $18 {[%csl Bg5] Key intermezzo, the only winning move, so probably I overlooked it.}) 14. Rg4 Kh8 15. a4 $1 $146 {[%csl Ba4] I think this is a very nice improvement over what was played in the game.} Bc6 16. Ra3 $1 $40 {[%cal Ga3f3,Ga3h3] This is the point, the rook joins the attack.}) 13. c3 $5 {[%csl Gc3] We can just wait, because Black either way doesn't want to allow Nxd4 Rxd4-g4, so his pieces are a bit stuck.} (13. Bg5 {is met with:} h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] Very strong move, and some pieces get off the board.} 14. Nxc6 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Bxc6 16. Ne4 $11 {Black is fine with a lot of moves.}) (13. Bf4 $6 {We don't want to play this very soon, since after:} Nxd4 14. Rxd4 c5 $1 $11 {[%csl Gc5,Rf4][%cal Rd4g4] The rook cannot go to g4 anymore.}) 13... Rd8 14. h4 $5 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gc1g5] Continue to improve.} h6 15. Rd3 $40 {[%cal Gd3g3,Gf3d4] Slowly, but surely White is organizing an attack. All in all, I like White's position after 8...dxe6, I think that we can put Black in a lot of pressure, and it's also difficult for Black to prepare, since there are a lot of decent options for White, it's tough to imagine somebody prepared against all of the ideas.} *

