{[%evp 0,19,32,22,22,27,27,-11,-11,-36,-28,-42,-58,-27,20,20,28,23,15,15,23,-14]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 {This is a far less played line than 6...Ne4, but it's a serious one nevertheless, and it has been played in 1200 games.} 7. O-O {[%cal Yf8e7,Yf8c5] Black has 2 logical squares to develop the bishop.} Be7 {Main move.} (7... Bc5 $6 {Less precise. White has a strong reaction:} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] White develops with tempo, and Black needs Be7 anyway.} Be7 10. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] Key move.} ({Not} 10. Bxe7 $2 Qxe7 11. Nxd4 c5 $11 {Black is absolutely fine.} 12. e6 fxe6 13. Nxe6 $11 {Equal position, but no advantage for White.}) 10... Bb7 {Best move.} (10... Nb8 $2 {A typical move in the main line, but here it is too slow.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Rc6c5] A nice developing move, to stop c5.} O-O 13. f4 $18 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1e1,Gf4f5] According to the engine, White's attack is too fast, Black's position is hopeless.}) (10... Bxg5 $2 11. Nxc6 $18 {[%csl Rd8] The queen is trapped, which is the point.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {There are only 8 games here, and visually, Black is in a lot of trouble, but if you dig deep enough with the engine, Black still has surviving chances.} 12. e6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] The most concrete move.} (12. Nf5 $5 $146 {If you want to have a game, this is a good alternative.} Qf8 13. Re1 O-O-O 14. Nd2 c5 15. Qg4 g6 16. Nh4 $36 {[%cal Gh4f3] Slightly better for White, but of course, very playable.}) 12... fxe6 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 {Black has to take.} 14. Re1 Ne5 15. Qh5+ $1 {The line is forced up until here.} g6 16. Rxe5 gxh5 17. Rxe6+ Kf7 18. Rh6 {White will win a pawn, but it's too early to stop:} Rae8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] A necessary move, to activate the rook.} 19. Nc3 {The critical move, stopping Re2. We are following the game Samunenkov-Kandil, 2020.} (19. Nd2 $5 $146 {Deserves attention.} Re2 20. Nf3 Rxc2 21. Rxh5 Ke7 $1 {[%cal Ge7d7] A strong move, and Black is most likely equalizing:} (21... Rxb2 $2 22. Re1 $40 {[%csl Rf7] The king is in trouble.}) 22. b4 Kd7 23. h3 c5 24. bxc5 Rxc5 25. Rd1 $14 {Still, it's +0.30 so White can play on.}) 19... d4 $1 {A necessary move, to gain access to e2.} 20. Na4 Re5 $1 {[%csl Be5][%cal Ge5c5,Ge5h5] The rook defends both the pawn, and the c5 square.} ({Not immediately:} 20... Re2 {since White is just better after:} 21. Rc1 Rhe8 22. h4 $16 {[%csl Rh5,Rh7] White will win a pawn.}) 21. f4 Re2 $1 {[%csl Rg2] And now g2 can be a target as well.} 22. Nc5 Bc8 $1 $146 {The best defense.} (22... Ba8 $2 {Was a very poor move played in the game.} 23. Rc1 $18 {[%csl Ra8] White is just winning, since the bishop is doomed.}) 23. Rxc6 h4 $1 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4h3] Necessary, to create counterplay.} 24. Rxc7+ Kg6 25. Nb3 $5 {Is perhaps more interesting.} (25. h3 {[%cal Rh4h3] A logical move against h3, but Black has:} Rg8 $1 {[%csl Rg2,Bg8] And g2 is not at all easy to protect.} 26. Nd3 Kf6 27. Nf2 Bxh3 $1 {A necessary decision, and Black equalizes after:} 28. Nxh3 Rgxg2+ 29. Kf1 Rxc2 30. Rxc2 Rxc2 $11 {With full compensation. The pieces are very active, a draw is the most likely result.}) 25... h3 $1 26. gxh3 d3 $1 {[%csl Gd3] Key move.} 27. Nd4 Re4 28. Nf3 dxc2 29. Rxc2 Rxf4 {Black is 2 pawns down, but after the logical line:} 30. Kf2 Bb7 31. Rg1+ Kh6 32. Rc3 Rhf8 33. Rg3 a5 $44 {Black has full compensation, and it's unlikely that White can make progress.}) 8. Bxc6 {The main move.} (8. c3 $5 {White can play in a gambit style. Objectively, White is not worse, and it is Black who must be more accurate.} dxc3 (8... d3 {Not challenging.} 9. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gb5d3] White is just slightly better.}) 9. Nxc3 Nb6 {The most logical, and the best.} (9... O-O $6 {Has been played in some games, but it's a concession.} 10. Qxd5 {[%csl Gd5] White captures the key d5 pawn.} Nc5 11. Be3 Be6 {A bit strange to note that here GM Thomas Beerdsen forgot the move twice:} 12. Qd1 $1 $14 {An important novelty, and White is slightly better.}) (9... a6 {A forcing line, but it's a bit unpractical.} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nd4 Nb8 $1 {Necessary.} (11... Bb7 $2 12. Nf5 $36 {[%csl Gf5] This is the problem.}) 12. f4 c5 13. Nb3 c4 {We are following the game Beerdsen-Leko, Bundesliga 2023.} 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. Nxd5 cxb3 {The start of the concrete line:} 16. Nxc7+ Kd7 17. Nxa8 Bc5+ $1 18. Kh1 Bb7 19. Rd1+ Kc6 {Leko's move, and here we can improve upon on the game.} 20. a4 $1 $146 {The endgame is very strange, but most likely equal.} Bxa8 21. Rd3 Nd7 22. Bd2 (22. Rc3 {If all else, White always has a draw in reserve.} Kd5 23. Rd3+ $11) 22... Nb6 23. Rxb3 Kd5 $1 $13 {[%csl Gd5] The best move, and the position is balanced, but complex.} (23... Rd8 $2 {Losing move.} 24. Ba5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5][%cal Ga1c1] Game over.})) 10. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga4a5] A standard move, to target the knight.} a6 {More ambitious, but also more risky.} (10... a5 {Black stops a5.} 11. Be3 O-O {A straight-forward solution.} (11... Be6 {Leads to an unclear game.} 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Qf3 $13 {Double edged position.}) 12. Bxb6 {We enter an endgame.} cxb6 13. Qxd5 Bc5 14. Qe4 Nd4 15. Nxd4 Qxd4 16. Rad1 Qxe4 17. Nxe4 {Perhaps White has some small chances, but with accurate play, Black equalizes:} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] Key.} 18. Nxc5 Bxd1 19. Nd7 Bb3 20. Nxf8 Kxf8 21. Rc1 $11 {Equal, with a playable endgame.}) 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. a5 {We are following the game Beerdsen-Durarbayli.} Nd7 13. Nd4 Nb8 14. f4 c5 {Black tried to activate his pieces:} 15. Nc2 d4 16. Qf3 c6 17. f5 $5 {[%csl Gf5] White goes all-in.} dxc3 18. f6 gxf6 19. exf6 Bd6 20. Bf4 Bxf4 21. Qxf4 Be6 {Black played well so far, and in the end won the game, but an improvement would be:} 22. Rae1 $1 $146 {Although it's only good enough for equality.} Nd7 23. Qd6 Nxf6 24. Qxc6+ Nd7 25. Rxf7 $1 {And the game soon ends in a perpetual.} Kxf7 26. Qxe6+ Kg7 27. Qg4+ $11 {Equal.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 $1 {[%csl Cb8] The most sound variation, I have also used it once with Black.} (9... Bb7 $6 {This is as usual very risky:} 10. Nf5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf5] Key point.} Bf8 11. Re1 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e6] Logical move to prepare Ne6.} 12. Nd4 $1 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Rc5e6] Stopping Black's idea.} Qd7 13. Nd2 Be7 {Black just finishes development, but doesn't fully equalize:} (13... Ne6 {Logical, but White is in time to controll all of the dark squares after:} 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1e3] A typical positional idea.} c5 16. Na5 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc2c4] The bishop is short of squares, Black is worse.}) 14. b4 Ne6 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3d4] With a standard positional advantage.}) (9... Nxe5 {Possible move, but very concrete, so Black must have serious knowledge to enter into this line.} 10. Bf4 c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] The engine's way.} (10... Ng6 $6 {The most common move, but inaccurate:} 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Nxe7 Nxe7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3] Simple, and slightly better, thanks to the better structure and dark squares.}) 11. Bxe5 cxd4 12. Bxg7 Rg8 13. Be5 $1 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Ge5g3] A necessary move, to have Bg3, just in case.} (13. Bxd4 $2 {Runs into:} Bh3 $19 {[%csl Rg2] White loses material.}) 13... c5 {Black defends the strong central pawn.} (13... Bh3 $2 14. Bg3 $18 {[%cal Gd1d4] This is how the game Warakomska-Kiolbasa, 2023 continued, White captured on d4 next with a winning advantage.}) 14. Re1 $13 {The position is unclear, but playable for a long time.} Bg4 $1 {The strongest move for the engines, and it was played in the game between GMs Ehlvest-Heberla, 2024.} (14... Qb6 {Logical move, played in an old game.} 15. Nd2 $146 {White can finish development.} (15. Bg3 {This is more straight-forward.} Bg4 (15... Qxb2 $2 16. Nd2 $18) 16. Qd3 Rg6 17. Nd2 c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Black must try this concrete move.} 18. Nxc4 dxc4 19. Rxe7+ $1 {[%cal Re8e7,Gd3e4] Fancy stuff.} Kxe7 20. Qe4+ {[%csl Ra8,Re7][%cal Ge4a8,Ge4e7] The point.} Re6 21. Qxa8 Qxb2 22. Rf1 {The position is crazy, and as usual, the engines ruin all of the fun, by showing 0.00 after:} Be2 $1 23. Re1 d3 24. Qxa7+ Kf6 25. Qa5 dxc2 26. Bf4 Kg7 $1 $11 {[%cal Ga5g5,Gg5d8] At minimum, White has a repetition, or you can play on as well.}) 15... Bg4 16. Nf3 Kf8 $1 {[%csl Gf8] Best, standard prophylactic move.} 17. c3 dxc3 18. bxc3 $132 {White has a slight pull, for example:} Rd8 19. Rb1 Qc6 20. Bg3 {[%csl Gg3] Good improving moves.} Bf6 21. Qd3 c4 $1 {[%csl Bc4] Only move, otherwise Black is seriously worse.} 22. Qe3 {[%cal Gf3e5] White is ready for Ne5, so Black could resign, if not for:} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Bf3] To eliminate the knight.} 23. Qxf3 Rg6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] Another strong move.} 24. h4 h5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] Black must stop h5.} 25. Rb8 Rxb8 26. Bxb8 Qb6 $1 27. Bf4 $36 {And we can go on forever, but the general picture is clear, Black must be crazy accurate.}) (14... Be6 $2 $146 {Human move, but after the safe:} 15. c3 $1 {To destroy the center, White has a simple and clear advantage.} dxc3 16. Nxc3 $16 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 15. Qd3 Qd7 16. Qxh7 $146 {Taking the pawn is critical, but understandably as one might be in a blitz game, White was a bit scared.} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc8,Gd8] Black's idea.} 17. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3a6] We return to the game with tempo.} Kb7 18. Nd2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge5g3,Gc2c4] Visually, Black has some compensation, but if not careful, it can very soon disappear, after all, the long term advantages of White are very solid assets, while Black's center and activity might evaporate.} Bf5 $1 {That's why Black must be prepared for this line, and continue to play like an engine.} 19. Qa3 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge5d4] Bxd4 is threatened.} Bf8 $3 {[%csl Bf8] Key move.} (19... Rde8 $6 {Logical, but too slow.} 20. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] And this is the scenario that I was talking about:} cxb4 21. Qb3 $36 {[%csl Rb4,Rb7,Rd4][%cal Ga2a3,Ge5d4] The center fell apart, and White is seriously better.}) 20. c4 $5 {Positional try.} (20. b4 {Logical idea, but here it is a bit different.} cxb4 21. Qb3 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rc2,Gc8,Bf8][%cal Gc8c2] Black has counterplay against c2.}) 20... dxc4 21. Nxc4 Be6 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6d5] Black is ready to create some threats against g2.} 22. Qb3+ $1 {White includes this annoying check.} (22. Qd3 $4 {Be careful to not fall for this trap.} Qd5 $19 {[%csl Rc4,Ge6,Rg2][%cal Gd5c4,Gd5g2] The piece is lost, and this was the hidden idea behind 21...Be6.}) 22... Ka8 23. Qd3 Bd5 $1 {Best.} (23... Qd5 $4 {[%csl Rd5] Was winning 1 move ago, but now it's a game losing blunder.} 24. Nb6+ $3 {A royal fork.} axb6 25. Qa6# {[%csl Ra8] That's why we included 22.Qb3+!}) 24. f3 Bh6 25. b3 {[%cal Ge5g3] And if so far, I could somehow explain and understand what Black is doing, then this is a complete "cold shower move":} Be6 $3 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6f5] Absolutely the best, how many times has the bishop moved already?} 26. Bf4 $5 {[%csl Ra8,Gf4][%cal Rh6f4,Gd3e4] This move continues the crazy battle.} (26. Qe4+ {This leads to a repetition.} Bd5 27. Qd3 $11 {At this point, the opponent deserves it, but you can play on as well.}) 26... Bxf4 27. Qe4+ Bd5 28. Qxf4 Qh3 29. g3 {Black must still be accurate.} Rg6 $3 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Rc4d6,Gd8g8] Key move, to defend the d6 square for now and also swing the d8 rook.} 30. Nd2 Rdg8 31. Nf1 {[%csl Gg3] We defend g3, but sadly Black has the strong:} Rg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] And it's time to repeat moves.} 32. Qf6 R4g6 33. Qf4 Rg4 $11 {If you will ever make a draw like this, make sure to ask the arbiter if there is the Beauty Prize for the best game, since you will win it for sure!}) 10. Nc3 {The best move, and my main recommendation. It could be part of your repertoire for a long time. Black has two main tries: 10...0-0 and 10...c5, which will be analyzed in the next chapter.} (10. Qf3 $5 {This is the only decent alternative.} O-O 11. c4 $13 {A complicated position, Black can equalize, but if you would like to investigate it further, it's a good option to play.}) (10. f4 $6 {A positional mistake, but it was played against me by the FM Andreev.} c5 11. Nf3 {Was played, but is no better.} (11. Nb3 {[%csl Rb3] The knight is misplaced here.}) 11... O-O 12. Be3 Nc6 13. Re1 {Black is already better:} Rb8 14. b3 Bf5 15. Bf2 Nb4 16. Re2 d4 $17 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Gf5] And I was close to having a winning advantage already.}) (10. Qh5 $6 {This is also a mistake.} c5 $15 {[%csl Rd4] Not a good square for the knight.} 11. Nf5 $2 {Fails tactically.} g6 $1 12. Ng7+ Kf8 13. Qh6 Kg8 $1 $19 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g7] The knight is just lost.}) *

