{[%evp 0,35,28,23,23,23,23,2,2,-30,-6,-55,-55,-51,19,16,20,13,13,13,19,19,19,19,39,36,83,52,53,53,38,30,35,29,29,28,38,-26]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Nd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxd4 Nb8 $1 {[%csl Cb8] The most sound variation, I have also used it once with Black.} 10. Nc3 {The best move, and my main recommendation. It can be a part of your repertoire for a long time. Black has two main tries: 10...0-0 and 10...c5.} O-O {The best move for Black.} (10... c5 $6 {Is a bit premature.} 11. Ndb5 $1 {[%csl Rd5] Attacking the d5-pawn.} c6 12. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] This is an annoying check.} Bxd6 13. exd6 O-O {Necessary move.} (13... Qxd6 $4 {14 games continued like this, including one with GM Shirov, but it's a losing mistake.} 14. Re1+ $1 {The beginning of a forced sequence:} Be6 15. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd6][%cal Rd5e4] With tempo on the queen.} Qe7 16. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re7] Another tempo.} f6 17. Nxc5 {White wins with brute force.} Qxc5 18. Rxe6+ Kf7 19. Rxf6+ $3 $18 {[%csl Gf6] A beautiful tactic, as we can see in the game Jones-Shirov, 2020.} gxf6 20. Qh5+ Ke7 21. Re1+ Kd7 22. Qg4+ Kc7 23. Bf4+ Kb7 24. Qg7+ Nd7 25. Qxd7+ $18 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gf4e3] The rook enters, and it was soon game over.}) 14. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6] White holds onto the passed pawn.} Be6 (14... Qf6 15. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Gd6] It is impossible for Black to get rid of this pawn.}) 15. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4]} Nd7 16. Na4 $36 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gb2b3,Gf4g3] The pawn is a strong asset, White dominates on the dark squares.}) 11. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga1d1,Gf1e1] Preventing c5} a5 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Ga5a4,Ga8a6] Strong positional move with two ideas: a4, grabbing queenside space, and Ra6, activating the rook (c5 next).} (11... Be6 $6 {Was played in a few games, but it's not a challenging move.} 12. Qg3 $1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gc1h6] With a good tempo, threatening Bh6.} Kh8 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 Qd7 15. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc3a4] We want to create a blockade.} c5 16. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gc3e2,Rb8c6,Rc3d5] Black can't develop the knight to c6, due to the Nxd5 tactic, otherwise, White is ready to improve the knight either via e2-f4 or simply e4.}) (11... f6 $6 {Critical, but premature.} 12. e6 $1 {The pawn is an asset.} Re8 {The best, as played in Pichot-Durarbayli, 2024.} (12... Bc5 $6 13. Nce2 {[%csl Ge6] Black cannot easily capture it.} Re8 14. Qg4 $16 {White is better.}) 13. Qh5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gh5] An improvement.} Kh8 {Probably the best try, but still Black must show incredible accuracy merely to survive:} (13... g6 14. Qf3 {We are glad to have provoked g6.} Bc5 15. Be3 {[%csl Rf6] The pawn is a liability, and the structure is overall weaker.} Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Rxe6 17. Na4 $18 {[%csl Ga4,Ra8,Rb8,Rc5,Rc8,Gd4,Rf6][%cal Ga1e1] For the engine, this is close to a +2 advantage, with full domination.}) 14. Re1 Bc5 15. Be3 Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxe6 $1 {Necessary.} (16... Rxe6 $2 17. Qf7 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Rd8g8,Gf7c7] With a big advantage for White.}) 17. Re3 $36 {White has an big initiative for the missing pawn, for example:} c5 18. Rae1 $1 {With threats on the back rank.} cxd4 19. Rxe6 Rxe6 20. Rxe6 g6 21. Qxd5 {The endgame is pleasant for White.} Na6 $1 {The only move.} 22. Qxd8+ Rxd8 23. Ne4 $16 {With big chances to convert.}) (11... Re8 {The second most popular move, but not a special one.} 12. Re1 Bc5 {A better try.} (12... Bf8 $6 {Was played by GM Sokolov.} 13. Bf4 Be6 14. Rad1 Qc8 15. h3 a5 {This is how the game Can-Sokolov, CRO-chT 2023 continued, now we can improve with:} 16. b3 $5 $14 {[%cal Ra5a4,Ge1e3] To stop a4, and White is able to slowly improve the position with Re3.}) 13. Be3 Qh4 $1 {[%cal Rc3e2,Ge8e5,Ra1d1,Gc8g4] A strong move, using the fact the d4 cannot be easily protected.} (13... Bxd4 $2 {was played in the game Diermair-Buhmann, AUT-chT 2021, but it's a positonal concession.} 14. Bxd4 Qh4 15. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gf3c3] White has a large positonal advantage.}) 14. Qd1 $5 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Re8e5,Gd4f3] We can do it with the queen.} Bf8 15. f4 $14 {A slightly better position.}) (11... Qd7 {[%cal Gd7g4] A typical move and idea, Black is preparing Qg4.} 12. h3 $1 {[%cal Rd7g4,Gb8a6,Ga6c5,Gc5e6] Necessary to stop this.} Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] The best prophylactic move.} (12... Na6 $2 {Is part of Black's plan, but it fails tactically:} 13. Nxc6 $3 $146 {[%csl Bc6] A nice point.} Qxc6 14. Nxd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rc6,Re7][%cal Gd5e7] Black can't defend 3 pieces with one move, simple mathematics.}) (12... a5 $6 {Not the best.} 13. Qg3 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc1h6]} Kh8 14. Bg5 $16 {White is positionally better.}) 13. a3 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation, to hinder Black's development.} Na6 (13... Bf8 14. Bf4 Na6 15. Qg3 $132 {Playable position.}) 14. b4 $5 {[%csl Bb4] The point of our previous move.} (14. Rd1 {This is the concrete alternative.} Nc5 15. b4 Ne6 16. b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5,Rd5] This is the idea, to play against the d5-pawn.} Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bb7 18. bxc6 Qxc6 19. Nxd5 {The line is quite sharp:} Bc5 20. Rg4 $1 {[%cal Rc6d5,Gg4g7] Qxd5 is met with Rxg7!} h5 $1 {Best move.} 21. Nf6+ Kf8 {[%cal Gf6h7] White has at least a draw by repetition, or can play on with:} 22. Re4 Re6 23. Qxh5 gxf6 24. exf6 Bxf2+ $1 {The only move.} 25. Kh2 Ke8 $1 {The king must run.} 26. Rg4 Qd5 27. Rg8+ Kd7 28. Qxf7+ Kc6 29. Bf4 Rd6 30. Qxd5+ Rxd5 31. Rxa8 Bxa8 32. g4 $13 {The endgame is still tricky, but objectively equal.}) 14... Bf8 15. Bf4 c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Black must use this concrete resource:} 16. bxc5 c6 $1 {To defend d5.} 17. Na4 Nxc5 18. Nxc5 Bxc5 19. c3 $36 {Objectively, Black is fine, but White has some long term positional trumps.}) (11... c5 $4 {A blunder.} 12. Nxd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gd5e7,Rc5d4] With decisive threats.}) 12. Re1 {Simply some useful moves, and then Bd2-Rad1-h3. If Black waits, White's position will for sure be slightly better.} (12. Nf5 $6 {Premature.} Bxf5 13. Qxf5 Qd7 $1 14. Qd3 Na6 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e6] Black will improve the knight and even be slightly better.}) 12... a4 $1 {[%csl Ba4] This is Black's priority.} (12... Ra6 {Black's most common continuation.} 13. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Oa6,Ge1] Now it's a different story, Nf5 is a strong move, since the rook is too early on a6.} Bxf5 14. Qxf5 c5 {Black's best, played in the game Najer-Robson.} (14... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6] Black is ready to place the knight on the dream e6 square, this is why:} 15. Be3 $1 $146 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Rd7c5,Ge3c5] is a very important positional idea. We want to trade the knight as soon as possible, as it's the only minor piece than can defend on the light squares.} Nc5 16. Bxc5 $1 {The point.} Bxc5 17. Na4 Be7 18. b3 c5 19. Rad1 Re6 20. Qd3 c6 21. f4 $16 {[%csl Ba4,Re7][%cal Gc2c4] Typical good knight vs bad bishop scenario.}) (14... Qd7 15. Qd3 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Rb8a6] Here the point of 13.Nf5 is well highlighted.} Ra8 {Black's best, but okay, we are ready to play the same position with 2 extra tempi:} 16. Be3 Na6 17. Rad1 Nc5 18. Bxc5 Bxc5 19. g3 $14 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gf2f4] With a positional advantage.}) 15. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Rd5] A strong improvement.} d4 (15... c6 $2 16. b3 $16 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc3a4] The rook is out of the game.}) 16. Ne4 $14 {Black for sure didn't equalize, White has solid positional trumps.}) 13. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2] That's why, the bishop is placed on d2 for the moment, and it's not a bad square.} (13. Bf4 $6 {[%cal Rd4f5] Not wise, as there is no Nf5 move in the future.} Ra6 14. Rad1 c5 $132 {[%cal Rd4f5] Nf5 is impossible.}) 13... Ra6 {A human move.} (13... a3 {was seen in the game Wagner-Perez, 2021, but after:} 14. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra3,Gb3] Was a good inclusion for White.}) (13... Re8 $146 {A logical move.} 14. Rad1 Bf8 {For the engine this is fine, but from human perspective it looks risky for Black, for example:} 15. Qg3 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7g4] The best move, with the idea of Qg4.} 16. h3 {[%cal Rd7g4] We prevent this.} c5 $1 17. Nf3 Bb7 18. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2f4] White is ready for Nf4, but Black has a strong idea:} Qf5 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Gf5] To target the c2 pawn.} 19. Nh4 Qxc2 20. Bh6 Nd7 21. Nc3 Nxe5 {And unfortunately White doesn't have any advantage:} 22. Rd2 $5 {[%csl Rc2] Wait, isn't the queen on c2 trapped?} (22. Rxe5 {This leads to a forced draw:} Rxe5 23. Qxe5 d4 24. Rc1 Qxb2 25. Nf5 gxh6 26. Qg3+ Kh8 27. Qe5+ $11) 22... Nf3+ $3 {[%csl Bf3] A fantastic tactical trick, and the reason why this whole line is possible to play with Black.} 23. Nxf3 Rxe1+ 24. Nxe1 Qc1 $1 {[%csl Gc1] Despite all odds, the queen is safe on c1.} 25. Nd1 d4 $1 {And in this crazy mess, the computer assessment is balanced.} 26. Qxc7 gxh6 27. Rxd4 $11) 14. Nf5 {Straight-forward.} (14. Rad1 $5 $146 {This novelty leads to a playable position.} c5 15. Nf5 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Rc3d5,Gc8f5]} 16. Nxe7+ {We capture the bishop so that we can play on the dark squares.} Nxe7 17. Bg5 c6 18. Qg3 Qc7 19. e6 $5 {An interesting decision.} Qxg3 20. exf7+ Rxf7 21. hxg3 $36 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg3g4,Gb2b3] The endgame can be slightly annoying to play from the Black side.}) 14... Bxf5 15. Qxf5 Nd7 {[%csl Ca4][%cal Gd7c5] Thanks to the pawn on a4, White cannot stop the positional idea of Nc5.} 16. Rad1 {White should just develop.} (16. Be3 $6 {We don't play this move anymore.} a3 $1 {Black's idea.} 17. b3 Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Rc3][%cal Rf5e5,Re7f6] This is the point.} 18. Qxe5 Bf6 $132) 16... Nc5 17. Ne2 Ne4 {The best.} (17... Ne6 18. Qg4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] The f-pawn runs down the board and White is better.}) 18. Qh3 $14 {[%cal Gh3d3] The queen can be maneuvered to the center, and it's slightly more pleasant to play for White, for a long time.} *

