{[%evp 0,15,31,31,6,13,13,2,2,-19,0,-15,-15,-15,-26,-34,59,-17]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 {The best way for Black.} 8. Be3 {[%csl Ce3] This is our recommendation.} (8. Nxc6 $5 {A bit of a crazy try.} Bxf2+ 9. Kf1 bxc6 (9... Qh4 $11) 10. Bxc6+ Kf8 $13 {Objectively equal, but I don't believe that Black is risking more than White.}) 8... O-O $1 {[%csl Bg8] The best line.} (8... Bd7 {The old main line.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nd2 $1 $14 {[%csl Bd2] Key move, to eliminate Black's strongest piece.} Nxd2 {Black must capture the knight.} (10... Qe7 $2 {A logical move, but it fails to the nice sequence:} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. e6 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Be6,Re8][%cal Gd1h5] A typical resource, using the vulnerability of the bishop on c5.} fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 {[%csl Ge5] The queen is very strong in the center.} O-O 15. Nxc6 $1 {A small tactic, and White is better after:} Bxc6 16. Bxc5 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Rxf6 18. O-O-O $16 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6] Probably this endgame is objectively winning for White, thanks to the much better bishop and structure.}) (10... O-O $2 {Blunders material.} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nxc6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc5] Common tactic.}) (10... Qh4 $6 {Quite a common try, but the queen is simply misplaced on h4.} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 $1 {[%csl Re4,Gf4,Rh4] To disrupt the connection between the queen and the knight.} Bb6 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7,Ge3,Re4][%cal Ge2c4] With a straight forward positional advantage.}) 11. Qxd2 Bb6 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black has the positional threat of c5.} (11... O-O {Is another move order to get to the same position.} 12. Nb3 Bb6 (12... Bxe3 $2 {Positional mistake.} 13. Qxe3 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Gc5,Rd7][%cal Ge1g1,Gf2f4] Dream scenario in the Scotch Gambit, a good knight vs a bad bishop.}) 13. O-O {Transposes to 11...Bb6.}) (11... Qe7 {A common move, but the queen is not great on this square.} 12. O-O O-O 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rf7f6] Tough to come up with a plan for Black.}) 12. Nb3 $1 {[%cal Rc6c5] For this reason, White must stop it.} O-O 13. O-O a5 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5a4] This is Black's best try, to pose a question to the knight on b3.} (13... f6 $6 {A common plan, but it doesn't solve Black's problems.} 14. exf6 Qxf6 15. Nc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] The only move to fight for the advantage.} Bf5 16. c3 $16 {[%csl Cc5][%cal Gf2f3,Ge3d4,Ga1e1] White has great control of the dark squares, and Black has no counterplay.}) 14. Qc3 a4 15. Nc5 Qe7 16. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] A good reaction, to reinforce the knight.} axb3 17. axb3 {This is the best position Black can achieve after 8...Bd7, it is holdable with correct play, but quite unpleasant, for example:} h6 18. b4 Bf5 19. h3 $5 {[%csl Gh3] White can slowly improve.} Rfe8 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. g4 Bg6 22. f3 $14 {[%cal Gg1h2,Gh2g3,Gh2h4,Ge3d4] Or the more aggresive 22.f4, it's +0.30 evaluation, not a lot, but the point is that White has a pleasant and playable position.}) (8... Bxd4 $2 {Has been played in some games, but it's a mistake.} 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] To eliminate the last minor piece that can control the dark squares, and White is better.} Bf5 {Black finishes development and now it's a good time to trade the knights:} (11... Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e6] Was tried in the majority of the games, but it's time consuming.} 12. O-O-O Ne6 13. Qa4 Bd7 14. Qa3 $1 {[%csl Ba3,Rc5,Rd4] A good prophylactic move against c5.} f6 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd7][%cal Ge4c5,Rd5e4] The best move for a big advantage.} Qg6 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. Qxc5 $16 {[%csl Gc5,Ge3,Rg7][%cal Ge3d4,Gg6g2,Gh1g1] +1 for the engine.}) 12. Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Ge4] Key move.} (12. O-O-O $2 {Was played by GM Nevednichy against GM Banusz in the Romanian Team Championship 2013, but it allowed Black to obtain counterplay:} c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Even at the cost of a pawn, this move is quite strong.} 13. Qd3 c4 14. Qxd5 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qc8 $44 {Black has full compensation.}) 12... Bxe4 13. O-O-O {[%cal Rc6c5] The main difference is that now Black doesn't have the c5 counter-strike.} Qe7 14. f3 Bg6 {This is how the old game Sveshnikov-Gligoric, YUG Cup 1999 continued.} 15. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Rc5,Rd4,Ge3][%cal Ge3c5] Good move to open the diagonal for the bishop.} Rfe8 16. Bd4 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] White can slowly expand on the kingside, Black is doomed.}) 9. Nxc6 {White should enter into this semi-concrete line:} (9. Bxc6 $6 {This is not a challenging option.} bxc6 10. O-O (10. Nxc6 $4 {Taking on c6 falls into a famous trap.} Bxe3 $3 {[%csl Ce3] Brilliant intermezzo.} 11. Nxd8 Bxf2+ {[%cal Re1e2,Gc8g4,Re1f1,Gc8a6] And no matter where the king moves, the queen is lost.} 12. Kf1 Ba6+ $19) 10... Qe8 $36 {With a very comfortable position for Black.}) 9... bxc6 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. Qxd5 {For the moment, White won two pawns, but the theory only begins here.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Be7] The best move.} (12... Qxd5 {[%csl Rd5] Entering the endgame is quite risky for Black:} 13. Bxd5 Rxb2 14. Na3 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] I don't want to say that it's lost, but White can for sure try to convert the extra material.} Rb4 $1 {This rare move is the best, according to the engine.} (14... Ba6 $2 {Most common move, but a mistake.} 15. O-O-O Rb4 16. Rhe1 $16 {[%csl Gd1,Gd5,Ge1] Black has no compensation for the pawn, and in fact, White scored 100% out of 7 games that reached this position.}) (14... Be6 {The second most common move.} 15. O-O-O $1 {[%csl Rb2] Good tempo.} Rb4 16. Rhe1 Rfb8 17. g3 {White is better, it's tough to see how Black should hold.} Ra4 (17... g5 {The best for the engine, but what next?} 18. Re3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7][%cal Ge3c3] Followed by Rc3.}) 18. Nb1 Rab4 19. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3] White simply improved the knight.}) 15. O-O-O $146 {The position is already new.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Be4][%cal Gb4e4] This is Black's idea.} 16. Rde1 $5 {We can gain a tempo against the knight.} Nc3 $1 {This is the best, but includes very difficult moves.} (16... Nxf2 $2 {A logical human move, but quite bad.} 17. Rhf1 Ng4 18. h3 Nh6 19. g4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge1,Gf1,Rh6][%cal Ga3c4] The knight is misplaced on h6.}) 17. Bb3 Be6 $1 {[%csl Be6] Black must be accurate all the way.} 18. Re3 Nd5 19. Rf3 Re4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Re5] When engines are playing, it's quite difficult to distinguish it from magic, suddenly Black is regaining the pawn on e5.} 20. Rd1 Rxe5 21. Nb5 a6 22. Nd4 $14 {Still, White can try to push, thanks to the better pieces.}) 13. O-O Rxb2 {The main line.} (13... Ba6 14. Re1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge1e5] I think the rook is more useful on e1.} (14. Rc1 $5 {A possible move, but I don't believe in it too much.} Rfd8 15. Qf3 Ne6 16. Nc3 Nd4 17. Qe4 $13 {Unclear, but playable position.}) 14... Rxb2 {Forcing try.} (14... Rfd8 {Was played in the game Atabayev-Delchev, 2020.} 15. Qf3 Rxb2 16. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Bc3] A strong tempo against b2.} Rb6 17. Bf3 Na4 18. Qa3 {White went into the endgame.} Qxa3 19. Nxa3 $14 {For the engine, this is not a big advantage, Black has some compensation, but for sure White can try to play.}) 15. Qd2 Nd3 $1 {[%csl Bd3] A nice move, using the pin.} (15... Ne6 {Positional, but slow.} 16. Nc3 Rd8 17. Qc1 Rb6 18. Ba4 $14 {[%cal Ga4b3] White finishes development and is just better.}) (15... Rd8 16. Qc3 {And we transpose to the Atabayev-Delchev game.}) 16. Re3 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rc2][%cal Gb4c2,Gb4a2] A smart maneuver to attack both pawns.} 17. Be4 Rd8 18. Qc1 Rxa2 19. Nc3 Rxa1 20. Qxa1 $36 {For the engine, this is +0.20, so it's safe to say that White has at least some initiative thanks to the potential on the kingside.}) (13... Rd8 14. Qf3 Rxb2 {Transposes to the main line.} (14... Qxe5 $2 {A logical, but bad move.} 15. Nc3 Rxb2 16. Nd5 $1 $40 {[%csl Cc6,Cd5,Rd8,Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ga1d1] Black is actually in a lot of trouble.})) 14. Nc3 {Black has two tries with an equal amount of 64 games: 14...Rd8 or 14...Rxc2.} Rxc2 {This is the most challenging, Black aims to kill the game in a concrete manner.} (14... Rd8 {This is more positional, Black aims to finish development.} 15. Qf3 Ne6 {The most common move, by far.} (15... Rxc2 16. Rad1 $36 {White gets control of the d5 square, with a typical initiative.}) (15... Qxe5 $2 16. Nd5 $1 $40 {[%csl Cc6,Cd5,Re5][%cal Gf1e1,Ga1d1] Standard motif.}) 16. Rfd1 $5 {[%csl Bd1] This is probably White's most interesting try.} (16. Be4 {Is met with:} Ng5 $1 $11 {[%csl Bg5] And Black is fine.}) (16. Rad1 {[%csl Rd1] I think this is less precise, as after:} Nd4 $1 (16... Rxc2 17. Be4 Rb2 18. Nd5) 17. Qe4 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Black has this extra idea.} 18. Nd5 $5 Bxe4 19. Nxe7+ Kf8 20. Bxe4 Ne2+ $1 $132 {[%csl Be2,Rf1][%cal Rg1h1] White is forced to go away from the center, due to the rook still being on f1.}) 16... Nd4 $1 17. Qe4 Nxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6] Black captures our strong bishop, and in the arising position:} (17... Bf5 {Concrete try, but compared to 16.Rad1, after the complications:} 18. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} Bxe4 19. Nxe7+ Kf8 20. Bxe4 Ne2+ 21. Kf1 $1 {[%csl Bf1] White's king can go to f1, and it's a serious improvement.} Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Nc3 23. Re1 Nxe4 24. Rxe4 Kxe7 25. Rc4 $14 {Of course, engine will make a draw with Black, but it's not 100%, at some point Black will need to make a decision and it's not guaranteed that it will be the correct one.}) 18. Qxc6 Bb7 {[%csl Gb7] The bishop on b7 is quite strong.} 19. Qc4 (19. Qa4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 19... Re8 20. Re1 {However, White keeps some ideas, for example:} Rb4 21. Qd3 Qc5 22. Rad1 h6 23. Qg3 {[%csl Gd1,Ge1][%cal Ge5e6,Gd1d7] Everything is centralized, and White is ready to strike with e6!} Bc6 24. e6 Rxe6 25. Rxe6 fxe6 26. h3 $132 {[%csl Rg8] No objective advantage, but White can play on, since White's king is much safer than the one on g8, so we can't say that this position is a dead draw.}) 15. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4e5,Gc3d5,Gd4c3] White defends the c3 knight, and at the same time prepares the knight jump.} Ne6 $1 (15... Be6 $6 {Logical, but quite slow.} 16. Rfd1 h6 17. h3 $14 {[%csl Rc7] White is slightly better for a long time, thanks to the better structure and pieces.}) (15... Ba6 $2 {Was played in the game Lu Miaoyi-Spasic, 2022 ,but Black soon ended up in a lost position.} 16. Nd5 $1 Qg5 17. Rfd1 Rc4 18. Qb2 Kh8 19. Ne3 Rh4 20. Qa3 $1 {The young talent did everything correct:} Qxe5 21. g3 Rd4 22. Rxd4 Qxd4 23. Rc1 $18 {[%csl Ba3,Ra6,Rc5,Rf8] Lu won a piece and soon the game.}) 16. Qd3 Rb2 17. Nd5 {This is my recommendation.} (17. Qe3 {Was played in the game Bersamina-Sargissian, Olympiad 2024.} Bd7 $1 $11 {A clean equalizer, I couldn't find any idea.} (17... Qc5 $6 {This was Gabriel's move, but the endgame can be more pleasant for White after:} 18. Qxc5 Nxc5 19. f4 $5 $146 {Small practical chances.})) 17... Qc5 18. Rac1 {Critical try.} (18. Qe3 {I don't believe too much in this version of the endgame:} Qxe3 $1 $146 19. fxe3 Ba6 {Black is doing fine.} 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Rf2 Rxf2 22. Kxf2 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Gf2f3] Still, if you are fine with a risk free and equal endgame, this is more or less playable.}) 18... Qd4 19. Qf5 $5 {[%csl Bf5] This is interesting, to protect the e5 pawn, there are only 6 games here, and Black, even after all of these good moves, must show precision.} (19. Qa3 {was played in the game Najer-Matlakov, RUS-ch 2022.} Qxe5 {Soon, players agreed to a draw after:} 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 22. Bd7 Rd8 23. Bxe6 fxe6 24. Qxa7 $11 {Of course, only with equality.}) 19... Kh8 $1 {This move is the strongest one and was recommended by GM Roiz in his course.} (19... Qh4 {[%csl Gh4] Black argues that the queen is better on the kingside, to protect the king.} 20. g3 Qh6 $1 $146 {The best, but this whole idea is a bit artificial, for example:} (20... Nd4 $2 {Has been played in all of the 3 games that reached this position, but it's an unfortunate intermezzo.} 21. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Bd3] Strong reply.} Qg4 22. Ne7+ Kh8 23. Rc4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc4g4] Black has concrete problems.} Ne2+ 24. Kh1 Ba6 25. Qxh7+ $1 {A neat tactic.} Kxh7 26. Rxg4 {[%cal Gg4h4] Rh4# is threatened.} g6 27. Re1 $16 {White is better in the endgame.}) 21. Qd3 Rxa2 22. Ne7+ Kh8 23. Nxc8 Rxc8 24. Rcd1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd1,Gd3][%cal Gc6a8,Gc6e8] White gains access to the d-file, and of course, is not risking anything, thanks to the superior bishop.} Kg8 25. Bd5 Rb2 26. Qa3 $36 {With practical chances.}) (19... Ba6 $6 {After this general active move, White has chances:} 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Be4 $1 {[%csl Rh7] A strong tempo.} Ng5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Necesary defense.} 22. Qxg5 Qxe4 23. Rfe1 Re2 24. Rxe2 Qxe2 25. h3 $14 {Slightly better for a long time.}) 20. Rcd1 $5 $146 {We are already in new territory.} Rd2 {Roiz stops here saying that Black is fine, I went a bit further:} (20... Qh4 {Possible move.} 21. Qd3 {White will try to ''fish'' for Black's mistake:} Rxa2 22. Qb3 Re2 23. Qa3 Qc4 24. Nxc7 $5 {[%csl Gc7] Some small tactics here and there.} Qc5 $1 25. Qxc5 Nxc5 26. f4 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4,Yf7,Gg2,Yg7,Gh2,Yh7] And White can most likely obtain a 4vs3 on the kingside, which is objectively drawn, but with practical chances.}) 21. Ne3 $5 {A tricky move, to hold the d-file, we must check Black's discoveries with the knight:} Nc5 $1 {The best for the engine.} (21... Nf4 {Leads to a playable endgame.} 22. Rxd2 $1 Bxf5 23. Rxd4 Ne2+ $1 {Black's point.} 24. Kh1 Nxd4 25. Bd5 Be6 26. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rc7] c7 is weak, rook and knight endgames are very tricky, so I wouldn't be surprised if White will ocasionally win this.}) 22. e6 $1 {A cool move, using the fact that Bxe6 is not possible.} Nxe6 {Necessary.} (22... Bxe6 $4 23. Rxd2 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rd4][%cal Gf5c5] Intermezzo, White wins a piece.}) 23. Rxd2 Qxd2 24. Be4 $1 {Looks scary for Black, but he is just in time to defend:} g6 25. Qf6+ Ng7 $1 {[%csl Bg7] Only move.} (25... Kg8 $4 {Is terrible.} 26. Rd1 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd2,Rh6][%cal Ge3g4] To kick the queen away from the h6 square, Ng4 next and Black can resign.}) 26. Bd5 Kg8 27. h3 $44 {[%cal Gf1d1] White has full compensation, there is some piece activity. Black is a bit passive, that's why I wouldn't be opposed to play this position, although objectively, Black is okay.} *

