{[%evp 0,39,24,8,8,25,28,14,23,-39,-55,-62,-58,-51,-51,-11,-45,-27,-25,-25,-7,-10,-9,-32,2,-16,6,-51,0,0,11,10,7,-10,-4,-33,-15,2,16,12,8,-10]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6] White must ruin Black's structure.} (8. O-O $2 {too slow.} Nxd4 $1 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd4 Bc5 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge4] Black has no structural problems and is just slightly better. Black is slightly better.}) 8... bxc6 (8... Bxc6 $6 {Small sideline, but it's not very sensible.} 9. O-O Bc5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nd2 {White succesfully ruined Black's structure and in Black has nothing to show for it in return.} Nxd2 12. Qxd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gc1e3] White has easy development next and is slightly better, for example:} O-O 13. Qc3 Qe7 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f5,Gc2c3] White can play both on the kingside and in the center, and it doesn't matter that all minor pieces got traded off the board.}) 9. O-O {The starting position of the main line. Black has two plausible replies: 9...Be7 or 9...Bc5.} Be7 $5 {This is an old line, but objectively it has the same strength as the more active Bc5. That's why ocasionally this is used by strong players as well.} 10. f3 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3f4] White's idea is to first kick the knight from e4 before going f4, this way we win a tempo.} Nc5 (10... Ng5 11. f4 {[%csl Rg5] will transpose to the main line, it's just a less flexible move order for Black.}) 11. f4 O-O $1 {Black's most common and best try.} (11... f5 {[%csl Ge5] It's not so bad to stop f5 with brute force, but this move gives White a defended passed pawn for free.} 12. Be3 O-O 13. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2b3,Gh2h3,Gg1h2,Yd4b3] White is the one holding all the positional trumps, there is no rush in the position, just slow improvement.}) (11... Ne4 $6 {It was played in 1/3 of the games that reached this position, but it's not a great idea.} 12. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Re4][%cal Gc3e4] White trades Black's most active piece.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 c5 $5 {[%csl Gc5] Black's best bet is to improve the pawn structure.} (13... O-O $2 {Common mistake.} 14. f5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Rg8][%cal Gf5f6] White gains all the space.} c5 15. Nb3 c4 16. Nd4 c5 17. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rg8] 20 games continued this way, but White is close to having a winning advantage.}) 14. Nb3 c4 15. Nd4 c5 16. Ne2 Bc6 {However Black's position is still super risky:} 17. Ng3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg3f5,Rg7g6] We plan to go Nf5 or provoke g6, which is a clear concession.}) (11... f6 $4 {Terrible mistake.} 12. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Rc5e4,Ge5e6] If the knight moves to e4, White has e6 winning material.} Ne6 13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. f5 $18 {[%csl Re8,Gf5][%cal Ge5e6,Re6c8,Gd1h5,Re6g8] The position is just doomed.}) 12. f5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] White achieves f5, and the position becomes concrete, since Black must have a reaction, otherwise he gets run over.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rf5f6,Gc6c5] Black gets the knight to e4, stopping f6 and also preparing c5.} (12... Re8 {Common try, but has little independent value.} 13. Nc3 Ne4 {will transpose to the main line after:} (13... Bf8 $6 {Common move, but quite slow.} 14. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gd1g4,Yf4g3,Yf5f6] White has a very strong attack brewing on the kingside.}) (13... Bg5 $6 {This relies on a trick, but otherwise, it's not so sensible.} 14. Bxg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] We must start by first trading the g5 bishop.} (14. Qe2 $2 {Falls for it.} Bxc1 $1 (14... Bf6 $5 {[%csl Re5,Gf6][%cal Gf6e5] More sophisticated, but also works.}) 15. Raxc1 Ne4 $1 $36 {[%csl Re2,Re5][%cal Ge8e5,Rc3e4] The e5 pawn falls thanks to the pin.}) 14... Qxg5 15. Qe2 $2 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf1f3,Gf3g3] On high depths, this is already a close to winning advantage for White.}) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nb3 {See under 12...Ne4.}) 13. Nb3 $5 {[%csl Bb3] I think this is White's best try, it's an useful prophylactic move.} Re8 {More human approach.} (13... a5 $5 {was only tried in correspondence games, so it's difficult to say how likely it is to happen.} 14. a4 Re8 {[%csl Ya4,Ya5] We get the main line with the moves a4 and a5 included, so in essence, it will be very similar:} 15. N1d2 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Re4] Once again, White trades Black's most active piece.} Bc5+ $1 {[%csl Bc5] Engine's idea.} 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. e6 $5 {[%csl Be6] If you are in the mood for romantical chess, this is a nice option:} (17. b3 $5 {The easiest choice.} Rxe5 18. f6 $1 $36 {[%csl Gb2,Gc1,Rc5,Rg7][%cal Gc1b2,Gc1a3,Gd2f3] The engine is not scared, but over the board, it looks like a very risky position for Black, especially since the dark squares bishop is free to do damage on the long diagonal and on the weaknesses.}) 17... fxe6 18. f6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] This is the point.} gxf6 19. b4 $1 {White sacrifices all the pawns, to get the pieces active.} Nb7 $1 {[%csl Bb7] This is Black's necessary move, so you can see why 13...a5 hasn't yet been played in over the board games.} (19... axb4 $6 {Taking is quite dangerous.} 20. Qg4+ $1 {[%csl Rb4,Rg8][%cal Gg4g8,Gg4b4] Double attack.} Kh8 21. Qxb4 Ne4 $1 {Necessary.} (21... Na6 $2 22. Qh4 $18 {[%csl Rf6,Rh8] White has a winning attack.}) 22. Nxe4 dxe4 23. Be3 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Rd7,Ge3][%cal Ga4a7] White is clearly better thanks to the passed pawn and dark squares domination.}) 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Bb2 e5 22. Qh4 $13 {[%csl Rh8] For the engine, it's equal, but of course Black is the one who has to be super careful here.}) 14. N1d2 Bf8 $1 {[%csl Re5] Black creates counterplay against the e5 pawn.} (14... Bc5+ {Similar to 13...a5.} 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. e6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] In this scenario, this motive works even better:} (16. b3 $5 $146 {Simple option.} Rxe5 17. f6 $36 {[%cal Gc1b2] With initiative for White.}) 16... fxe6 17. f6 $1 gxf6 18. Qg4+ Kh8 19. Qd4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rd8e7,Gb2b4] Qe7 is met with b4, White has a very good grip on the dark squares.}) (14... Nxd2 $2 {Positional mistake.} 15. Bxd2 Bf8 16. Bc3 $1 $40 {[%csl Gb3,Gc3,Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gd1f3] White is just too fast with the attack.}) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qd4 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Re4,Ge5][%cal Gd4e5,Rd4e4] I like this option played by Carlsen and Vocaturo. White attacks e4 and defends e5.} (16. Bf4 {The most common move, but Black can equalize with a strong sequence:} Bxf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Wins the important f-pawn.} 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 18. Bg5 g6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] Key move, and Black is doing fine in the arising endgame:} 19. Bxd8 Rxd8 20. Rad1 Re8 $11 {3 correspondence games ended in a draw, so I guess Black should have okay chances to hold.}) 16... Bc8 $1 {This is the best reply, played in Vocaturo-Gledura, Barcelona 2017.} (16... Qe7 $6 {was played in Carlsen-Le Quang, Miami FTX 2022.} 17. f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] White must be concrete:} gxf6 18. exf6 Qd6 19. Qf2 $5 {[%csl Gf2] Carlsen correctly kept queens on the board.} Qe5 20. Bf4 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf4] Even better than 20.Be3.} Qxf6 21. Rae1 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Ge1,Gf1,Gf2,Gf4] Every piece is working in White's camp, White has a great positional bind.}) 17. Be3 $1 {[%csl Ge3] Good improvement, we just keep the tension and our dark square control.} (17. Qc3 $2 {GM Vocaturo went wrong.} Qd5 $1 {[%csl Re5] And White can't defend e5.} 18. Bf4 Bxf5 $1 $15 {Black was just a pawn up and later on converted the material advantage.}) 17... Qd5 {The most logical move.} (17... Qxd4 18. Bxd4 $14 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga1e1] White is slightly better thanks to the control and extra space.}) (17... a5 {Engine's best reply.} 18. Rae1 {Good solid option.} (18. a4 $5 $146 {Maybe even better.} Qe7 19. e6 fxe6 20. f6 $1 {[%csl Ra5] a5 is going to be a long term weakness.} gxf6 21. Qxe4 $44 {White has full compensation, and some human initiative.}) 18... Qe7 {[%cal Re3f4,Gc8f5]} 19. e6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] We must give up the pawn, since holding onto it was not an option.} fxe6 20. f6 $1 {Standard reaction for this line.} gxf6 21. Qxe4 $13 {Unclear position, but very difficult to play with Black.} (21. Qxf6 $11 {Risk free endgame.})) 18. e6 $1 {[%csl Be6] Key concept to remember.} Qxd4 $1 {First Black should capture the queen.} (18... fxe6 $4 {This is a blunder now.} 19. f6 $1 {[%csl Gf6] The pawn is too strong.} Qxd4 20. f7+ $1 $18 {[%csl Re8,Gf7,Rg8][%cal Gf7e8,Gf7g8] White gives mate.}) 19. Bxd4 fxe6 20. f6 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7,Re4,Re6] White is definitely slightly better thanks to the ruined pawn structure.} *

