{[%evp 0,43,20,20,20,20,18,18,18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18,-25,-25,-29,-33,-29,-11,-30,-30,-30,-30,-74,-76,-104,-104,-96,-86,-82,-116,-118,-108,-130,-119,-1,-94,-85]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 {[%csl Bc5] The main line. You should be expecting to face this quite often, since this move has a good reputation and is consistently used at all levels.} 10. f3 $1 {White should include this move.} (10. Be3 $6 {Wrong move order.} Qe7 $1 {[%cal Re7e5] To put pressure on e5.} 11. f3 Nd6 $1 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd6f5] Using the pin and Black is more than fine.}) 10... Ng5 11. f4 {White's most testing line.} Ne4 {Most common.} (11... Ne6 {Positional line, but a bit passive.} 12. c3 f5 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5] This is Black's point, to blockade the passed e5 pawn.} 13. Na3 $5 {This is my recommendation, and it's a new move. The idea is to support the d4 knight.} (13. Be3 $6 {is by far the most played move, but actually it gives Black the chance to equalize:} Bxd4 $1 {Very active decision.} 14. cxd4 c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Bd5d4] The point.} 15. dxc5 d4 16. Bxd4 Bc6 $11 {[%cal Gg7g5] g5 will come at some moment, and Black has enough compensation to equalize.}) 13... O-O (13... Bxa3 {Not scary.} 14. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Rd7] The important asset is the undisputed c1 bishop.} O-O 15. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ga3a4,Gc1a3] White is slightly better.}) 14. Nac2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a3,Gc1e3,Gg1h1] White can slowly create a bind on the dark squares, and enjoys a positional advantage.}) 12. Be3 {Black has some options.} Bb6 {The old main line.} (12... Qb8 $1 {[%csl Bb8] The modern line, which according to the engine is the best try.} 13. Nd2 $5 {I prefer to go for this tricky line, since Black is forced to capture the pawn on b2, which carries out some risk.} (13. b3 $132 {[%cal Rd4b3] Playable move, but Black is fine with a lot of moves, and this is the point behind Qb8, to eliminate the option of going Nb3.}) 13... Qxb2 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qd2 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf4f5,Ge5e6,Gf5f6,Yd4b3] White's compensation is straight-forward: potential kingside attack, better development and bind on the dark squares.} Rd8 {The most common move.} (15... Qb4 {Second most common move, Black improves the queen.} 16. Qf2 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Gf2][%cal Gd4c6,Gd4f5] Both Nxc6 and Nf5 are serious threats.} Qc3 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc3e3] The best move, to pin the knight to the bishop.} (16... Bb6 {is met with:} 17. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Rb6][%cal Ga4a5] To further put pressure on the bishop, typical idea.} a5 {Necessary, but it is a good inclusion for White.} (17... O-O $2 {Mistake.} 18. a5 $1 {[%csl Rb6] White's point.} Bxa5 $4 19. Rfb1 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4] White will win a piece thanks to the bad coordination.} Qc3 20. Ne2 $18 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Rc3c2,Gb1c1] The piece drops.}) 18. f5 {[%csl Ga7,Rb6,Rc7] We can go f5 now, since the bishop on b6 is more vulnerable and we have more ideas against it.} O-O 19. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Gf5f6] White has a good advantage.}) (16... Qc4 $6 {Common move, but White has a lot of freedom.} 17. h3 $5 {[%csl Gh3] There is no hurry to do anything.} O-O 18. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3] White has a very pleasant position.}) 17. Rfe1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ge1e3] White can protet the bishop.} O-O (17... Bb6 {was tried in another email game.} 18. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4] Key idea.} a5 $1 (18... O-O $2 19. a5 $1 {[%csl Rb6] The bishop is in trouble.} Bxa5 20. Ne2 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Rc3] Wins material.}) 19. Nb3 O-O (19... Bxe3 $6 20. Rxe3 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rd7,Ge3,Gf2] Great scenario for White.}) 20. Bxb6 cxb6 21. Re3 Qb2 $1 {[%csl Gb2,Re5][%cal Rf4f5] Last precise move Black should know.} (21... Qb4 $6 {looks logical, but not the most precise.} 22. f5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rb4,Ge5,Gf5,Rg8][%cal Ge3g3] This move is possible, and White has a huge attack.}) 22. Qe1 $11 {[%cal Ge3c3,Ga1b1,Gb1a1] Soon, it will be a draw by repetition.}) 18. Nxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc6e7,Rc5e3] White uses a standard tactical shot.} (18. Nb3 $5 {also possible.}) 18... Ba3 $1 {Best move for Black.} (18... Bxe3 19. Ne7+ Kh8 20. Qxe3 $14 {The endgame is better for White.}) 19. Nd4 a5 $1 $13 {The position is quite unclear, but playable.}) (15... O-O 16. Nb3 $5 {Good positional option.} (16. a3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf1b1] Straight-forward try.} Rab8 17. Rfb1 Qxb1+ 18. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 19. Kf2 Bxa3 20. Nb5 $36 {[%cal Gf4f5,Ge5e6,Gd2d7] Black needs to be very careful to equalize.}) 16... Bxe3+ 17. Qxe3 Be6 {We are following an old game: Trent-Mamedyarov, Wch U16 2001.} 18. Qc5 $146 {Improvement.} Bxb3 19. axb3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7] Even though all the minor pieces are off the board, White is slightly better thanks to the structure.}) (15... Rb8 $2 {was played in two games, but it's mistake.} 16. Rab1 $1 {[%csl Bb1] Key idea.} Qxb1 17. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 18. Kf2 $16 {[%csl Re8] White has a better version, and is much better.}) 16. Rab1 Qxa2 $1 {Black should accept the second pawn, but this looks too scary for a human eye.} (16... Qa3 $6 {Black invites us to win another tempo, and we will happily do so:} 17. Rb3 $1 {[%csl Gb3] The rook is useful on b3, as it can later swing to the kingside.} Qa6 (17... Qa4 18. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] Important move.} Be7 $1 (18... Bb6 $4 19. Ra3 $18 {[%csl Ra4] Black loses the queen.}) 19. f5 $1 $40 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gf5f6] White goes for the standard attack, although several moves are good.}) 18. f5 {[%csl Ge5,Re8,Gf5] Black's position is very unpleasant already.} Bb6 (18... Qc4 $4 {was played in a human game, but it turned out to be losing after:} 19. Rc3 $1 $146 {[%csl Gc3,Rc4,Rc5] Good improvement.} Qb4 20. Rxc5 $1 Qxc5 21. Ne6 $18 {[%cal Ge6d8,Ge6g7] Black is doomed.}) 19. Rxb6 $5 {[%csl Gb6] We can go for this nice positional sacrifice.} (19. Bg5 $5 {also good and simple.}) 19... axb6 20. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Rd7,Rd8,Ge5,Re8,Gf5,Gg5] White has huge control over the position.}) 17. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb1a1] There are only corr. games here.} Bb6 18. Nb3 $5 {Simple option.} (18. Nxc6 $5 $146 {[%csl Gc6] This is a very crazy option, to just play with a piece down.} Bxe3+ 19. Kh1 Bb6 20. f5 $1 $11 {[%csl Re8] It is a draw in the end however.}) 18... Bxe3+ 19. Qxe3 Qxc2 $1 {Black goes all-in.} (19... O-O 20. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gb3,Rc6,Rc7,Rd7,Re4][%cal Gb1a1,Ga1a7] White has a good knight vs bad bishop scenario, Black is 2 pawns up, but it's irelevant.}) 20. f5 O-O 21. f6 {[%csl Rg8] This is however is very scary if you don't have an engine nearby telling you the moves:} gxf6 $1 22. Rbd1 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g8] Black's defence.} 23. Rd2 Qc4 24. Rfd1 {There are a lot of alternatives, but this is testing.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Bb8] Strong move.} 25. Na5 Qb5 26. Qf4 $11 {[%cal Gf4f6] And White can repeat.} Qxe5 $2 27. Qxe5 fxe5 28. Rxd7 $18 {[%csl Ga5] Despite Black having 4 pawns, White should convert with the extra piece.}) (12... O-O {Second most common move, but White gets very easy and standard play:} 13. Nd2 {We want to get rid of the knight.} f6 $1 {Rare, but strong.} (13... Nxd2 {Most played, but White achieves the goal of this line:} 14. Qxd2 f6 15. Rae1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3] Same spirit of the position, White has a positional advantage.} fxe5 16. fxe5 Rxf1+ 17. Rxf1 Qe7 18. e6 $1 {[%csl Be6] Instructive point.} Bxd4 19. Bxd4 Bxe6 20. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gc3,Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Re6] Despite being up a pawn, Black is nowhere near equalizing.}) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qe2 {[%cal Ga1d1] White however still, has a very risk free pleasant position:} Bg4 $1 {To stop Rd1.} 16. Qf2 Qd7 17. Nb3 $14 {Small advantage.}) (12... Qe7 $2 {This is as not mpressive, the queen is not doing much here.} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Re4] To trade on e4.} Nxd2 14. Qxd2 O-O 15. Nb3 {White achieves a dream position.} Bb6 16. Rae1 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Rb6,Rc5,Gd2,Rd4,Rd7,Ge3][%cal Gd2c3,Ge3c5,Ga2a4,Ga4a5] Strategically winning for us.}) 13. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Re4][%cal Gd2e4] Usual good move.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Re8] Black's best reaction, to get rid of the holes on the dark squares.} (13... Nxd2 14. Qxd2 c5 {This is the main line, that we check from another move order.} (14... O-O 15. Nb3 {see under 12...0-0.}) 15. Nf3 {see under 13...c5.}) 14. N4f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 d4 $1 {The most logical.} (15... Bc6 $6 16. c3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rd5d4] White can stop d4, and c5 will be a target, that's why Black should hurry.}) 16. Bf2 Bc6 {The most played move, but also here, White has a large choice to be slightly better:} (16... O-O {was played in 100 games, but White has a lot of good options:} 17. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5] Critical, typical idea.} (17. c4 $5 $132 {[%csl Rc5,Rd4][%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3,Gb2b3,Gh2h3] This is a very positional move, trying to slowly maneuver against Black's structure.}) 17... a5 {[%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rc5,Rc7] The bishop on b6 is more like a pawn.} 18. Bh4 Qe8 19. h3 {[%cal Gg1h2,Gg2g4] This is the concrete plan.} Be6 20. Ra3 $14 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ga3g3] White is of course, at least slightly better.}) 17. a4 $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5] I prefer the usual plan, to provoke a5.} a5 18. b3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gf2h4,Gf3d2] White needs a few moves to positionally dominate.} Bxf3 {The best.} (18... Qd5 {runs into:} 19. c4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rd5] Instructive way to reach a big advantage.}) 19. gxf3 {[%csl Rb6] However, Black is stuck with a big pawn on b6.} Qd5 20. Qd3 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga1e1,Ge1e4,Gf2h4] Engine is not so pessimistic with Black's position, but in every world I will choose White, with a risk free position, and where White can slowly improve and make use of the kingside majority.} *

